></li>\n<li><em>protensive</em></li>\n<li><em>propaedeutic</em></li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>The main clause declares that hand washing is primarily a measure. However, preceding the declaration is a condition or constraint expressed in an introductory phrase, \"a hospital setting\". This phrase sets the contextual field within which the main clause is to be understood. if you generalize from your knowledge, it would seem that any measure promoted in a hospital should result in good health. Only one of the answers would result in this. That is choice (a) in which&nbsp;<em>prophylactic&nbsp;</em>means \"prevents disease\".</strong></p>','',20,247),(633,'2016-11-02 05:03:25','2016-12-27 09:05:23','<p>The second strategy is to attend to sets, whether a set of synonyms or antonyms or special word groups. Try this at the following question:</p>\n<p><em>Even when a ____________ mother was made available to the infant chimpanzee, the infant detected the __________ and reacted with high anxiety.</em></p>\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: lower-alpha;\">\n<li><em>hedonistic .... contrivance</em></li>\n<li><em>vagrant .... apostasy</em></li>\n<li><em>veteran .... ruse</em></li>\n<li><em>pretender .... interference</em></li>\n</ol>','',20,247),(634,'2016-11-02 06:51:36','2016-12-27 09:05:23','<p>option b? correct</p>\n<p>because what ever load that will balance either side as well as,may it cat like cantilever beam on it</p>','',50,251),(635,'2016-11-02 06:52:45','2016-12-27 09:05:23','<p>option c correct</p>\n<p>because L&lt;4l</p>\n<p>so no weare at the beam</p>','',50,250),(636,'2016-11-02 07:50:29','2016-12-27 09:05:23','<p>Can you &nbsp;write the formula for buckling load for a column? And also tell which is the term in that equation that represents the resistance to bending/ rotation about an axis?&nbsp;</p>','',2,251),(637,'2016-11-02 09:22:55','2016-12-27 09:05:23','<p>Answer&nbsp;d</p>','',118,252),(641,'2016-11-02 09:30:04','2016-12-27 09:05:23','C.because convection happens in two ways for hollow sphere . ','',73,252),(642,'2016-11-02 09:34:11','2016-12-27 09:05:23','<p>Can u state a valid reason and proof supporting your answer.&nbsp;</p>','',2,252),(643,'2016-11-02 09:34:33','2016-12-27 09:05:23','<p>Abrar you are correct on this.&nbsp;</p>','',2,252),(644,'2016-11-02 10:04:07','2016-12-27 09:05:23','<p>Sir time constant for hollow sphere is Greater then time constant for solid sphere.&nbsp;</p>','',48,252),(645,'2016-11-02 13:16:19','2016-12-27 09:05:23','<p>b</p>','',151,251),(648,'2016-11-03 03:02:37','2016-12-27 09:05:23','<p>The load carrying capacity of a column is governed by its Moment of Inertia (I). Here in this question, the cross section details are not given. So as a best guess, we have to visualize which section shape will provide maximum resistance to bending, i.e. maximum MOI.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>As per the shapes given option (a) will have the maximum MOI for a given load in comparison to all the other shapes.&nbsp;</p>','',2,251),(649,'2016-11-03 06:38:46','2016-12-27 09:05:23','<p><img src=\"https://static.mindvis.in/static/geekvis/znzmhaitxcghbjsdae.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"1872\" height=\"3328\" /></p>','',80,253),(650,'2016-11-04 13:06:02','2016-12-27 09:05:23','<p>b) mass also has to be unit</p>','',48,154),(655,'2016-11-09 07:39:38','2016-12-27 09:05:23','','',2,253),(656,'2016-11-09 14:03:11','2016-12-27 09:05:23','<p>Sir what will be the correct explanation for the question</p>','',62,252),(657,'2016-11-09 14:04:31','2016-12-27 09:05:23','<p>Sir how to guess the MOI in a fast and accurate way for the given figures</p>','',62,251),(658,'2016-11-12 02:29:13','2016-12-27 09:05:24','<div class=\"page\" title=\"Page 1\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n<p>linear programming problems come in pairs. That is, if you have one linear programming problem, then there is automatically another one, derived from the same data. The starting LP, i.e. something of the sort, &nbsp;</p>\n<p>max cx,</p>\n<p>where x is subject to&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=Ax%20%5Cleq%20b\" alt=\"\" /></p>\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=x%20%5Cgeq%200\" alt=\"\" /></p>\n<p>The above LP form is called primal.&nbsp;</p>\n<div class=\"page\" title=\"Page 1\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n<p>Assume that there are n variables (components of x) and m constraints. That means that c is n&minus;dimensional, b is m&minus;dimensional, and A is a matrix with m rows and n columns. The data of the problem are b, c, and A. Using the same information, we can write down a new LP. This one has n constraints and m variables. The new problem, called the Dual has the form:</p>\n<p>min yb</p>\n<p>where y is subject to&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=yA%20%5Cgeq%20c\" alt=\"\" /></p>\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=y%20%5Cgeq%200\" alt=\"\" /></p>\n<div class=\"page\" title=\"Page 1\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n<p>You get the dual by &ldquo;switching around&rdquo; the parts of the Primal. The ob- jective switches from max to min. The constraints switch from &le; to &ge;. The number of constraints changes from m to n. The number of variables changes from n to m. The objective function coefficients switch roles with the right-hand side constants.&nbsp;</p>\n<div class=\"page\" title=\"Page 1\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n<p>The Primal and the Dual are not just two linear programming problems formed using the same data. They are intimately related. Knowing something about one problem tells you something about the other. The mathe- matical relationship is described in what is called the Duality Theorem of Linear Programming.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>','',2,265),(660,'2016-11-12 02:41:54','2016-12-27 09:05:24','<p>The Duality theorem:</p>\n<p>Statement:</p>\n<div class=\"page\" title=\"Page 3\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n<p><strong>Theorem 1:</strong> If problem (P) has a solution x&lowast;, then problem (D) also has a solution (call it y&lowast;). Furthermore, the values of the problems are equal: c &middot; x&lowast; = b &middot; y&lowast;. If problem (P) is unbounded, then problem (D) is not feasible.</p>\n<p>Similarly, if problem (D) has a solution y&lowast;, then problem (P) also has a solution (call it x&lowast;). Furthermore, the values of the problems are equal: c &middot; x&lowast; = b &middot; y&lowast;. If problem (D) is unbounded, then problem (P) is not feasible.</p>\n<p><strong>Theorem 2:&nbsp;</strong>Assume problem (P) has a solution x&lowast; and problem (D) has a solution y&lowast;.</p>\n<div class=\"page\" title=\"Page 7\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n<p>1. If x&lowast;j &gt; 0, then the jth constraint in (D) is binding.<br /> 2. If the jth constraint in (D) is not binding, then x&lowast;j = 0. 3. If yi&lowast; &gt; 0, then the ith constraint in (P) is binding.<br /> 4. If the ith constraint in (P) is not binding, then yi&lowast; = 0.&nbsp;</p>\n<div class=\"page\" title=\"Page 7\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n<p>The theorem identifies a relationship between variables in one problem and associated constraints in the other problem. Specifically, it says that if a variable is positive, then the associated dual constraint must be binding. It also says that if a constraint fails to bind, then the associated variable must be zero. The statement really is about &ldquo;complementary slackness&rdquo; in the sense that it asserts that there cannot be slack in both a constraint and the associated dual variable. It is extremely important to note that the result says that you cannot have slack in two associate places at the same time (primal variable, dual constraint) or (primal constraint, dual variable). So: it is possible for a primal constraint to be binding while the associated dual variable is equal to zero (that is, no slack in two places), but it is not possible for the primal constraint to have slack (to be non-binding) and the associated dual variable be positive.&nbsp;</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>','',2,265),(676,'2016-11-13 05:24:10','2016-12-27 09:05:24','<p>We have to write equilibrium eqns for x,y and z direction.facing problem in finding the components of forces in each direction</p>','',62,268),(677,'2016-11-13 05:34:31','2016-12-27 09:05:24','<p>Would love to see a solution for it.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','',2,268),(678,'2016-11-13 06:10:51','2016-12-27 09:05:24','<p>33 KN is the max force that can be applied</p>\n<p>The presence of a hole decreases the strength of the plate by a factor which is called the stress conc factor.In this case the factor is 3 so the max stress that can be applied here reduces by a factor of 3. Sir?</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','',62,269),(679,'2016-11-13 06:14:50','2016-12-27 09:05:24','<p>How much is the stress concentration factor for this geometry? Use the pic attached to find the stress concentration factor.</p>','',2,269),(680,'2016-11-13 06:19:40','2016-12-27 09:05:24','<p>The maximum load without the hole in it must be:</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=220%20%5Ctimes%206%20%5Ctimes%2075%20%3D%2099%20kN\" alt=\"\" /></p>\n<p>From where did you get 33 kN?</p>','',2,269),(681,'2016-11-13 06:20:41','2016-12-27 09:05:24','<p>Acc to the figure it\'s around 2.4 ?</p>','',62,269),(682,'2016-11-13 06:24:16','2016-12-27 09:05:24','<p>Sir while calculating force aren\'t we suppose to consider the effect of hole !?&nbsp;</p>','',62,269),(683,'2016-11-13 06:26:23','2016-12-27 09:05:24'