ue of A. We know that the determinant of A is product of eigen value so determinant of A is zero.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>So A is a singular matrix, so it cannot be invertible.</p>','',2,653),(2363,'2017-07-06 08:47:16','2017-07-06 08:47:16','<p>sol 5) let A be mxn matrix with linearly independent columns, then rank (A) =n .&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>let&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=c%3DA%5E%7BT%7DA\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;then,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=rank(c)%3Drank(A%5E%7BT%7DA)%3Dn\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>this implies that&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=A%5E%7BT%7DA\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;is invertible, which is the fundamental theorem of invertible matrices.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=AA%5E%7BT%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;need not be invertible. For example,</p>\r\n<p>let A = [1 0] is a (2x1) matrix and A<sup>T</sup> = [1 0] is a (1x2) matrix.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>rank (A) = 1, and&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=AA%5E%7BT%7D%3D%5Cbegin%7Bbmatrix%7D%201%20%26%200%5C%5C%20%200%20%26%200%20%5Cend%7Bbmatrix%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;which means that&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=AA%5E%7BT%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;will not be invertible.&nbsp;</p>','',2,653),(2364,'2017-07-06 08:54:45','2017-07-06 08:54:45','<p>sol 6</p>','/uploads/images/comment-qngWyRFL.jpg',2,653),(2365,'2017-07-06 08:57:44','2017-07-06 08:57:44','<p>Sol 7) Let A and B are skew symmetric nxn matrices so by definition.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=A%5E%7BT%7D%3D-A\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;and&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=B%5E%7BT%7D%3D-B\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>Now&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=(A%2BB)%5E%7BT%7D%3DA%5E%7BT%7D%2BB%5E%7BT%7D\" alt=\"\" /><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=-A-B%3D-(A%2BB)\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>So this means that A+B is also skew symmetric.</p>','',2,653),(2366,'2017-07-06 09:12:49','2017-07-06 09:12:49','<p>Sol 8) the squre matrix A is invertible if and only if&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=det(A)%20%5Cneq%200\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>Consider an invertible matrix AB the product of two square matrices A and B. As the matrix AB is invertible, so&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=det(AB)%5Cneq%200\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>Consider the property of the determinant,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=det(AB)%3Ddet(A).det(B)\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>from the above argument it is evident,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=det(A).det(B)%20%5Cneq%200\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;which means&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=det(A)%20%5Cneq%200\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;and&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=det(B)%20%5Cneq%200\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>so by the definition of an invertible matrix, it is seen that A and B are also invertible.</p>','',2,653),(2367,'2017-07-06 10:29:33','2017-07-06 10:29:33','Q1, 2','/uploads/images/comment-a8mXcxX0.jpg',347,653),(2370,'2017-07-07 09:59:51','2017-07-07 09:59:51','Q1. 442.38N','',355,654),(2371,'2017-07-07 10:08:39','2017-07-07 10:08:39','q1,2,3,4','/uploads/images/comment-qixrH