e-prep-course\" target=\"_blank\">UPSC ESE 2017</a>.</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://mindvis.in/articles/reliability-in-engineering-for-upsc-ese-mechanical-engineering-2017\" target=\"_blank\">https://mindvis.in/articles/reliability-in-engineering-for-upsc-ese-mechanical-engineering-2017</a></p>',0,'',163,5,2,7,'','',1),(65,'2016-08-09 08:14:28','2017-07-09 23:43:17','Notes on Steady State Conduction in Multiple Dimensions for GATE Mechanical Engineering','article','65','','<p>During our preparation for <a href=\"https://mindvis.in/courses/gate-2017-mechanical-engineering\" target=\"_blank\">GATE Mechanical Engineering</a>, we have all studied One Dimensional Steady State Heat Conduction. In this article, we have created short notes useful for <a href=\"https://mindvis.in/courses/gate-2017-mechanical-engineering\" target=\"_blank\">GATE Mechanical Engineering </a>aspirants, on the topic of Steady State Heat Conduction in Multiple Dimensions.</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://mindvis.in/articles/notes-on-steady-state-conduction-in-multiple-dimensions-for-gate-mechanical-engi\" target=\"_blank\">https://mindvis.in/articles/notes-on-steady-state-conduction-in-multiple-dimensions-for-gate-mechanical-engi</a></p>',0,'',126,5,2,4,'','',1),(109,'2016-08-11 09:25:09','2017-07-09 22:57:16','Question on Adiabatic Throttling of ideal gas.','question','109','','<p>When an ideal gas with constant specific heats is throttled adiabatically with negligible changes in kinetic and potential changes.</p>\n<p>a. delta h=0, delta T=0 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;b. delta h&gt;0, delta T=0</p>\n<p>c. delta h=&gt;0, delta S&gt;0 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;d. delta h=0, delta S&gt;0</p>',0,'',127,5,2,3,'','',1),(122,'2016-08-20 00:20:13','2017-07-05 11:53:43','mathematics','question','mathematics','','<p>solve it</p>\n<p>x^2.(d^2y/dx^2)+x(dx/dy)-4y=0</p>\n<p>boundary condition y(0)=0,y(1)=1</p>\n<p>a)x^2</p>\n<p>b)sin(pi.x/2)</p>\n<p>c)e^x.sin(pi/2x)</p>\n<p>d)e^-x.sin(pi.x/2)</p>',0,'',96,5,50,2,'','',1),(123,'2016-08-20 17:56:50','2017-07-02 15:27:35','Question on calculation of Skin Temperature using concepts of Heat Transfer.','question','question-on-calculation-of-skin-temperature-using-concepts-of-heat-transfer','','<div class=\"page\" title=\"Page 2\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n<p>Humans are able to control their heat production rate and heat loss rate to maintain a nearly constant core temperature of <img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=T_%7Bc%7D%3D37%5E%7Bo%7DC\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;under a wide range of environmental conditions. This process is called thermoregulation. From the perspective of calculating heat transfer between a human body and its surroundings, we focus on a layer of skin and fat, with its outer surface exposed to the environment and its inner surface at a temperature slightly less than the core temperature, <img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=T_%7Bi%7D%3D308K\" alt=\"\" />. Consider a person with a skin/fat layer of thickness L = 3 mm and effective thermal conductivity k = 0.3 W/mK. The person has a surface area <img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=A%3D1.8%20m%5E%7B2%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;and is dressed in a bathing suit. The emissivity of the skin is ',0,'',117,5,2,4,'','',1),(124,'2016-08-23 12:05:54','2017-07-05 13:02:22','Area of Irreversible process under a T-S diagram','question','area-of-irreversible-process-under-a-t-s-diagram','','<p>What does the area under a T-S diagram for an irreversible process represent?</p>',0,'',100,5,2,3,'','',1),(125,'2016-08-24 06:34:54','2017-07-09 21:15:59','Question on Thermal Stresses in materials.','question','question-on-thermal-stresses-in-materials','','<p>The rigid bar CDE is attached to a pin support at E and rests on the 30 mm diameter brass cylinder BD. A 22 mm diameter steel rod AC passes through a hole in the bar and is secured by a nut which is snugly fitted when the temperature of the entire assembly is 20<sup>o</sup>C. The temperature of the brass cylinder is then raised to 50<sup>o</sup>C while the steel rod remains at 20<sup>o</sup>C. Assuming that no stresses were present before the temperature change, determine the stress in the cylinder.</p>\n<p>Rod AC (steel): E = 200 GPa,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Calpha%20%3D%2011.7%20%5Ctimes%2010%5E%7B-6%7D%20%2F%5E%7Bo%7DC\" alt=\"\" /></p>\n<p>Rod BD (brass): E = 105 GPa,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Calpha%20%3D%2020.9%20%5Ctimes%2010%5E%7B-6%7D%20%2F%5E%7Bo%7DC\" alt=\"\" /></p>\n<p><img src=\"static/uploads/images/jueazzsohtmnsqsw.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"410\" height=\"381\" /></p>',0,'',83,5,2,6,'','',1),(128,'2016-08-24 10:27:49','2017-07-05 14:24:45','Question on Steady State Heat Conduction','question','question-on-steady-state-heat-conduction','','<p>A current of 200 A is passed through a stainless-steel wire [<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=k%3D19W%2Fm%5E%7Bo%7DC\" alt=\"\" />] 3 mm in diameter.&nbsp;The resistivity of the steel may be taken as 70 <em>&mu;<img title=\"\\Omega\" src=\"https://latex.codecogs.com/gif.latex?\\Omega\" alt=\"\" /> </em>&middot; cm, and the length of the wire is 1 m. The&nbsp;wire is submerged in a liquid at <img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=110%5E%7Bo%7DC\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;and experiences a convection heat-transfer coefficient of&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=4kW%2Fm%5E%7B2%7DC\" alt=\"\" />. Calculate the center temperature of the wire.</p>',0,'',97,5,2,4,'','',1),(129,'2016-08-31 09:47:41','2017-07-07 18:56:18','general engineering question(SOM)','question','general-engineering-questionsom','','<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>When a nut is tightened by placing a washer below it,the bolt will subjected to</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">a)Compression</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">b)Tension</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">c)Shear</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">d)Compression&amp;Shear</p>',0,'',109,5,50,2,'','',1),(130,'2016-08-31 10:51:29','2017-07-01 14:30:04','A question very often asked on tightening of nuts and bolts while discussing the topic of fasteners.','question','a-question-very-often-asked-on-tightening-of-nuts-and-bolts-while-discussing-the','','<p><span class=\"title\">While making a joint whether we should tighten the Nut or the Bolt?</span></p>\n<p><span class=\"title\"><img src=\"static/uploads/images/lkprbjnygqqgtkzc.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"356\" height=\"356\" /></span></p>',0,'',95,5,2,9,'','',1),(131,'2016-09-02 09:46:04','2017-07-05 12:37:17','Finding slopes of PV diagrams','question','finding-slopes-of-pv-diagrams','','<p>How is slope of Adiabatic Process greater than slope of an Isothermal process?</p>',0,'',130,5,2,3,'','',1),(132,'2016-09-05 04:18:22','2017-07-05 11:53:53','thermodynomics','question','thermodynomics','','<p><strong>Plz</strong>&nbsp;define<strong> 3rd law</strong> of TDjQuery224005631087240888477_1473851940711</p>\n<p>also define control pressure????</p>',0,'',128,5,50,2,'','',1),(133,'2016-09-09 16:05:49','2017-07-09 03:52:08','engineering mathematics','question','engineering-mathematics','','<p>sir how can calculated the no of linearly indipendent value in a given matrix</p>\n<p>supose u can take a matrix</p>\n<p><strong><img title=\"\\begin{bmatrix} 1 &amp;2 \\\\ 0 &amp; 2\\end{bmatrix}\" src=\"https://latex.codecogs.com/gif.latex?\\begin{bmatrix}&amp;space;1&amp;space;&amp;2&amp;space;\\\\&amp;space;0&amp;space;&amp;&amp;space;2\\end{bmatrix}\" alt=\"\" width=\"68\" height=\"68\" /></stro