6-12-30 08:21:11','2017-07-05 12:41:57','SOLVE THIS QUESTION ON MOBILITY','question','solve-this-question-on-mobility','/uploads/images/solve-this-question-on-mobility-09NRX33Q.PNG','<p>WHAT IS THE MOBILITY OF MECHANISM ?</p>',0,'',162,5,186,23,'','',1),(528,'2016-12-30 11:26:00','2017-07-05 11:56:17','EDM','question','edm','/uploads/images/edm-18aESYwh.PNG','<p>Share solution</p>',0,'',150,5,174,9,'','',1),(529,'2016-12-31 02:16:56','2017-07-05 12:39:18','Question on Orthogonal cutting','question','question-on-orthogonal-cutting','','<p>In an orthogonal cutting, the following data is observed:</p>\r\n<p>Uncut chip thickness = 0.35 mm</p>\r\n<p>Cut chip thickness = 0.76 mm</p>\r\n<p>Width of cut = 4 mm</p>\r\n<p>Cutting speed = 30 m/min</p>\r\n<p>Cutting force component parallel to machined surface = 1500 N</p>\r\n<p>Cutting force component normal to machined surface = 300 N</p>\r\n<p>Rake angle of tool = 15 degrees</p>\r\n<p>Determine the power required, shear plane angle and the average coefficient of friction on the tool rake face.</p>',0,'',108,5,2,9,'gate mechanical practice questions, free practice questions for gate','',1),(530,'2016-12-31 02:20:30','2017-07-02 11:10:57','Question on machining process in Manufacturing engineering','question','question-on-machining-process-in-manufacturing-engineering','','<p>In a turning operation, life of the cutting tool has been observed to vary with changes in spindle speed and feed as follows:</p>\r\n<table style=\"width: 343px; height: 66px;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 89px;\">Spindle speed in rpm</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 89px;\">80</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 90px;\">106</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 49px;\">125</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 89px;\">feed (mm/rev)</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 89px;\">0.35</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 90px;\">0.30</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 49px;\">0.25</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 89px;\">Tool life (min)</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 89px;\">110</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 90px;\">60</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 49px;\">54</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>determine the tool life when the operation is performed at 130 rpm and a feed of 0.22 mm/rev</p>',0,'',103,5,2,9,'gate mechanical practice questions, free practice questions for gate','',0),(531,'2016-12-31 02:24:20','2017-07-04 19:54:33','Question on milling operation in machining processes','question','question-on-milling-operation-in-machining-processes','','<p>Following data relate to a peripheral milling operation:</p>\r\n<p>Dia of the milling cutter = 100 mm</p>\r\n<p>Cutter speed = 500 rpm</p>\r\n<p>Width of the cutter = 100 mm</p>\r\n<p>Depth of the cut = 5 mm</p>\r\n<p>Table speed = 100 mm/min</p>\r\n<p>Helix angle of teeth = 45 degrees</p>\r\n<p>Length of workpiece = 500 mm</p>\r\n<p>Width of workpiece = 50 mm</p>\r\n<p>No. of teeth = 8</p>\r\n<p>Calculate the cutting speed, maximum effective uncut chip thickness, plane area of cut, MRR and machining time. </p>',0,'',178,5,2,9,'gate mechanical practice questions, free practice questions for gate','',1),(532,'2016-12-31 02:28:01','2017-07-04 06:46:29','Question on Orthogonal cutting in machining processes','question','question-on-orthogonal-cutting-in-machining-processes','','<p>In an orthogonal cutting process, the following observations were made:</p>\r\n<p>Depth of cut = 0.25 mm</p>\r\n<p>Chip thickness ratio = 0.45</p>\r\n<p>Width of cut = 4 mm</p>\r\n<p>Cutting velocity = 40 m/min</p>\r\n<p>Cutting force component parallel to cutting velocity vector = 1150 N</p>\r\n<p>Cutting force component normal to cutting velocity vector = 140 N</p>\r\n<p>Rake angle of the tool = 18 degrees</p>\r\n<p>Determine resultant cutting force, power of cutting, shear plane angle, friction angle and force component parallel to shear plane.&nbsp;</p>',0,'',200,5,2,9,'gate mechanical practice questions, free practice questions for gate','',1),(533,'2016-12-31 04:34:54','2017-07-08 02:39:50','Question on Work study in industrial engineering','question','question-on-work-study-in-industrial-engineering','','<p>Work sampling studies are conducted to find the utilization of a machine. Out of 200 observations made, only 40 observations indicated the machine to be idle. Find the number of observations to be made in order to satisfy 95% confidence to state the utilization of machine with expected accuracy 0f +\\- 5%.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>',0,'',123,5,2,13,'free gate questions on gate mechanical, gate mechanical practice questions, gate mechanical engineering free questions, gate 2019, gate 2018, gate 2018 free practice questions','',1),(534,'2016-12-31 13:02:10','2017-07-09 21:16:11','Practice questions on strength of materials','question','practice-questions-on-strength-of-materials','','<p>Q1) For most brittle materials, the ultimate strength&nbsp;in compression is much larger than the ultimate strength in tension. That is simply due to</p>\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: lower-alpha;\">\r\n<li>presence of flaws, microscopic cracks or flaws</li>\r\n<li>necking in tension</li>\r\n<li>severity of tensile stress as compared to compressive stress</li>\r\n<li>non-linearity of stress-strain diagram</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>Q2) A SSB of rectangular section 4 cm by 6 cm carries a mid-span concentrated load such that the 6 cm side lies parallel to line of action of loading; deflection under the load is&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cdelta\" alt=\"\" />. If the beam is now supported with the 4 cm side parallel to the line of action of loading, the deflection under the load will be</p>\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: lower-alpha;\">\r\n<li><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=0.44%20%5Cdelta\" alt=\"\" /></li>\r\n<li><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=0.67%20%5Cdelta\" alt=\"\" /></li>\r\n<li><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=1.5%20%5Cdelta\" alt=\"\" /></li>\r\n<li><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=2.25%20%5Cdelta\" alt=\"\" /></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>Q3) A horizontal beam with a&nbsp;square cross section is simply supported with sides of the square horizontal and vertical and carries a distributed loading that produces maximum bending stress&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Csigma\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;in the beam. When the beam is placed with one of the diagonals horizontal the maximum bending stress will be</p>\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: lower-alpha;\">\r\n<li><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B%5Csqrt%7B2%7D%7D%20%5Csigma\" alt=\"\" /></li>\r\n<li><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Csigma\" alt=\"\" /></li>\r\n<li><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Csqrt%20%7B2%7D%20%5Csigma\" alt=\"\" /></li>\r\n<li><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=2%20%5Csigma\" alt=\"\" /></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>Q4) If failure in shear along&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=45%5E%7Bo%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;planes is to be avoided then a material subjected to uniaxial tension should have its shear strength equal to at least</p>\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: lower-alpha;\">\r\n<li>tensile strength</li>\r\n<li>compressive strength</li>\r\n<li>half the difference between the tensile and compressive strengths</li>\r\n<li>half the tensile strength</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>Q5) A cantilever beam having length 5 m length is so loaded that it develops a shearing force of 20T and a bending moment of 20T-m at a section 2m from the free end. Maximum shearing force and maximum bending moment developed in the beam under this load, are respectively 50T and 125T-m. The load on the beam is</p>\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: lower-alpha;\">\r\n<li>25T concentrated load at free end</li>\r\n<li>20T concentrated load at free end</li>\r\n<li>5T concentrated load at free end and 2T/m load over entire length</li>\r\n<li>10T/m UDL over entire length</li>\r\n</ol>',0,'',215,5,2,6,'gate practice questions, gate mechanical practice questions, free gate mechanical questions bank, gate 2018 question bank for mechanical engineering, gate mechanical engineering practice questions','',1),(535,'2016-12-31 20:44:39','2017-07-09 12:31:43','Try this','question','try-this','/uploads/images/try-this-OmNMa9tH.png','<p>Find it.</p>',0,'',146,5,186,2,'','',1),(536,'2017-01-02 01:49:19','2017-07-05 12:32:52','Question on heat convection','question','question-on-heat-convection','','<p>Ait at 300 K and 1 atm flows over a flat plate at a speed of 2 m/s. The plate is heated uniformly at 333 K throughout. Calculate the rate of heat transfer from the (a) first 250 mm of plate, and (b) first 400 mm of plate.</p>',0,'',152,5,2,4,'gate mechanical practice questions, free practice questions for gate','',1),(537,'2017-01-02 01:53:57','2017-07-06 21:07:13','Question on heat exchanger','question','question-on-heat-exchanger','','<p>A surface condenser is to be designed to condense per hour 40 ton of dry saturated steam of 0.12 atm absolute on the shell side with cooling water. The inlet temperature of water is&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=20%5E%7Bo%7DC\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;and flows through tubes of inside diameter 2 cm and outside diameter 2.4 cm. The film coefficients on the steam side and water side being 5000 and 4200&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=W%2Fcm%5E%7B2%7D.%5E%7Bo%7DC\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;respectively. If the cooling water outlet temperature is&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=25%5E%7Bo%7DC\" alt=\"\" />, calculate the surface area of the tubes required. Thermal conductivity of tube material is&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=52%20W%2Fm%5E%7Bo%7DC\" alt=\"\" />.</p>',0,'',131,5,2,4,'gate mechanical practice questions, free practice questions for gate','',1),(538,'2017-01-02 01:56:45','2017-07-05 12:48:42','Question on heat transfer','question','question-on-heat-transfer-LU3dxD7p','','<p>An infinitely long plate of thickness 22 mm is heated to a uniform temperature of <img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&chl=150%5E%7Bo%7DC\" alt=\"\" /> and then exposed to the ambient air at <img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&chl=20%5E%7Bo%7DC\" alt=\"\" />. The thermal conductivity and thermal diffusivity of the plate material being 0.175 <img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&chl=W%2Fm.%5E%7Bo%7DC\" alt=\"\" /> and <img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&chl=0.666%20%5Ctimes%2010%5E%7B-7%7D%20m%5E%7B2%7D%2Fs\" alt=\"\" /> respectively.</p>\r\n\r\nCalculate the temperatures at central section and at surface of the plate in a time interval of 25 min after cooling down of plate was started. The local coefficient of heat transfer from the plate to the ambient air is 59.33 W/m2C.',0,'',152,5,2,4,'gate mechanical practice questions, free practice questions for gate','',1),(539,'2017-01-02 02:00:24','2017-07-10 07:08:31','Question on heat exchangers in heat transfer','question','question-on-heat-exchangers-in-heat-transfer','','<p>A counterflow heat exchanger is to heat air entering at&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=400%5E%7Bo%7DC%20\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;with a flow rate of 6 kg/s by the exhaust gas entering at&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=800%5E%7Bo%7DC\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;with a flow rate of 4 kg/s. The overall heat transfer coefficient is&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=100%20W%2Fm%5E%7B2%7DK\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;and the outlet temperature of air is&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=551.5%5E%7Bo%7DC\" alt=\"\" />. Specific heat at constant pressure for both air and exhaust gas can be taken as 1100 J/kgK. Calculate the heat transfer area needed and the number of transfer units.</p>',0,'',158,5,2,4,'gate mechanical practice questions, free practice questions for gate','',1),(540,'2017-01-02 06:33:32','2017-07-05 13:04:22','Question on heat exchangers in Heat transfer theory','question','question-on-heat-exchangers-in-heat-transfer-theory','','<p>In a certain double pipe heat exchanger, hot water flows at a rate of 50,000 kg.h and gets cooled from 95 degrees to 65 degrees celsius. At the same time, 50,000 kg/h of cooling water at 30 degrees celsius enters the heat exchanger. The flow conditions are such that the overall heat transfer coefficient remains constant at 2270 W/m2K. Determine the heat transfer area required and the effectiveness assuming the two streams are in parallel flow. Assume for both streams,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=c_%7Bp%7D%3D4.2kJ%2FkgK\" alt=\"\" /></p>',0,'',113,5,2,4,'gate practice questions, gate mechanical practice questions, free gate mechanical questions bank, gate 2018 question bank for mechanical engineering, gate mechanical engineering practice questions','',1),(541,'2017-01-02 06:37:38','2017-07-05 23:39:14','A good question for practice on heat exchangers from heat transfer','question','a-good-question-for-practice-on-heat-exchangers-from-heat-transfer','','<p>In the design of heat exchanger for aircraft application, the maximum wall temperature in steady state is not to exceed 800K. For the conditions tabulated below, determine the maximum permissible unit thermal resistance per square metre of the metal wall between hot gas on the one side and cold gas on the other.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Hot gas temperature&nbsp;= 1300K</p>\r\n<p>Unit surface conductance on hot side = 200 W/m2K</p>\r\n<p>Unit surface conductance on cold side = 400 W/m2K</p>\r\n<p>Coolant temperature = 300 K</p>',0,'',135,5,2,4,'gate practice questions, gate mechanical practice questions, free gate mechanical questions bank, gate 2018 question bank for mechanical engineering, gate mechanical engineering practice questions','',1),(542,'2017-01-03 07:17:42','2017-07-07 23:30:13','Try this from lapace transforms','question','try-this-from-lapace-transforms','/uploads/images/try-this-from-lapace-transforms-i0YsLB8A.jpg','<p>Solve it.</p>',0,'',180,5,186,2,'','',1),(543,'2017-01-03 07:49:55','2017-07-05 12:44:47','Solve this question on IC Engines ','question','solve-this-question-on-ic-engines','','<p>A hydrocarbon fuel when burned with air gave the following Orsat analyis:</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=CO_%7B2%7D%3D11.94%25\" alt=\"\" />,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=O_%7B2%7D%3D2.26%25\" alt=\"\" />,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=CO%3D0.41%25\" alt=\"\" />,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=N_%7B2%7D%3D85.39%25\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>Determine&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>(i) the air-fuel ratio on mass basis</p>\r\n<p>(ii) the percent of carbon and hydrogen in the fuel on mass basis</p>\r\n<p>(iii) percent of theoretical air supplied.</p>\r\n<p>Assume air contains 21% oxygen by volume.&nbsp;</p>',0,'',110,5,2,3,'gate 2018 practice questions, free question bank for gate mechanical engineering, gate 2019, gate practice questions, gate questions for mechanical engineering','',1),(544,'2017-01-03 07:53:42','2017-07-05 13:02:57','Practice question on multi cylinder diesel engine','question','practice-question-on-multi-cylinder-diesel-engine','','<p>A 16-cylinder diesel engine has a power output of 800 kW at 900 rpm. The engine works on the 4 stroke cycle and has a fuel consumption of 0.238 kg/kWhr. The pressure in the cylinder at the beginning of injection is 32.4 bar and the maximum cylinder pressure is 55 bar. The injector is set at 214 bar and maximum pressure at the injector is around 600 bar. The coefficient of discharge for the injector is 0.6. The specific gravity of the fuel is 0.86. Calculate the orifice area required per injector, if the injection takes place over 10 degree crank angle.&nbsp;</p>',0,'',117,5,2,3,'gate 2018 practice questions, free question bank for gate mechanical engineering, gate 2019, gate practice questions, gate questions for mechanical engineering','',1),(545,'2017-01-03 07:58:10','2017-07-04 13:28:55','Practice question on power calculations for IC Engines','question','practice-question-on-power-calculations-for-ic-engines','','<p>A 6 cylinder, 4 stroke SI engine of 10 cm x 12 cm (bore x stroke) with a compression ratio of 6 is tested at 4800 rpm on a dynamometer of arm 55 cm. During a 0 minutes test, the dynamometer reads 45 kg and the engine consumed 5 kg of petrol of CV = 45 MJ/kg. The carburettor receives the air at&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=29%5E%7Bo%7DC\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;and 1 bar at the rate of 10 kg/min. Calculate,</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>the brake power</li>\r\n<li>the brake m.e.p</li>\r\n<li>the brake sfc</li>\r\n<li>the brake specific air consumption</li>\r\n<li>the brake thermal efficiency, and&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li>the air-fuel ratio</li>\r\n</ol>',0,'',176,5,2,3,'gate 2018 practice questions, free question bank for gate mechanical engineering, gate 2019, gate practice questions, gate questions for mechanical engineering','',1),(546,'2017-01-04 02:44:40','2017-07-05 12:13:22','Eng Mechanics Problem','question','eng-mechanics-problem','/uploads/images/eng-mechanics-problem-JpZZx6Ex.jpeg','<p>solve 5.15 Question</p>',0,'',149,5,118,11,'','',1),(547,'2017-01-04 03:01:09','2017-07-05 12:56:47','Revision Notes - First Law of Thermodynamics','article','revision-notes-first-law-of-thermodynamics','/uploads/images/revision-notes-first-law-of-thermodynamics-qPmbQ32P.jpg','<p>The first law of thermodynamics also known as conservation of energy principle provides a sound basis for studying the relationships for studying the relationships among various forms of energy and energy interactions.</p>\r\n<p>Based on experimental observations first law of thermodynamics states that&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\"<strong>ENERGY CAN NEITHER BE CREATED NOR BE DESTROYED DURING A PROCESS,IT CAN ONLY CHANGE FORMS</strong>.\"</p>\r\n<p>Consider the following example:</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/12q-GiWtoXMR.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"219\" height=\"259\" /></p>\r\n<p>Rock at some elevation possesses some potential energy and part of this potential energy is converted into kinetic energy as rock falls. Experimental data show that decrease in potential energy (mg∆z) exactly equals the increase in kinetic energy [m(V<sub>2</sub><sup>2 </sup>&ndash;V<sub>1</sub><sup>2 </sup>)/2], when air resistance is negligible, thus confirming the conservation of energy principle for mechanical energy.</p>\r\n<p><strong>First law for any cyclic process:</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"../../uploads/images/23-EaXkWyyz.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"196\" height=\"143\" /></strong></p>\r\n<p>For any cyclic process in the closed system ,relationship between heat and work shall be as follows:</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Coint%20%5Cdelta%20q%20%3D%20%5Coint%20%5Cdelta%20W\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>Where:</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Coint%20%5Cdelta%20q\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;=&nbsp;Net heat transfer to the system</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Coint%20%5Cdelta%20W\" alt=\"\" />= Net work transfer from the system</p>\r\n<p><strong>First for non cyclic process:</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"../../uploads/images/ws-ES6o8msR.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"188\" height=\"163\" /></strong></p>\r\n<p>The change in state is accomplished by energy interactions. If we assume the system to have heat interaction ∆Q and work interaction to be ∆W then from the basic principles it can be said: <strong>Energy lost =Energy gained</strong></p>\r\n<p>As energy can neither be created nor be destroyed.</p>\r\n<p>Therefore energy balance between states 1-2 can be written as:</p>\r\n<p><strong>Q<sub>1-2 </sub>&ndash;W<sub>1-2 </sub>= U<sub>1-2</sub></strong></p>\r\n<p>Also,it can be written as</p>\r\n<p><strong>∆U=Q-W&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong>which means <em>internal energy change in a closed a system during any non cyclic process is obtained by subtracting net amount of work done by the system from the net amount of heat added to the system.</em></p>\r\n<p>There is no absolute value of internal energy of any system. Internal energy is thermodynamic property ,which means change in thermodynamic property is independent of path followed.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Total energy =Internal energy+kinetic energy+potential energy</strong>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; E&nbsp; = U+KE+PE</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;H =U+PV</p>\r\n<p>Where, H= Enthalpy</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; U=internal energy</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; P=Pressure</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; V=volume</p>\r\n<p>Heat interaction for ∆T temperature change in m mass of the substance can be given as follows</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>For isochoric conditions:Q=mC<sub>v</sub>∆T</li>\r\n<li>For isobaric conditions:Q=mC<sub>p</sub>∆T</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Where C<sub>V</sub>=specific heat at constant volume</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=C_%7Bv%7D%3D(%5Cfrac%7B%5Cpartial%20u%7D%7B%5Cpartial%20T%7D)_%7Bv%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>C<sub>P</sub> = Specific heat at constant pressure</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=C_%7Bp%7D%3D(%5Cfrac%7B%5Cpartial%20h%7D%7B%5Cpartial%20T%7D)_%7Bp%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=C_%7Bp%7D%3DC_%7Bv%7D%3DC\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;for incompressible substances</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=C_%7Bp%7D-C_%7Bv%7D%3DR\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cfrac%20%7BC_%7Bp%7D%7D%7BC_%7Bv%7D%7D%3D%5Cgamma\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>So combining the above two formulas, we get the following results.</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=C_%7Bp%7D%3D%5Cfrac%20%7B%5Cgamma%20R%7D%7B%5Cgamma%20-1%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;and&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=C_%7Bp%7D%3D%5Cfrac%20%7BR%7D%7B%5Cgamma%20-1%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p><strong>First law of thermodynamics applied to steady&nbsp; flow energy systems and Analysis of steady flow energy systems :</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"../../uploads/images/ead-PfksiGn1.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"456\" height=\"234\" /></strong></p>\r\n<p>Steady flow refers to flow in which its properties at any time remain constant with respect to time. Steady system is system whose properties are independent of time i.e any property at a point&nbsp; in system shall not change with respect to time</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/w-w-vaOVpAXF.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"511\" height=\"141\" /></p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/3vqf-6laJlrUe.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"516\" height=\"74\" /></p>\r\n<p>And from definition of enthalpy h<sub>1</sub>=u<sub>1</sub>+p<sub>1</sub>v<sub>1</sub></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;h<sub>2</sub>=u<sub>2</sub>+p<sub>2</sub>v<sub>2</sub></p>\r\n<p><sub><img src=\"../../uploads/images/eafdarw-gsJ1Jls3.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"384\" height=\"65\" /><br /></sub></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"font-size: xx-small;\">Take care of the units here.&nbsp;</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Above equation is known as steady flow energy equation(S.F.E.E).If mass flow rate at inlet and exit are same i.e. m1=m2 =m</p>\r\n<p>Then,</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/aesd-jRefD6rS.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"420\" height=\"72\" /></p>\r\n<p>Or on unit mass basis the S.F.E.E shall be</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/aqa-GqzAGRqe.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"304\" height=\"67\" /></p>\r\n<p>Where, q = Q/m, w = W/m</p>\r\n<p>Equation of continuity for steady flow system:&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Crho_%7B1%7D%20A_%7B1%7D%20V_%7B1%7D%3D%5Crho_%7B2%7D%20A_%7B2%7D%20V_%7B2%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p><strong>First Law applied to engineering systems:</strong></p>\r\n<p>a) <strong>Turbine</strong>: It is a device in which high temperature and high pressure fluid is expanded to low temperature and low pressure fluid , resulting in generation of positive work at turbine shaft. It is a work producing device.</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/qaz-fhmOktkf.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"312\" height=\"242\" /></p>\r\n<p>Assumption:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Adiabatic</li>\r\n<li>Neglecting changes in kinetic energy and potential energy</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/ae-Ur0JWmUu.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"184\" height=\"50\" /></p>\r\n<p>Q =0</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/aqsd-8DpFur4S.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"344\" height=\"26\" /></p>\r\n<p>Where m= mass flow rate ,T<sub>1</sub> is inlet temperature ,T<sub>2</sub> is outlet temperature.</p>\r\n<p>b)<strong> Compressor</strong>: Compressor is a work absorbing device used for increasing pressure of a fluid .Pressure of fluid is increased by doing work upon it which is accompanied by increase in temperature depending on gas properties.</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/wea-hKW1AJdH.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"352\" height=\"232\" /></p>\r\n<p>Assumptions</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Adiabatic</li>\r\n<li>Neglecting changes in kinetic and potential energy</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=W_%7Bc%7D%3Dm(h_%7B2%7D-h_%7B1%7D)\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>Where&nbsp; T<sub>1</sub> and T<sub>2</sub> are temperature at inlet and outlet and m is mass flow rate.</p>\r\n<p>c) <strong>Pump</strong>: A pump is used for pumping liquid or suction of liquid.</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/wqefr-31TZzZ8U.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"428\" height=\"184\" /></p>\r\n<p>Assumptions:</p>\r\n<p>1)Adiabatic</p>\r\n<p>2)change in internal energy ∆U =0</p>\r\n<p>Therefore,</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/edxa-LCXLZJ6a.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"464\" height=\"128\" /></p>\r\n<p>d) <strong>Boiler</strong>: Boiler is an engg device used for steam generation at constant pressure .Heat is supplied externally to the boiler for steam generation.</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/ssa-t78iSgZX.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"329\" height=\"149\" /></p>\r\n<p>Assumptions:</p>\r\n<p>1)W=0</p>\r\n<p>2)∆KE=0;∆PE=0</p>\r\n<p>Applying S.F.E.E we get&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=Q_%7Bboiler%7D%2Bm(h_%7B1%7D)%3Dm(h_%7B2%7D)\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=Q_%7Bboiler%7D%3Dm(h_%7B1%7D-h_%7B2%7D)%3Dmc_%7Bp%7D(T_%7B2%7D-T_%7B1%7D)\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>e)&nbsp;<strong>Condensor</strong>: Condensor is&nbsp; a device used for condensing vapour into liquid at a constant pressure.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/evvgr-ln8Fe5au.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"324\" height=\"147\" /></p>\r\n<p>Assumptions:</p>\r\n<p>1)W=0</p>\r\n<p>2)∆ KE=0;∆P.E.=0</p>\r\n<p>Heat lost by steam:&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=Q%3Dm(h_%7B1%7D-h_%7B2%7D)\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>f) <strong>Nozzle</strong>: Nozzle is an engineering device in which expansion of fluid takes place and pressure drops simultaneously.Thus in nozzle velocity of fluid increases from inlet to exit .In case of <u>subsonic</u> flow nozzle has converging cross section area in the duct where as in supersonic flow nozzle has diverging cross sectional area on the duct.</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/qazd-WtXk2BZ8.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"396\" height=\"172\" /></p>\r\n<p>Assumptions:</p>\r\n<p>1)No heat interaction with the surroundings&nbsp; Q=0</p>\r\n<p>2)No work interaction with the surroundings W=0</p>\r\n<p>3)change in potential energy =0</p>\r\n<p>Applying S.F.E.E on nozzle:</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/efrw-eg8CeyyM.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"218\" height=\"170\" /></p>\r\n<p>In case velocity to nozzle inlet is very small C<sub>1</sub> may be neglected&nbsp; and velocity at nozzle at nozzle exit will be as follows:</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/ecr-L5Wp7H3X.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"160\" height=\"39\" /></p>\r\n<p>g)<strong>Throttling</strong>: Throttling refers to passage of a fluid through a restricted opening under isenthalpic conditions. Thus in figure shown below fluid passes through&nbsp; a restriction from section 1 to 2 and undergoes drop in its pressure and increase in volume but during this passage enthalpy remains constant such that h<sub>1</sub>=h<sub>2.</sub></p>\r\n<p><sub><img src=\"../../uploads/images/2rf-BZvkSxaN.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"192\" height=\"96\" /></sub></p>\r\n<p>Temperature may drop or increase during the process depending upon joule Thompson coefficient &mu;</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/3cqde-k7WrPvYz.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"312\" height=\"65\" /></p>\r\n<p>If &mu;=0 Temperature remains constant</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/zaz-D4KfItsF.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"244\" height=\"49\" /></p>\r\n<p>h) <strong>Adiabatic mixing</strong> :Adiabatic mixing refers to mixing of two or more streams of same or different fluids under adiabatic conditions.</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/wsx-yaY8dMS6.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"254\" height=\"142\" /></p>\r\n<p>Assumptions for applying S.F.E.E will be as follows:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>No heat interaction Q=0</li>\r\n<li>No work interaction W=0</li>\r\n<li>∆K.E.=0</li>\r\n<li>∆P.E.=0</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Thus,</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/zaq-dibZWySY.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"340\" height=\"143\" /></p>',0,'',597,5,223,3,'gate mechanical revision notes, gate mechanical free notes, gate mechanical free preparation, gate mechanical online preparation, gate 2018 mechanical online course, gate 2018 online notes','Free short notes for revision for GATE Mechanical Engineering, SSC JE Mechanical, UPSC ESE Mechanical Engineering on First Law of Thermodynamics.',1),(548,'2017-01-04 07:57:33','2017-07-09 09:25:26','SOLVE INTEGRALS PROBLEM','question','solve-integrals-problem','/uploads/images/solve-integrals-problem-FL4OdQd7.jpg','<p>Solve it.</p>',0,'',143,5,186,22,'','',1),(549,'2017-01-05 02:09:36','2017-07-10 04:33:30','Revision notes - Second Law of Thermodynamics','article','revision-notes-second-law-of-thermodynamics','/uploads/images/revision-notes-second-law-of-thermodynamics-15a0QwmV.jpg','<p>Second law says that natural processes occur in a certain direction. Energy has quantity as well as quality .A process cannot take place unless it satisfies First law and second law of thermodynamics.</p>\r\n<p>e.g. 1) A cup of hot coffee does not get hotter in a cold room</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;2) Transferring heat to an electric wire will not generate electricity</p>\r\n<p>The first law places no restriction on direction of process ,but satisfying first law does not ensure that process will occur.</p>\r\n<p>Work is said to be high grade energy and heat is a low grade energy .The complete conversion of low grade energy into high grade energy in&nbsp; a cycle is impossible while complete conversion of high grade energy into low grade is possible.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Thermal energy reservoir:</strong></p>\r\n<p>A hypothetical body with a relatively large thermal capacity that can supply finite amounts of heat without any change in its temperature.</p>\r\n<p>A Reservoir that supplies energy in form of heat is called <strong>Source</strong> and one that absorbs energy in form of heat&nbsp; is called <strong>Sink.</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Heat Engines</strong>:</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"\\uploads/images/fsbg-CSfpFAlD.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"353\" height=\"480\" /></p>\r\n<p>They receive heat from high temperature source, convert part of this heat to work and reject remaining waste heat to low temperature sink.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>They operate in a cycle .Heat engines and other cyclic devices involve a fluid to or from which heat is transferred while undergoing in&nbsp; cycle. This fluid is called working fluid.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Q<sub>in</sub>=Amount of heat supplied to steam in boiler from high temperature source</p>\r\n<p>Q<sub>out</sub>=Amount of heat rejected from the steam in the condenser to low temperature sink</p>\r\n<p>W<sub>out</sub>= Amount of work delivered by steam as it expands in the turbine</p>\r\n<p>W<sub>in</sub>=Amount of work required to compress water to boiler pressure</p>\r\n<p><strong>W<sub>net</sub>= W<sub>out </sub>- W<sub>in</sub></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>W<sub>net</sub>=Q<sub>in</sub>-Q<sub>out</sub></strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Thermal efficiency:</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Ceta%20%3D%20%5Cfrac%20%7BW_%7Bnet-out%7D%7D%7BQ_%7BH%7D%7D\" alt=\"\" /></strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Ceta%20%3D%201-%20%5Cfrac%20%7BQ_%7BL%7D%7D%7BQ_%7BH%7D%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>Efficiency of engine cannot be 100% some heat has to be rejected. Q<sub>L</sub>&ne;0.This is <strong>Kelvin Planck&rsquo;s Statement.</strong>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Clausius statement of Second Law:</strong></p>\r\n<p>No process is possible whose&nbsp;<strong>sole</strong>&nbsp;result is the transfer of heat from a cooler to a hotter body.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Refrigerator</strong>:The sole purpose of refrigerator is to remove Q<sub>L</sub> from Cooled space</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=COP_%7BR%7D%3D%5Cfrac%20%7BQ_%7BL%7D%7D%7BW_%7Bnet-in%7D%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>Where W<sub>net in</sub>=Q<sub>H</sub>-Q<sub>L</sub></p>\r\n<p>So<strong>,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=COP_%7BR%7D%3D%20%5Cfrac%20%7BQ_%7BL%7D%7D%7BQ_%7BH%7D-Q_%7BL%7D%7D\" alt=\"\" /></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Heat Pump</strong>:The objective heat pump is to supply the heat Q<sub>H </sub>to the warmer space.</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=COP_%7BHP%7D%3D%20%5Cfrac%20%7BQ_%7BH%7D%7D%7BQ_%7BH%7D-Q_%7BL%7D%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>Relationship between COP of Heat Pump and COP of Refrigerator.</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=COP_%7BHP%7D%3DCOP_%7BR%7D%2B1\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p><strong>Reversible Processes</strong></p>\r\n<p>A process is called completely reversible if, after the process has occurred, both the system and its surroundings can be wholly restored by any means to their respective initial states.</p>\r\n<p>For a process to be completely reversible, it is necessary that it be quasi-static and that there be no dissipative influences such as friction and diffusion.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Carnot cycle:</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"\\uploads/images/dv-MDWVj5kE.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"408\" height=\"265\" /></strong></p>\r\n<p>It consists of two reversible adiabatics and two reversible isothermal Procesess</p>\r\n<p>It is an ideal cycle</p>\r\n<p>It is reversible cycle</p>\r\n<p><strong>Carnot theorem:</strong></p>\r\n<p>It states that among all the heat engines operating between a given constant temperature source and given constant temperature sink None has a higher efficiency than a reversible engine.</p>\r\n<p>The efficiency of all reversible engines operating between same temperature levels is same.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Thermodynamic temperature scale:</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cfrac%20%7BQ_%7B1%7D%7D%7BQ_%7B2%7D%7D%3D%5Cfrac%20%7BT_%7B1%7D%7D%7BT_%7B2%7D%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;For a reversible cycle</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Efficiency of a Reversible cycle:</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Ceta%20%3D%201-%5Cfrac%20%7BQ_%7BL%7D%7D%7BQ_%7BH%7D%7D%3D1-%5Cfrac%7BT_%7BL%7D%7D%7BT_%7BH%7D%7D\" alt=\"\" />.</strong></p>',0,'',313,5,223,3,'gate mechanical revision notes, gate mechanical free notes, gate mechanical free preparation, gate mechanical online preparation, gate 2018 mechanical online course, gate 2018 online notes','Free short notes for revision for GATE Mechanical Engineering, SSC JE Mechanical, UPSC ESE Mechanical Engineering on Second Law of Thermodynamics.',1),(550,'2017-01-05 08:17:34','2017-07-05 12:33:32','SOLVE AREA BOUNDED BY CURVES','question','solve-aria-bounded-by-curves','/uploads/images/solve-aria-bounded-by-curves-5VGTZAxO.jpg','<p>Solve it.</p>',0,'',159,5,186,22,'','',1),(553,'2017-01-05 12:46:56','2017-07-05 11:59:07','General  aptitude','question','general-aptitude','','<p>Given digits 2,2,3,3,3,4,4,4,4 how many distinct four digit numbers greater than 3000 formed?</p>',0,'',149,5,65,2,'','',1),(554,'2017-01-06 05:30:09','2017-07-05 12:28:02','Find the natural frequency','question','find-the-natural-frequency','/uploads/images/find-the-natural-frequency-9qedqqWR.png','<p>Find the natural frequncy of this system. Use&nbsp;combination of springs.&nbsp;</p>',0,'',189,5,2,21,'gate 2018 practice questions, free question bank for gate mechanical engineering, gate 2019, gate practice questions, gate questions for mechanical engineering','A practice question on undamped free vibrations in the subject of mechanical vibrations. Helpful for GATE Mechanical Engineering and UPSC Engineering services exams.',1),(555,'2017-01-06 05:34:08','2017-07-06 23:40:14','Find the change in the natural frequency','question','find-the-change-in-the-natural-frequency','/uploads/images/find-the-change-in-the-natural-frequency-Jforivmp.png','<p>A cylinder partially immersed in riverwater is depressed slightly and released. Find its natural frequency assuming it stays upright all the time. What is the change in frequency, if the riverwater is replaced by seawater of Specific Gravity 1.1 times the river water.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Hint: Apply Newton\'s method.&nbsp;</p>',0,'',159,5,2,2,'gate 2018 practice questions, free question bank for gate mechanical engineering, gate 2019, gate practice questions, gate questions for mechanical engineering','A practice question on undamped free vibrations in the subject of mechanical vibrations. Helpful for GATE Mechanical Engineering and UPSC Engineering services exams.',1),(556,'2017-01-06 05:55:15','2017-07-05 12:55:08','Find the natural frequency of the system','question','find-the-natural-frequency-of-the-system','/uploads/images/find-the-natural-frequency-of-the-system-NtLyirmP.png','<p>A uniform stiff rod of length \'L\' is restrained to move vertically by both linear and torsional springs as shown in the figure. The stiffness of the linear springs is \'k\' Nm and that of the torsional spring is&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=k_%7Bt%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;Nm. Calculate the natural frequency of the vertical oscillation of the rod.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Hint: Draw the free body diagram and apply the Newton\'s method, i.e. applied torque = resisting torque.&nbsp;</p>',0,'',173,5,2,21,'gate 2018 practice questions, free question bank for gate mechanical engineering, gate 2019, gate practice questions, gate questions for mechanical engineering','A practice question on undamped free vibrations in the subject of mechanical vibrations. Helpful for GATE Mechanical Engineering and UPSC Engineering services exams.',1),(557,'2017-01-06 08:59:16','2017-07-05 13:02:37','Manufacturing of Iron and Steel - Basic fundamentals','article','manufacturing-of-iron-and-steel-bare-fundamentals','/uploads/images/manufacturing-of-iron-and-steel-bare-fundamentals-E4FnD95Y.jpg','<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Manufacturing of various steels and irons is done using iron ores, which is the basic material used in the manufacture of iron and steel. Iron ore contains many impurities in its natural form and the iron content also varies. Make a note of the variation of the iron in the iron ores in the below mentioned ores:</span></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Hematite - 30-65% of iron content</span></li>\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Magnetite - 60-70% or iron content</span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Creation of steel from this low-grade, impure iron ore (also called </span><strong><em>taconite</em></strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">) requires a process of:</span></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Mining</span></li>\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Crushing</span></li>\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Separating</span></li>\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Concentrating</span></li>\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Mixing</span></li>\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Pelletizing, and</span></li>\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Shipping</span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Before the iron ores are fed to the blast furnace, they are prepared. The preparation process is involves some form of concentrating process which means washing out the impurities and earthy matter like rocks and sand , which is followed by crushing, screening and sintering process. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">With the help of crushing, even sized lumps of ore and fines are formed. The fines and lumps are separated in the screening process. After this, the fines are mixed with coal or tar dust and sintered. The sintering process causes agglomeration of the fines and coal dust, and also helps in the removal of some volatile substances. The sinter and the unsintered ore is then fed to the blast furnace as a part of the charge. Other than this, the charge also contains coke which serves as a fuel, along with limestone which serves as a flux. </span></p>\r\n<p>Inside the blast furnace, the charge is subjected to intense heat at 1800 degree celsius. The reactions taking place inside a blast furnace are:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">At the bottom, Carbon + Oxygen = Carbon dioxide</span></li>\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">At the middle, Carbon dioxide + Carbon = Carbon Monoxide</span></li>\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">At the top, Iron oxide + Carbon Monoxide = Iron + Carbon Dioxide</span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">After reaction 3, the iron which is produced is a spongy mass which falls to the furnace bottom. The molten iron is collected in the hearth of the furnace, with the slag floating at the top of the surface. Removal of the iron from the furnace, which is also called </span><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">tapping</span></em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> is done every 6 hours. After tapping, the molten iron runs from the furnace through sand channels into </span><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">pig beds</span></em><strong><em>, </em></strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">and that is the term </span><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">pig iron </span></em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">is used. This pig iron is very brittle and has very little use. A random sample of pig iron will contain the below given components:</span></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Combined carbon 0.5%</span></li>\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Manganese 0.5%</span></li>\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Graphite 3.4%</span></li>\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Phosphorus 0.03%</span></li>\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Silicon 2.6%</span></li>\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Sulphur 0.02%</span></li>\r\n</ol>',0,'',342,5,2,16,'manufacture of steel and iron, notes for class 4 exams, marine engineering, notes for mechanical engineering, notes of blast furnace, marine engineering notes, mechanical engineering notes','Basic notes on manufacture of steel and iron from iron ore. Useful for students in Mechanical Engineering, practicing mechanical engineers and Marine Engineers.',1),(558,'2017-01-07 07:23:52','2017-07-09 04:45:12','Try this from som','question','try-this-from-som','/uploads/images/try-this-from-som-ZgtFBixv.jpg','<p>Solve it.</p>',0,'',159,5,186,2,'','',1),(559,'2017-01-07 09:46:40','2017-07-09 05:28:53','Try this question from vibration','question','try-this-question-from-vibration','/uploads/images/try-this-question-from-vibration-7FBQ11J9.jpg','<p>Solve it.</p>',0,'',124,5,186,21,'','',1),(560,'2017-01-08 06:26:44','2017-07-09 21:10:16','flow work','question','flow-work','/uploads/images/flow-work-5MvhPgPU.PNG','<p>help me to tackle this question</p>',0,'',183,5,233,3,'','',1),(561,'2017-01-08 16:24:39','2017-07-09 11:46:37','Short notes on Network Scheduling by PERT and CPM','article','short-notes-on-network-scheduling-by-pert-and-cpm','/uploads/images/short-notes-on-network-scheduling-by-pert-and-cpm-pWnfIv8p.png','<p><strong>PERT &amp; CPM is a very important topic in GATE Mechanical Engineering and other engineering exams from the subject of Industrial Engineering.&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>INTRODUCTION</strong></p>\r\n<p>Network scheduling is a technique&nbsp; used for planning and scheduling large projects in the fields of construction, maintenance, fabrication and purchasing of computer systems etc. It is a method of minimizing trouble spots such as production,delays and interruptions by determining critical factors and coordinating various parts of overall job.</p>\r\n<p>There are two basic planning and control techniques that utilize a network to complete a predetermined&nbsp; project or schedule. These are Programme evaluation Review Technique(PERT) and Critical path method(CPM).</p>\r\n<p>A project is defined as a combination of interrelated activities,all of which must be executed in a certain order for its completion.</p>\r\n<p>The work involved in a project can be divided into 3 phases corresponding&nbsp; to the management functions of planning ,scheduling and controlling.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Planning:</strong>This phase involves setting the objectives of the project as well as assumptions to be made .It also involves the listing of tasks or jobs that must be performed in order to complete a project under consideration. In this phase ,in addition to the estimates of costs and duration of various activities,the manpower ,machines and&nbsp; materials required for project are also determined.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Scheduling:</strong>This consists of laying the activities according to their order of precedence and determine the following :</p>\r\n<p>[i] The start and finish times of each activity</p>\r\n<p>[ii] The critical activities on which activities require special attention.</p>\r\n<p>[iii] The slack and float for the non critical paths.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Controlling: </strong>This phase is exercised after the planning and scheduling .It involves the following :</p>\r\n<p>[i] Making periodical progress reports</p>\r\n<p>[ii] reviewing the process</p>\r\n<p>[iii]Analysing the status of the project</p>\r\n<p>[iv] Making management decisions regarding updating ,crashing, and resource allocation</p>\r\n<p><strong>BASIC TERMS:</strong></p>\r\n<p>To understand the network techniques one should be familiar with a few basic terms of which both CPM and PERT are special applications:</p>\r\n<p><strong>Network:&nbsp;</strong>It is graphic representation of sequentially connected arrows and nodes representing activities and events in a project. Networks are also called arrow diagrams</p>\r\n<p><strong>Activity:</strong> An activity represents some action and is a time consuming effort necessary to complete a particular part of the overall project .Thus each and every activity has appoint of time where it begins and a point where it ends.</p>\r\n<p>It is represented in the network by an arrow.</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/p1-XqkWJrix.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"269\" height=\"77\" /></p>\r\n<p>Here A is called activity</p>\r\n<p><strong>Event: </strong>The beginning and end points of an activity&nbsp; are called events or nodes .Event is point in time and does not&nbsp; consume any resources. It is represented by a numbered circle. The head event&nbsp; called j<sup>th</sup> event always has a number higher than the tail event which is also called i<sup>th</sup> event.</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/p2-R5qfeIpL.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"226\" height=\"91\" /></p>\r\n<p><strong>Merge and Burst Events</strong>: It is not necessary for an event to be the ending event of only one activity as it can be the ending event for two or more activities. Such an event is defined as merge event.</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/p3-oqroBsjw.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"235\" height=\"192\" /></p>\r\n<p>If the event happens to be beginning event of two or more activities ,it is defined as&nbsp; burst event.</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/p4-ZOW9KUqb.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"178\" height=\"129\" /></p>\r\n<p><strong>Preceding, succeeding and concurrent activities: &nbsp;</strong>Activities that must be completed before a given event can occur are termed as <em>preceding activities</em>.</p>\r\n<p>Activities that cannot be accomplished until an event has occurred are termed as <em>succeeding activities.</em></p>\r\n<p>Activities that can be accomplished concurrently are known as <em>concurrent activities</em>.</p>\r\n<p>This classification is relative which means that one activity can be preceding to a certain event and the same activity can be succeeding to some other event or it may be a concurrent activity with one or more activities.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Dummy Activity</strong>: Certain activities which neither consume time nor resources but are used&nbsp; simply to represent a connection or link between the events are known as dummies. It is shown in the network by dotted line. The purpose of introducing dummy activity is:</p>\r\n<p>[i] To maintain the uniqueness in numbering system as every activity may have a distinct set of events by which activity can be identified.</p>\r\n<p>[ii] To maintain a proper logic in&nbsp; the network</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/p6-vma4HLPt.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"354\" height=\"230\" /></p>\r\n<p>COMMON ERRORS:</p>\r\n<p>Following are common errors in a network construction:</p>\r\n<p><strong>Looping(Cycling) </strong>In a network diagram a looping error is also known as cycling error. Drawing an endless loop in network is known as error of looping .A loop can be formed if an activity is represented by going back in time.</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/p7-fhzWFDIS.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"385\" height=\"250\" /></p>\r\n<p><strong>Dangling:&nbsp;</strong>To disconnect an activity before completion of all activities in the network diagram is known as dangling.</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/p8-HmPyDh1p.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"332\" height=\"251\" /></p>\r\n<p><strong>Redundancy:</strong></p>\r\n<p>If a dummy activity is only activity emanating from an event and can be eliminated it is known as redundancy.</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/p9-pay93cRh.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"429\" height=\"208\" /></p>\r\n<p>In the next set of short notes, we will look at&nbsp;<strong>Rules of network construction.&nbsp;</strong></p>',0,'',435,5,2,13,'gate, gate 2019 online course, gate 2019 mechanical engineering course, gate mechanical engineering, gate 2019, gate, gate online course, gate online course 2019 on mechanical engineering, gate short notes on pert and cpm','In this article, we will study about the topic of PERT and CPM in the form of short notes for GATE Mechanical Engineering.',1),(562,'2017-01-09 02:06:01','2017-07-09 09:27:34','Short Notes on PERT & CPM for GATE Mechanical Engineering - Part 2','article','short-notes-on-pert-cpm-for-gate-mechanical-engineering-part-2','/uploads/images/short-notes-on-pert-cpm-for-gate-mechanical-engineering-part-2-gxSpkZnI.jpg','<p>In this article, we will continue the topic of PERT and CPM and discuss about network constructiion.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Rules of network construction:</strong></p>\r\n<p>There are number of rules in connection with handling of events and activities of project network that should be followed :</p>\r\n<p>[i] Try to avoid arrows that cross each other</p>\r\n<p>[ii]Use straight arrows.</p>\r\n<p>[iii]No event can occur until an activity preceding it has been completed</p>\r\n<p>[iv] An event cannot occur twice i.e. there must be no loops</p>\r\n<p>[v]An activity succeeding an event cannot be started until that event has occurred .</p>\r\n<p>[vi]Use arrows from left to right .Avoid mixing two directions, vertical and standing arrows may be used if necessary .</p>\r\n<p>[vii]Dummies should be introduced only if it is extremely necessary.</p>\r\n<p>[viii]The network has only one entry point called the start event and one point of emergence called the end or terminal point.</p>\r\n<p><strong>NUMBERING THE EVENTS[FULKERSON&rsquo;S RULE]</strong></p>\r\n<p>[i]Event numbers should be unique</p>\r\n<p>[ii]Event numbering should be carried out on a sequential basis from left to right</p>\r\n<p>[iii] The initial event which has all outgoing arrows with no incoming arrows is numbered as 1</p>\r\n<p>[iv]&nbsp; Delete all arrows emerging from all numbered events .This will create at least one new start event out of preceding events</p>\r\n<p>[v]Number all new start events 2,3 and so on Repeat this process until the terminal event without any successor activity is reached .Number the terminal node suitably.</p>\r\n<p>*The head of an arrow should always bear a number higher than one assigned&nbsp; to the tail of the arrow.</p>\r\n<p><strong>CONSTRUCTION OF NETWORK</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Example </strong>Construct a network for each of the projects whose activities and their precedence relationships are&nbsp; given below:</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/aqaqa-YKsVE1i7.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"491\" height=\"34\" /></p>\r\n<p><strong>Soln:&nbsp;</strong>A,B,C are concurrent activities as they start simultaneously .B becomes predecessor of activities E and F.</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/1212-ntY1uN0s.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"326\" height=\"257\" /></p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/12123-kGldEZ9u.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"355\" height=\"181\" /></p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/12121-8z71cHJL.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"422\" height=\"215\" /></p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/121212-fzUHKK7M.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"438\" height=\"223\" /></p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/1212122-fd418u69.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"412\" height=\"221\" /></p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/121112-sr8scdd1.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"385\" height=\"207\" /></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>In the next article, we will talk about Time Analysis for a project, which forms an important part of scheduling calcuations questions in GATE Mechancal Engineering.&nbsp;</strong></p>',0,'',387,5,2,13,'gate, gate 2019 online course, gate 2019 mechanical engineering course, gate mechanical engineering, gate 2019, gate, gate online course, gate online course 2019 on mechanical engineering, gate short notes on pert and cpm','In this article, we will study about the topic of PERT and CPM in the form of short notes for GATE Mechanical Engineering.',1),(566,'2017-01-10 12:22:54','2017-07-10 03:11:42','Important points to remember for IC Engines - Short notes for GATE Mechanical Engineering','article','important-points-to-remember-for-ic-engines-short-notes-for-gate-mechanical-engi','/uploads/images/important-points-to-remember-for-ic-engines-short-notes-for-gate-mechanical-engineering-6fmmtwFF.jpg','<p>In this article, we will list down all the important mathematical relations and formulas to be used in the topic of IC Engines.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>1) Air Standard Efficiency</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>For SI Engines, air standard efficiency increases as the compression ration increases and then becomes more or less constant as the compression ratio becomes more than 14.&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li>For&nbsp;CI Engines, air standard efficiency decreases as the cut-off ratio increases but increases as the compression ratio increases.&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li>The mean effective pressure increases as the compression ratio and cut off ratio increase.&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li>Air standard efficiency is the maximum for an engine cycle.&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>The Otto cycle is shown in the figure below,</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/otto-MCv1Vfo4.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"287\" height=\"222\" /></p>\r\n<p>Compression ration,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=r%3D%5Cfrac%7Bv_%7B1%7D%7D%7Bv_%7B2%7D%7D%3D%5Cfrac%7Bv_%7B4%7D%7D%7Bv_%7B3%7D%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>Where,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=v_%7B2%7D%3Dv_%7B3%7D\" alt=\"\" />=clearance volume.</p>\r\n<p>Air standard or themal efficiency,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Ceta_%7Ba%7D%3D%5Ceta_%7Bth%7D%3D1-%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7Br%5E%7B%5Cgamma%20-1%7D%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>Mean effective pressure = Work done/ Swept volume =&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cfrac%7Bc_%7Bv%7D%5B(T_%7B3%7D-T_%7B2%7D)-(T_%7B4%7D-T_%7B1%7D)%5D%7D%7Bv_%7B1%7D-v_%7B2%7D%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>The Diesel cycle is shown in the figure below:</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/diesel-GIRH8JXl.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"303\" height=\"226\" /></p>\r\n<p>Cut off ratio,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Crho%20%3D%20%5Cfrac%7Bv_%7B3%7D%7D%7Bv_%7B2%7D%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>Compression ratio,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=r%3D%5Cfrac%7Bv_%7B1%7D%7D%7Bv_%7B2%7D%7D%3D%5Cfrac%7Bv_%7B4%7D%7D%7Bv_%7B2%7D%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Ceta_%7Bth%7D%3D1-%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7Br%5E%7B%5Cgamma%20-1%7D%7D%5B%5Cfrac%20%7B%5Crho%5E%7B%5Cgamma%7D-1%7D%7B%5Cgamma%20(%5Crho%20-1)%7D%5D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>Mean effective pressure,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=p_%7Bm%7D%3D%5Cfrac%7Bc_%7Bp%7D(T_%7B3%7D-T_%7B2%7D)-c_%7Bv%7D(T_%7B4%7D-T_%7B1%7D)%7D%7Bv_%7B1%7D-v_%7B2%7D%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>2) Fuel ignition formulas for SI Engines:</p>\r\n<p>The ignition of fuel in petrol engines may be through a battery of 6 to 12 V and magneto ignition. The magneto system is used in high speed engines like scooters, motor cycles, racing cras, aeroplanes etc. The ignition voltage is as high as 25000 V.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Number of sparks produced = (rpm of engine x number of cylinders)/2 , for a 4 stroke engine</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>and</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Number of sparks produced = (rpm of engine x number of cylinders), for a 2 stroke engine&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p>3) Governing of IC Engines</p>\r\n<p>Governing is to keep the speed of the engine constant regardless of the changes in the load on the engine. The different methods of governing are:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li><strong>Hit and miss governing:&nbsp;</strong>In this the fuel supplied to the engine is completely cut-off during few cycles of the engine. This is used for gas engines.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Quality governing:&nbsp;</strong>The fuel supplied per cycle to the engine is varied, i.e AF ratio is changed according to the load on the engine. This is used for diesel engines.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Quantity governing:&nbsp;</strong>The quantity of AF mixture supplied is varied according to the load on the engine. This is used for petrol engines. In this the AF ratio does not change.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>4) Knocking in CI Engines:</p>\r\n<p>At higher compression ratios, the combustion process causes abnormal pressure rise resulting in nouse and rapid deterioration of engine parts. This produces a metallic sound by the pressure impact on the piston and is termed as knocking or pinging. It is due to auto-ignition at the end portion of the unburned charge in the combustion chamber. To reduce knocking, read the table given below.</p>\r\n<table style=\"width: 250.515625px;\" border=\"1\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 109px;\"><strong>Variable</strong></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 162.515625px;\"><strong>Action to be taken to reduce knocking</strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 109px;\">1. Charge inlet temperature</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 162.515625px;\">Increase</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 109px;\">2. Charge inlet pressure</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 162.515625px;\">Increase</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 109px;\">3. Compression load</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 162.515625px;\">Increase</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 109px;\">4. Engine load</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 162.515625px;\">Increase</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 109px;\">5. Cooling water temperature&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 162.515625px;\">Decrease</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 109px;\">6. Fuel droplets</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 162.515625px;\">Decrease their size</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 109px;\">7. Fuel injection</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 162.515625px;\">About&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=11.5%5E%7Bo%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;before TDC</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 109px;\">8. Engine speed</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 162.515625px;\">Decrease</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 109px;\">9. Engine size</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 162.515625px;\">Large</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 109px;\">10. Fuel ignitionability</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 162.515625px;\">High</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 109px;\">11. Hydrocarbons</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 162.515625px;\">use unsaturated hydrocarbons</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>5) Detonation in SI Engines:</p>\r\n<p>Detonation occurs due to auto-ignition of the fuel before the spark actually occurs. The variables to control detonation in SI are given in the table below.</p>\r\n<table style=\"width: 197px;\" border=\"1\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr style=\"height: 14px;\">\r\n<td style=\"width: 140.390625px; height: 14px;\"><strong>Running condition</strong></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 74.609375px; height: 14px;\"><strong>F/A ratio</strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr style=\"height: 13px;\">\r\n<td style=\"width: 140.390625px; height: 13px;\">Starting</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 74.609375px; height: 13px;\">0.2:1</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr style=\"height: 13px;\">\r\n<td style=\"width: 140.390625px; height: 13px;\">Warming</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 74.609375px; height: 13px;\">0.15:1</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr style=\"height: 13px;\">\r\n<td style=\"width: 140.390625px; height: 13px;\">idling</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 74.609375px; height: 13px;\">0.085:1</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr style=\"height: 13px;\">\r\n<td style=\"width: 140.390625px; height: 13px;\">Running with maximum thermal efficiency (80% throttle)</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 74.609375px; height: 13px;\">0.06 to 0.07:1</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr style=\"height: 13px;\">\r\n<td style=\"width: 140.390625px; height: 13px;\">Running with developing maximum power (80% throttle)</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 74.609375px; height: 13px;\">0.0775 to 0.08:1</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr style=\"height: 13px;\">\r\n<td style=\"width: 140.390625px; height: 13px;\">Full throttle</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 74.609375px; height: 13px;\">0.085:1</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr style=\"height: 13px;\">\r\n<td style=\"width: 140.390625px; height: 13px;\">Acceleration</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 74.609375px; height: 13px;\">0.1:1</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>To reduce detonation, following actions can be taken.</p>\r\n<table style=\"width: 187px;\" border=\"1\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 106.4375px;\"><strong>Variable</strong></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 97.5625px;\"><strong>Action to be taken to control detonation</strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 106.4375px;\">1. Compression ratio</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 97.5625px;\">Reduce</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 106.4375px;\">2. Mass inducted</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 97.5625px;\">Reduce</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 106.4375px;\">3. Inlet temperature</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 97.5625px;\">Reduce</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 106.4375px;\">4. Chamber wall temperature</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 97.5625px;\">Reduce</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 106.4375px;\">5. Spark timing</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 97.5625px;\">Reduce</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 106.4375px;\">6. Air-fuel ratio</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 97.5625px;\">make very rich</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 106.4375px;\">7. Turbulence</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 97.5625px;\">Increase</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 106.4375px;\">8. Engine speed&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 97.5625px;\">Increase</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 106.4375px;\">9. Distance of flame travel</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 97.5625px;\">Reduce</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>6) Performance Parameters:</p>\r\n<p>(a) Indicated power, IP =<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=(p_%7Bindicated%7D%20LAN)%2F(60%20%5Ctimes%201000%20%5Ctimes%20n)%20kW\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>Where&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=p_%7Bindicated%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;= indicated mean effective pressure</p>\r\n<p>L = length of stroke, m</p>\r\n<p>A = area of piston,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=m%5E%7B2%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>N = RPM of engine</p>\r\n<p>n = number of strokes per revolution = 2 for 4 stroke cycle and 1 for 2 stroke cycles.</p>\r\n<p>(b) Brake power, BP =<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=(p_%7Bbm)%20LAN)%2F(60%20%5Ctimes%201000%20%5Ctimes%20n)%20kW\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>Where&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=p_%7Bbm%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;= brake mean effective pressure</p>\r\n<p>(c) Frictional power = IP - BP</p>\r\n<p>(d) Mechanical efficiency,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Ceta%20_%7Bmech%7D%3DBP%2FIP%3Dp_%7Bbm%7D%2Fp_%7Bim%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>(e) BSFC =&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5B(60%20%5Ctimes%20m_%7Bf%7D)%2F(BP%20%5Ctimes%20t)%5D%20kg%2FBP.h\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>Where&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=m_%7Bf%7D\" alt=\"\" />=mass of fuel consumed, kg</p>\r\n<p>t = time in minutes</p>\r\n<p>(f) IFSC =&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=(60%20%5Ctimes%20m_%7Bf%7D)%2F(IP%20%5Ctimes%20t)%20kg%2FIP.h\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>(g) Brake thermal efficiency,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Ceta%20_%7Bbth%7D%3D(BP%20%5Ctimes%2060)%2F(m_%7Bf%7D%20%5Ctimes%20LCV)\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>LCV = lower calorific value of fuel</p>\r\n<p>(h) Indicated thermal efficiency,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Ceta_%7Bit%7D%3D(IP%20%5Ctimes%2060)%2F(m_%7Bf%7D%20%5Ctimes%20LCV)\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>(i) Relative efficiency,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Ceta_%7Br%7D%3D%5Ceta_%7Bbth%7D%2F%5Ceta_%7Ba%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>(j) Specific output = BP/A.L</p>\r\n<p>7) Testing of IC Engines:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Indicated power:&nbsp;</strong>Can be determined with the help of p-v diagram using a mechanical indicator</li>\r\n<li><strong>Brake power:&nbsp;</strong>Can be determined by measuring the torque on a dynamometer and speed by a tachometer or a stroboscope. For multi-cylinder engines,&nbsp;<strong>Morse test&nbsp;</strong>is carried out to determine the indicated power of each cylinder. The brake power of the engine is measured by cutting off each cylinder in turn. The indicated power of the engine cylinder cut off is:&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=(BP)_%7Bn%7D-(BP)_%7Bn-1%7D%3D(IP)_%7Bn%7D-(IP)_%7Bn-1%7D%3DIP\" alt=\"\" /></li>\r\n<li><strong>Air consumption:&nbsp;</strong>it can be determined with the help of the orifice chamber method.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Fuel consumption:&nbsp;</strong>it can be determined by using a burette and a stop watch.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Heat carried by cooling water:&nbsp;</strong>it is measure by measuring the water flow rate through the cooling jacket and the rise in temperature of the water during the flow through the engine.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Heat carried away by exhaust gases:&nbsp;</strong>The temperature of exhaust gases coming out of engine can be measured by a thermometer or thermocouple. An exhaust gas calorimeter can also be used to measure the heat carried away by the exhaust gases.&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Willian\'s line:</strong></p>\r\n<p>It is a plot of fuel consumption vs brake power. The intercept of the produced line with the x-axis which is the brake power line gives the frictional power. Check the figure below,</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/willian-line-e0u7rHSe.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"284\" height=\"195\" /></p>\r\n<p>8) Equivalence ratio =&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=AF_%7Bstoich%7D%2FAF_%7Bactual%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;= 1 for chemically correct charge</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &lt; 1 for lean mixture, and&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &gt; 1 for rich mixture</p>\r\n<p>Chemically correct (or stoichiometric) mixture of the air-fuel can be obtained from the chemical balance of the constituents of the fuel being used for the engine. Let us look at an example for gasoline fuel:</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=2C_%7B8%7DH_%7B18%7D%20%2B%2025%20O_%7B2%7D%20%3D16CO_%7B2%7D%2B18H_%7B2%7DO\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>mass of gasoline = 228 kg</p>\r\n<p>mass of oxygen = 800 kg</p>\r\n<p>Oxygen in air by weight = 23%</p>\r\n<p>Air required = 800/(228 x 0.23) = 15.25 kg of air /kg of fuel</p>\r\n<p>AF ratio = 15.25:1</p>\r\n<p>Useful AF ratio is 20% lean to 8% rich.&nbsp;</p>',0,'',500,5,223,3,'gate mechanical revision notes, gate mechanical free notes, gate mechanical free preparation, gate mechanical online preparation, gate 2018 mechanical online course, gate 2018 online notes','In this article, we have listed all the main points to remember for the topic of Internal Combustion Engines needed for solving numerical in GATE Mechanical Engineering and UPSC ESE Mechanical Engineering. ',1),(567,'2017-01-11 06:58:58','2017-07-09 16:03:38','Understanding Net Positive Suction Head - Short notes for GATE Mechanical Engineering','article','understanding-net-positive-suction-head-short-notes-for-gate-mechanical-engineer','/uploads/images/understanding-net-positive-suction-head-short-notes-for-gate-mechanical-engineering-ThHiy5s0.jpg','<p>In this article, we will look at the basic understanding of Net Positive Suction Head or NPSH. This topic is rather a difficult one to grasp for most of the students who are preparing for <a href=\"https://mindvis.in/courses/gate-2018-mechanical-engineering-online-course\" target=\"_blank\"><strong>GATE Mechanical Engineering</strong></a> or UPSC ESE Mechanical Engineering exams. Let us begin by understanding&nbsp;<strong>Atmospheric Air.&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Atmospheric Air:</strong></p>\r\n<p>As defined by Italian scientist,&nbsp;<strong>Evangelista Torricelli&nbsp;</strong>in 17th century, we live submerged at the bottom of an ocean of air. The weight of this ocean of air exerts a force on Earth\'s surface which is called&nbsp;<strong>barometric pressure.&nbsp;</strong>After this Torricelli created the mercury barometer, which uses a complete vacuum at the top of a glass tube to draw mercury up the tube. The weight of the mercury column is equal to the weight of the air outside the tube. For this reason, we measure the atmospheric pressure in&nbsp;<strong>mm Hg&nbsp;</strong>or&nbsp;<strong>inHg.&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"/uploads/images/barometer-EJsEJXEo.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"232\" height=\"319\" /></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Pump operation:</strong></p>\r\n<p>If you don\'t understand how a pump functions then you will always struggle at the problems involving pump calculations.&nbsp;<strong>Pumps work by creating a low pressure at inlet which allows the liquid to be pushed into the pump by atmospheric or head pressure (i.e. the pressure due to the liquid\'s surface being above the centreline of the pump).&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p>Consider, you have a pump at the top of the mercury barometer, which is shown in the figure above. Even if there is perfect vacuum at the pump inlet, atmospheric pressure limits how high the pump can lift the liquid. With liquids lighter than mercury, this lift can increase, but there is still a physical limit to the pump operation based on the pressure external to the pump.&nbsp;<strong>This limit is the key to understanding NPSH.&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Net Positive Suction Head (NPSH):</strong></p>\r\n<p>NPSH can be defined in two ways, as given below;</p>\r\n<p>1)&nbsp;<strong>NPSH Available (<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=NPSH_%7BA%7D\" alt=\"\" />):&nbsp;</strong>The absolute pressure at the suction port of the pump.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>AND</p>\r\n<p>2)&nbsp;<strong>NPSH Required (<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=NPSH_%7BR%7D\" alt=\"\" />):&nbsp;</strong>It is the minimum pressure required at the suction port of the pump to keep the pump from cavitating.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=NPSH_%7BA%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;is a function of your system and must be calculated, on the other hand&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=NPSH_%7BR%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;is a function of the pump and must be provided by the pump manufacturer. For the pump to operate without cavitating,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=NPSH_%7BA%7D%3ENPSH_%7BR%7D\" alt=\"\" />. To understand this in simpler words, you must have more suction side pressure&nbsp;<strong>available&nbsp;</strong>than the pump&nbsp;<strong>requires.&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Calculating&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=NPSH_%7BA%7D\" alt=\"\" />:</strong></p>\r\n<p>It is critical to get the value of&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=NPSH_%7BR%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;from the pump manufacturer and ensure that your&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=NPSH_%7BA%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;pressure is adequate to cover the requirement. The formula to calculate&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=NPSH_%7BA%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;is given below:</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=NPSH_%7BA%7D%3DH_%7BA%7D%20%5Cpm%20H_%7BZ%7D%20-%20H_%7BF%7D%20%2B%20H_%7BV%7D%20-%20H_%7BVP%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>Where,</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=H_%7BA%7D\" alt=\"\" />= The absolute pressure on the surface of the liquid in the supply tank. This is typically atmospheric pressure (vented supply tank), but can be different for closed tanks. It is always positive.</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=H_%7BZ%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;= The vertical distance between the surface of the liquid in the supply tank and the centreline of the pump. It can be positive when the liquid level is above the centreline of the pump,&nbsp;<strong>static head.&nbsp;</strong>It can be negative when the liquid level is below the centreline of the pump,&nbsp;<strong>suction lift.&nbsp;<em>Always use the lowest liquid level allowed in the tank.&nbsp;</em></strong></p>\r\n<p><em><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=H_%7BF%7D\" alt=\"\" />=&nbsp;</em>Friction lossed in the suction piping.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=H_%7BV%7D\" alt=\"\" />=Velocity head at the pump suction port</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=H_%7BVP%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;= Absolute vapor pressure of the liquid at the pumping temperature. It is usually subtracted at the end to make sure that the inlet pressure stays above the vapor pressure.&nbsp;<em>As the temperature goes up, so does the vapor pressure.&nbsp;</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>',0,'',493,5,2,5,'gate mechanical revision notes, gate mechanical free notes, gate mechanical free preparation, gate mechanical online preparation, gate 2018 mechanical online course, gate 2018 online notes','In this article we will learn the basic concept of Net Positive Suction Head (NPSH) in the topic of Fluid mechanics for GATE Mechanical Engineering. ',1),(568,'2017-01-12 10:12:11','2017-07-04 10:03:25','Solve this question on Coriolis acceleration','question','solve-this-question-on-coriolis-acceleration-mbo6808U','/uploads/images/solve-this-question-on-coriolis-acceleration-eulJjSYQ.PNG','<p>The direction of Coriolis component of acceleration of the slider A with respect to the coincident point B is shown in the figures above.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Directions shown by the figures</p>\r\n<p>(a) 2 and 4 are correct</p>\r\n<p>(b) 1 and 2 are correct</p>\r\n<p>(c) 1 and 3 are correct</p>\r\n<p>(d) 2 and 3 are correct</p>',0,'',172,5,2,23,'gate mechanical practice questions, gate mechanical revision notes, gate mechanical free notes, gate mechanical free preparation, gate mechanical online preparation, gate 2018 mechanical online course, gate 2018 online notes','Try this practice question on Coriolis Acceleration in Mechanisms, which is an important topic in GATE Mechanical Engineering. ',1),(569,'2017-01-12 10:18:59','2017-07-08 09:30:41','Solve this question on Instantaneous centre of mechanisms','question','solve-this-question-on-instantaneous-centre-of-mechanisms','/uploads/images/solve-this-question-on-instantaneous-centre-of-mechanisms-vhfKBvW6.PNG','<p>In the mechanism shown, the fixed link denoted as 1, crank AB as 2, rocker BD as 3, swivel trunion at C as 4. The instantaneous centre I<sub>41</sub> is at</p>\r\n<p>(a) the centre of the swivel trunion</p>\r\n<p>(b) the intersection of line AB and a perpendicular to BD at C</p>\r\n<p>(c) infinity along AC</p>\r\n<p>(d) infinity perpendicular to BD</p>',0,'',148,5,2,23,'gate practice questions, gate mechanical revision notes, gate mechanical free notes, gate mechanical free preparation, gate mechanical online preparation, gate 2018 mechanical online course, gate 2018 online notes','Try this practice question on Instantaneous Centre of Mechanisms, which is an important topic in GATE Mechanical Engineering. ',1),(570,'2017-01-12 10:23:31','2017-07-08 09:21:58','Solve this question on theory of machines','question','solve-this-question-on-theory-of-machines','/uploads/images/solve-this-question-on-theory-of-machines-YIde8yl2.PNG','<p>With reference to the mechanism shown in the figure, the relation between F and P is</p>\r\n<p>(a) F= (1/2) P tan&nbsp;&alpha;</p>\r\n<p>(b)&nbsp;F= &nbsp;P tan&nbsp;&alpha;</p>\r\n<p>(c)&nbsp;P = 2 F&nbsp;tan&nbsp;&alpha;</p>\r\n<p>(d)&nbsp;F= 2 P tan&nbsp;&alpha;</p>',0,'',159,5,2,23,'gate mechanical practice questions, gate mechanical revision notes, gate mechanical free notes, gate mechanical free preparation, gate mechanical online preparation, gate 2018 mechanical online course, gate 2018 online notes','Try this practice question on Theory of machines, which is an important topic in GATE Mechanical Engineering. ',1),(571,'2017-01-13 08:34:52','2017-07-05 12:55:02','Solve this question on logical reasoning ','question','solve-this-question-on-logical-reasoning','/uploads/images/solve-this-question-on-logical-reasoning-aHumKLH9.jpg','<p>Solve this question. Share your reasons as well.&nbsp;</p>',0,'',121,5,2,12,'General aptitude questions for gate, gate MECHANICAL engineering, gate question bank','Solve this problem on Logical reasoning from General aptitude section in GATE. ',1),(572,'2017-01-13 09:01:55','2017-07-10 05:00:10','Try and solve this question on engineering mechanics','question','try-and-solve-this-question-on-engineering-mechanics','/uploads/images/try-and-solve-this-question-on-engineering-mechanics-rHLftnTP.jpg','<p>Neglecting friction find the force on each block.&nbsp;</p>',0,'',148,5,2,11,' questions for gate, gate MECHANICAL engineering, gate question bank','Solve this problem on engineering mechanics section in GATE. ',1),(573,'2017-01-13 11:30:10','2017-07-08 22:18:28','Solve this question on general aptitude','question','solve-this-question-on-general-aptitude','/uploads/images/solve-this-question-on-general-aptitude-8xZxewHO.jpg','<p>Share your working along with your answers.</p>',0,'',121,5,2,18,'General aptitude questions for gate, gate MECHANICAL engineering, gate question bank','Solve this problem from General aptitude section in GATE. ',1),(574,'2017-01-14 04:19:13','2017-07-08 10:19:32','Practice questions on Probability','question','practice-questions-on-probability','/uploads/images/practice-questions-on-probability-1HboxK3c.jpg','<p>Q1) From 6 positive and 8 negative numbers, 4 numbers are chosen at random (without replacement) and multiplied. What is the probability that the product is positive?</p>\r\n<p>Q2) A box contains 4 bad and 6 good tubes. Two are drawn out from the box at a time. One of them is tested and found to be good. What is the probability that the other one is also good?</p>\r\n<p>Q3) In a shooting test, the probability of hitting the target is 1/2 for A, 2/3 for B and 3/4 for C. if all of them fire at the target, find the probability that (i) none of them hits the targer and (ii) at least one of them hits the target.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Q4) A bolt manufactured by three machines A, B and C. A turns out twice as many items as B, and machines B and C produce equal number of items. 2% of bolts produced by A and B are defective and 4% of the bolts produced by C are defective. All bolts are put into 1 stock pile and 1 is chosen from this pile. What is the probability that it is defective?</p>\r\n<p>Q5) In a coin tossing experiment, if the coin shows head, 1 dice is thrown and the result is recorded. But if the coin shows tail, 2 dice are thrown and their sum is recorded. What is the probability that the recorded number will be 2?</p>\r\n<p>Q6) If at least 1 child in a family with 2 children is a boy, what is the probability that both children are boys?</p>\r\n<p>Q7) A fair dice is rolled 5 times. Find the probability that 1 shows twice, 3 shows twice and 6 shows once.</p>',0,'',235,5,223,22,'','',1),(575,'2017-01-15 04:06:02','2017-07-09 15:29:44','Practice questions on machining','question','practice-questions-on-machining','/uploads/images/practice-questions-on-machining-xOViFL3Z.jpg','<p>Solve these on machining.</p>',0,'',142,5,2,9,' questions for gate, gate MECHANICAL engineering, gate question bank','Solve this problem on machining section in GATE. ',1),(576,'2017-01-15 04:08:19','2017-07-05 12:42:12','Machining questions for practice','question','machining-questions-for-practice','/uploads/images/machining-questions-for-practice-dE1cMQFN.jpg','<p>Try solving these</p>',0,'',162,5,2,9,' questions for gate, gate MECHANICAL engineering, gate question bank','Solve this problem on machining section in GATE. ',1),(577,'2017-01-16 07:47:54','2017-07-07 12:34:55','Special functions for Engineering Mathematics in GATE Mechanical Engineering','article','special-functions-for-engineering-mathematics-in-gate-mechanical-engineering','/uploads/images/special-functions-for-engineering-mathematics-in-gate-mechanical-engineering-OmX5u5tF.jpg','<p>In this article, we will study about the Special Functions that are used to solve questions in Engineering mathematics for <a href=\"https://mindvis.in/courses/gate-2018-mechanical-engineering-online-course\" target=\"_blank\">GATE Mechanical Engineering </a>and other competitive engineering exams like UPSC ESE, ISRO etc.</p>\r\n<p>In solving higher engineering problems, there arises a need to use higher transcendental functions which are of two types:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Function defined by improper integrals, and</li>\r\n<li>Functions defined by convergent infinite series, which are solutions of linear differential equations.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Gamma Function</strong></p>\r\n<p>The Gamma function is denoted as,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5CGamma%20%5Cleft(%20p%20%5Cright)\" alt=\"\" />, is defined by integral,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5CGamma%20p%20%3D%20%5Cint%5Climits_0%5E%5Cinfty%20%7Bt%5E%7Bp-1%7D%20e%5E%7B%20-%20t%7D%20dt%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;, p&gt;0.</p>\r\n<p>The Gamma function is known as Euler\'s integral of the second kind. Replace \'p\' by \'p+1\' in the integral above, and this will result in,</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5CGamma%20%5Cleft%20(p%2B1%20%5Cright)%3D%5Cint%5Climits_0%5E%5Cinfty%20%7Bt%5E%7Bp%7D%20e%5E%7B%20-%20t%7D%20dt%7D%20%3D%20p%20%5CGamma%20p\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p><strong>Recurrence relation or reduction formula:</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5CGamma%20%5Cleft%20(1%20%5Cright)%3D1\" alt=\"\" /></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5CGamma%20%5Cleft%20(2%20%5Cright)%20%3D%201%20%5CGamma%20%5Cleft%20(1%20%5Cright)%20%3D%201!\" alt=\"\" /></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5CGamma%203%20%3D%202%20%5CGamma%202%20%3D%202!\" alt=\"\" /></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5CGamma%204%20%3D%203%20%5CGamma%203%20%3D%203!\" alt=\"\" /></strong></p>\r\n<p>Generally,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5CGamma%20n%20%3D%20(n-1)%20%5CGamma%20(n-1)%20%3D%20(n-1)(n-2)!%20%3D%20(n-1)(n-2)....2.1%20%3D%20(n-1)!\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>The above equation is the recurrence relation for the gamma function. It is also called \'<strong>generalized factorial function</strong>\'.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Gamma function for negative non-integer values:</strong></p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%20p%20%5CGamma%20p%20%3D%20%5CGamma%20(p%2B1)\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;can be rewritten as,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5CGamma%20p%20%3D%20%5Cfrac%7B%5CGamma%20(p%2B1)%7D%7Bp%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>Let&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=p%20%5Crightarrow%200%5E%7B%2B%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;and&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=p%20%5Crightarrow%200%5E%7B-%7D\" alt=\"\" />, we get</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5CGamma%200%5E%7B%2B%7D%20%3D%20%5Cfrac%20%7B%5CGamma%201%7D%7Bp%7D%20%3D%20%5Cfrac%20%7B1%7D%7Bp%7D%20%3D%20%2B%20%5Cinfty%20\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;as&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=p%20%5Crightarrow%200%5E%7B%2B%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5CGamma%200%5E%7B-%7D%3D%5Cfrac%7B%5CGamma%201%7D%7Bp%7D%3D%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7Bp%7D%3D-%20%5Cinfty\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;as&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=p%20%5Crightarrow%200%5E%7B-%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>The above relation shows that&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5CGamma%200\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;is undefined. From this, it follows that&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5CGamma%20(-1)\" alt=\"\" />,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5CGamma%20(-2)\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;etc. are all undefined. So, for any real p&lt;0 except p = 0, -1, -2 ....we have the below given relation,</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5CGamma%20p%20%3D%20%5Cfrac%7B%5CGamma%20(p%2Bk%2B1)%7D%7Bp(p%2B1)(p%2B2)...(p%2Bk)%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p><strong>The Gamma function is defined and continuous for any p &gt;0, and it is undefined and discontinuous for p = 0, -1, -2, -3...</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"/uploads/images/defd-5HBVzHye.PNG\" alt=\"\" width=\"316\" height=\"366\" /></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Some standard results:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5CGamma%20(1%2F2)%20%3D%20%5Csqrt%20%7B%5Cpi%7D\" alt=\"\" /></strong></li>\r\n<li><strong><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5CGamma%20(3%2F2)%20%3D%20%5Cfrac%20%7B%5Csqrt%7B%5Cpi%7D%7D%7B2%7D%20%3D%200.886\" alt=\"\" /></strong></li>\r\n<li><strong><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5CGamma%20(-1%2F2)%20%3D%20-2%20%5Csqrt%20%7B%5Cpi%7D%7D%20%3D%20-3.544\" alt=\"\" /></strong></li>\r\n<li><strong><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5CGamma%20(-3%2F2)%20%3D%20%5Cfrac%7B4%7D%7B3%7D%20%5Csqrt%20%7B%5Cpi%7D%20%3D%202.363\" alt=\"\" /></strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Beta function</strong></p>\r\n<p>The beta function is denoted by&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=B(p%2Cq)\" alt=\"\" />, a function of two variables p and q, and is defined by the integral</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=B(p%2Cq)%3D%5Cint%5Climits_0%5E1%20%7Bt%5E%7Bp%20-%201%7D%20(1-t)%5E%7Bq%20-%201%7D%20dt%7D\" alt=\"\" />, where p&gt;0 and q&gt;0.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Although there are many special functions, but for the purpose of GATE, these many are more than enough for you to know and remember.&nbsp;</p>',0,'',274,5,2,22,'gate mechanical revision notes, gate mechanical free notes, gate mechanical free preparation, gate mechanical online preparation, gate 2018 mechanical online course, gate 2018 online notes','In this article, we will study about the Special Functions that are used to solve questions in Engineering mathematics for GATE Mechanical Engineering and other competitive engineering exams like UPSC ESE, ISRO etc.',1),(578,'2017-01-16 08:24:48','2017-07-07 00:20:14','Practice question on free damped vibrations','question','practice-question-on-free-damped-vibrations','/uploads/images/practice-question-on-free-damped-vibrations-Y25PT2ri.PNG','<p>A machine of mass 20 kg is mounted on a spring and a dashpot as shown in the figure. The total spring stiffness is 10 N/mm and the total damping is 0.15 Ns/mm. If the system is initially at rest and a velocity of 100 mm/sec is imparted to the mass, the determine</p>\r\n<p>(i) displacement and velocity of mass as a function of time, and</p>\r\n<p>(ii) displacement and velocity at time equal to one second</p>',0,'',185,5,2,21,'gate mechanical practice questions, gate mechanical free questions, gate mechanical free preparation, gate mechanical online preparation, gate 2018 mechanical online course, gate 2018 online questions','Practice this question on free damped vibrations in the subject of mechanical vibrations. ',1),(579,'2017-01-17 09:17:43','2017-07-10 11:54:10','GATE Mechanical Engineering Notes on Mechanical Vibrations','article','gate-mechanical-engineering-notes-on-mechanical-vibrations','/uploads/images/gate-mechanical-engineering-notes-on-mechanical-vibrations-oIBOf7VU.jpg','<p>In this article, we will list the motion and frequency equations for important vibratory systems asked in <a href=\"https://mindvis.in/courses/gate-2018-mechanical-engineering-online-course\" target=\"_blank\">GATE Mechanical Engineering</a> and other UPSC competetive exams.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>1)&nbsp;<strong>Spring mass system:</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"/uploads/images/sdq-b30TPRs6.PNG\" alt=\"\" width=\"112\" height=\"146\" /></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Equation of motion:&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=m%20%5Cddot%20x%20%2B%20kx%20%3D0\" alt=\"\" /></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Frequency equation:&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>(a)&nbsp;</strong>neglecting spring mass,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Comega_%7Bn%7D%3D%5Csqrt%7B%5Cfrac%7Bk%7D%7Bm%7D%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p><strong>(b)&nbsp;</strong>considering spring mass,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Comega_%7Bn%7D%3D%5Csqrt%20%7B%5Cfrac%7Bk%7D%7Bm%2B%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B3%7D%20m_%7Bs%7D%7D%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>2)&nbsp;<strong>Bifilar suspension:</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"/uploads/images/aqa-LtGYSCEB.PNG\" alt=\"\" width=\"112\" height=\"132\" /></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Equation of motion:&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cfrac%7BW%7D%7B3g%7D%20b%5E%7B2%7D%20%5Cddot%20%5Ctheta%20%2B%20%5Cfrac%7BWa%5E%7B2%7D%7D%7Bl%7D%20%5Ctheta%20%3D0\" alt=\"\" /></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Frequency equation:&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Comega_%7Bn%7D%20%3D%20%5Cfrac%7Ba%7D%7Bb%7D%20%5Csqrt%20%7B%5Cfrac%7B3g%7D%7Bl%7D%7D\" alt=\"\" /></strong></p>\r\n<p>3)&nbsp;<strong>Trifilar suspension:</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"/uploads/images/saqs-PtSpLyY7.PNG\" alt=\"\" width=\"126\" height=\"141\" /></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Equation of motion:&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cfrac%7BW%7D%7Bg%7D%20K%5E%7B2%7D%20%5Cddot%20%5Ctheta%20%2B%20%5Cfrac%20%7BWb%5E%7B2%7D%7D%7Bl%7D%20%5Ctheta%20%3D0\" alt=\"\" /></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Frequency motion:&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Comega_%7Bn%7D%3D%5Csqrt%7B%5Cfrac%7Bb%5E%7B2%7Dg%7D%7BK%5E%7B2%7Dl%7D%7D%2C%20K%5E%7B2%7D%3D%5Cfrac%7BR%5E%7B2%7D%7D%7B2%7D\" alt=\"\" /></strong></p>\r\n<p>4)&nbsp;<strong>Simply supported beam carrying central load:</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"/uploads/images/ssb-QMHE0Qg3.PNG\" alt=\"\" width=\"214\" height=\"69\" /></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Equation of motion:&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cfrac%7BW%7D%7Bg%7D%20%5Cddot%20x%20%2B%20%5Cfrac%7B48EI%7D%7Bl%5E%7B3%7D%7D%20x%20%3D0\" alt=\"\" /></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Frequency equation:&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Comega_%7Bn%7D%20%3D%20%5Csqrt%20%7B%5Cfrac%7B48EIg%7D%7BWl%5E%7B3%7D%7D%7D\" alt=\"\" /></strong></p>\r\n<p>5)&nbsp;<strong>Simply supported beam carrying UDL:</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"/uploads/images/sds-oEWSHHE8.PNG\" alt=\"\" width=\"234\" height=\"104\" /></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Equation of motion:&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cfrac%7Bwl%7D%7Bg%7D%20%5Cddot%20x%20%2B%20%5Cfrac%7B384%20EI%7D%7B5l%5E%7B3%7D%7D%20x%3D0\" alt=\"\" /></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Frequency equation:&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Comega_%7Bn%7D%3D%5Csqrt%7B%5Cfrac%7B384EIg%7D%7B5wl%5E%7B4%7D%7D%7D\" alt=\"\" /></strong></p>\r\n<p>6)&nbsp;<strong>Fixed beam carrying central load:</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"/uploads/images/sdsa-nqQgcEgE.PNG\" alt=\"\" width=\"216\" height=\"72\" /></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Equation of motion:&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cfrac%7BW%7D%7Bg%7D%20%5Cddot%20x%20%2B%20%5Cfrac%20%7B192EI%7D%7Bl%5E%7B3%7D%7D%20x%20%3D0\" alt=\"\" /></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Frequency equation:&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Comega_%7Bn%7D%20%3D%20%5Csqrt%20%7B%5Cfrac%7B192EIg%7D%7BWl%5E%7B3%7D%7D%7D\" alt=\"\" /></strong></p>\r\n<p>7)&nbsp;<strong>Spring mass pulley system:</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"/uploads/images/dsd-T8yonCcS.PNG\" alt=\"\" width=\"142\" height=\"130\" /></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Equation of motion:&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=(mr%5E%7B2%7D%20%2B%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B2%7D%20Mr%5E%7B2%7D)%20%5Cddot%20%5Ctheta%20%2B%20kr%5E%7B2%7D%20%5Ctheta%20%3D0\" alt=\"\" /></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Frequency equation:&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Comega_%7Bn%7D%3D%5Csqrt%20%7B%5Cfrac%7Bk%7D%7Bm%2B%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B2%7D%20M%7D%7D\" alt=\"\" /></strong></p>\r\n<p>8)&nbsp;<strong>Simple pendulum with rod mass:</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"/uploads/images/dsds-zuCLE7lJ.PNG\" alt=\"\" width=\"90\" height=\"124\" /></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Equation of motion:&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=(m%2B%5Cfrac%7BM%7D%7B3%7D)l%5E%7B2%7D%20%5Cddot%20%5Ctheta%20%2B%20(m%2B%5Cfrac%7BM%7D%7B2%7D)%20gl%20%5Ctheta%20%3D0\" alt=\"\" /></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Frequency equation:&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Comega_%7Bn%7D%20%3D%20%5Csqrt%20%7B%20%5Cfrac%7Bm%2B%5Cfrac%7BM%7D%7B2%7D%7D%7Bm%2B%5Cfrac%7BM%7D%7B3%7D%7D%7D%20%5Ctimes%20%5Csqrt%20%7B%5Cfrac%7Bg%7D%7Bl%7D%7D\" alt=\"\" /></strong></p>\r\n<p>9)&nbsp;<strong>Compound pendulum:</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"/uploads/images/fdfdd-v8j3AZk5.PNG\" alt=\"\" width=\"98\" height=\"141\" /></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Equation of motion:&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=J_%7Bo%7D%20%5Cddot%20%5Ctheta%20%2B%20mgl%20%5Ctheta%20%3D0%2C%20J_%7Bo%7D%3DmK%5E%7B2%7D\" alt=\"\" /></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Frequency equation:&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Comega_%7Bn%7D%3D%5Csqrt%7B%5Cfrac%7Bgl%7D%7BK%5E%7B2%7D%2Bl%5E%7B2%7D%7D%7D\" alt=\"\" /></strong></p>\r\n<p>10)&nbsp;<strong>Conical pendulum:</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"/uploads/images/dsdsd-4uXBjAOM.PNG\" alt=\"\" width=\"155\" height=\"125\" /></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Equation of motion:&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=ml%5E%7B2%7D%20cos%20%5Ctheta%20%5Cddot%20%5Ctheta%20%2B%20mgl%20%5Ctheta%20%3D0\" alt=\"\" /></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Frequency equation:&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Comega_%7Bn%7D%3D%5Csqrt%20%7B%5Cfrac%7Bg%7D%7Bl%20cos%20%5Ctheta%7D%7D\" alt=\"\" /></strong></p>',0,'',578,5,2,21,'gate mechanical practice questions, gate mechanical revision notes, gate mechanical free notes, gate mechanical free preparation, gate mechanical online preparation, gate 2018 mechanical online course, gate 2018 online notes','In this article as short notes for GATE Mechanical Engineering, we will study the equations of motion and frequency for commonly used vibratory systems. ',1),(581,'2017-01-19 03:59:36','2017-07-08 00:57:56','GATE Mechanical Notes on Complex functions-Part 1','article','gate-mechanical-notes-on-complex-functions-1','/uploads/images/short-notes-on-complex-functions-for-gate-engineering-mathematics-part-1-wtIvK1wQ.jpg','<p>In this article, we will study about the functions of complex variable which is a topic in which most of the students find difficulty in understanding. These short notes for <a href=\"https://mindvis.in/courses/gate-2018-mechanical-engineering-online-course\" target=\"_blank\">GATE Mechanical </a>can also be used for exams like <a href=\"https://mindvis.in/courses/upsc-ese-mechanical-engineering-2017-online-prep-course\" target=\"_blank\">UPSC ESE</a>, ISRO etc.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Most of you who are reading this article are already familiar with the basics of complex numbers, meaning of real and imaginary parts. So we will straight away jump to the geometrical interpretations of complex numbers.</p>\r\n<p>If \'z\' and \'a\' are points in the complex place&nbsp;<strong>C</strong> the distance between them is&nbsp;<strong><em>d(z,a)=|z-a|.</em></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Set of points</strong></p>\r\n<p>By a set of points we mean a collection of points in the complex plane&nbsp;<strong>C.</strong></p>\r\n<p>For example:&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=S_%7B1%7D%3D%7Bz%20%5Cepsilon%20C%20%7C%20%7Ciz-a%7C%3D%5Crho%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;is called a circle with centre \'a\' and radius&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Crho\" alt=\"\" />.</li>\r\n<li><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=S_%7B2%7D%3D%5Bz%20%5Cepsilon%20C%20%7C%20Re(z)%3E0%5D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;is called a right half plane.</li>\r\n<li>The set of all points z for which&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%7Cz-z_%7Bo%7D%7C%3C%20%5Cdelta\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;where&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cdelta\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;is a positive constant, is called neighbourhood of&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=z_%7Bo%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;and is written&nbsp;<strong>nbd of&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=z_%7Bo%7D\" alt=\"\" /></strong></li>\r\n<li>The set of all points z for which&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=0%3C%7Cz-z_%7Bo%7D%7C%3C%20%5Cdelta\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;is called&nbsp;<strong>deleted nbd of&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=z_%7Bo%7D\" alt=\"\" />.</strong></li>\r\n<li>The set of all points z for which&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%7Cz-z_%7Bo%7D%7C%3C%20%5Crho\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;is called an&nbsp;<strong>open circular disc.</strong></li>\r\n<li>The set of all points z for which&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%7Cz-z_%7Bo%7D%7C%20%5Cleq%20%5Crho\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;is called a&nbsp;<strong>closed circular disc.</strong></li>\r\n<li>The set of all points z such that&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Crho_%7B1%7D%20%3C%20%7Cz-z_%7Bo%7D%7C%20%3C%20%5Crho_%7B2%7D%20\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;where&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Crho_%7B1%7D%3C%20%5Crho_%7B2%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;is called an&nbsp;<strong>open annulus.</strong></li>\r\n<li>The set of all points z such that&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Crho_%7B1%7D%20%5Cleq%20%7Cz-z_%7Bo%7D%7C%20%5Cleq%20%5Crho_%7B2%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;where&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Crho_%7B1%7D%20%3C%20%5Crho_%7B2%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;is called a&nbsp;<strong>closed annulus.</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>A point&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=z_%7Bo%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;is called an interior point of a set S if there is a nbd of&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=z_%7Bo%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;containing only the points of S.&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Open Set:</strong></p>\r\n<p>A set S is called an open set if every point of S has a&nbsp;<strong>nbd&nbsp;</strong>every point of which belongs to S.</p>\r\n<p>Example:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The points inside a circle.</li>\r\n<li>The points inside a square.</li>\r\n<li>Right half plane Re(z) =x &gt; 0.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Open half plane:&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Open upper half plane:&nbsp;</strong>The set of points z such that&nbsp;<strong>Im(z) = y &gt; 0.</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Open lower half plane:&nbsp;</strong>The set of points z such that&nbsp;<strong>Im(z) = y &lt; 0.</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Closed set:</strong></p>\r\n<p>A set S is said to be closed if its complement S\' is open.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Example:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The set of points on and inside the unit circle |z| = 1.&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Bounded set:</strong></p>\r\n<p>A set S is called bounded if all its points lie within a circle of sufficiently large radius.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Example:&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Points in a rectangle, ellipse or polygon.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong><em>Points on a straight line or in an infinite strip do not form a bounded set.</em></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Connected set:</strong></p>\r\n<p>A set S in which any pair of points can be joined by a polygonal arc entirely lying in S, is called a connected set.</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/cvv-YrBz9dag.PNG\" alt=\"\" width=\"199\" height=\"136\" /></p>\r\n<p><strong>Domain:</strong></p>\r\n<p>An open connected set is called a domain.</p>\r\n<p>Example:&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Interior of a circle or a squre or a closed polygon.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Boundary point of a set S:</strong></p>\r\n<p>A point every&nbsp;<strong>nbd&nbsp;</strong>of which contains both points in S and points not in S.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Example:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Points on the two circles&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=C_%7B1%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;and&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=C_%7B2%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;of an annulus.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><em><strong>If S is open, no boundary point belongs to S. If S is closed, every boundary point belongs to S.&nbsp;</strong></em></p>\r\n<p><em><strong><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%7Cz%7C%20%5Cleq%201%3Aclosed\" alt=\"\" />, bounded set</strong></em></p>\r\n<p><em><strong><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=Im(z%5E%7B2%7D)%3Dxy%3E0\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;: Open, unbounded set.</strong></em></p>\r\n<p><em><strong><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Crho_%7B1%7D%20%3C%20%7Cz-z_%7Bo%7D%7C%20%3C%20%5Crho_%7B2%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;: Open, bounded, unconnected set.</strong></em></p>\r\n<p>In the next article, which will be the&nbsp;<strong>Part 2&nbsp;</strong>of the series of short notes on complex functions, we will start with the definition and calculus on Complex functions.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>',0,'',366,5,2,22,'gate mechanical notes, gate mechanical revision notes, gate mechanical free notes, gate mechanical free preparation, gate mechanical online preparation, gate 2018 mechanical online course, gate 2018 online notes, gate mechanical engineering notes','In this article, as GATE Mechanical notes, we will look at the important facts and concepts on Complex Functions.',1),(582,'2017-01-19 05:19:17','2017-07-07 04:08:41','GATE Mechanical Notes on Complex Functions - Part 2','article','gate-mechanical-notes-on-complex-functions-2','/uploads/images/short-notes-on-complex-functions-for-gate-engineering-mathematics-part-2-exTgSGBI.jpg','<p>Before you start with this article, make sure you have gone through the <a href=\"../gate-mechanical-notes-on-complex-functions-1\" target=\"_blank\">Part 1 </a>of this series. In this article, we will start with the definition of Functions of Complex Variables.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Complex function:</strong></p>\r\n<p>Let S be a set of complex numbers. A function&nbsp;<em>f</em> defined on S is a rule that assigns to every z in S a complex number&nbsp;<em>w</em>,&nbsp;called the value of&nbsp;<em>f&nbsp;</em>at z. We write it as:</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=w%3Df(z)\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>z varies in S and is called a complex variable and S is called the domain of definition of&nbsp;<em>f</em>.</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=z%3Dx%2Biy\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=w%3Du(x%2Cy)%2Biv(x%2Cy)\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>Example:</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=w%3Df(z)%20%3Dz%5E%7B2%7D%2B2z\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>Let&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=z%3Dx%2Biy\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;;&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=z%5E%7B2%7D%3D(x%2Biy)%5E%7B2%7D%20%3D%20x%5E%7B2%7D-y%5E%7B2%7D%2B2ixy\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;;&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=2z%20%3D%202x%2Bi2y\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>Therefore,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=w%3Du(x%2Cy)%2Biv(x%2Cy)%3Dx%5E%7B2%7D-y%5E%7B2%7D%2B2x%2Bi(2xy%2B2y)\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=Re(w)%3Du(x%2Cy)%3Dx%5E%7B2%7D-y%5E%7B2%7D%2B2x\" alt=\"\" />;&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=Im(w)%3D2xy%2B2y\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p><strong>Limit of a function</strong></p>\r\n<p>Let f(z) be a function defined in some deleted&nbsp;<strong>nbd&nbsp;</strong>of&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=z_%7Bo%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;and&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=l\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;be a complex number. If for every&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cepsilon%20%3E%200\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;there corresponds a&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cdelta%20%3E0%20\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;such that&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=0%3C%7Cz-z_%7Bo%7D%7C%3C%20%5Cdelta%20\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%7Cf(z)-l%7C%3C%20%5Cepsilon\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>Then we say that f(z) tends to&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=l\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;as&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=z\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;tends to&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=z_%7Bo%7D\" alt=\"\" />. We write it as,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Clim_%7Bz%20%5Cto%20z_%7Bo%7D%7D%20%3D%20l\" alt=\"\" />.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Continuity at&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=z_%7Bo%7D\" alt=\"\" /></strong></p>\r\n<p>Let f(z) be defined in a nbd of&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=z_%7Bo%7D\" alt=\"\" />. If&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Clim_%7Bz%20%5Cto%20z_%7Bo%7D%7D%20f(z)%3Df(z_%7Bo%7D)\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;then we say that f is continuous at&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=z_%7Bo%7D\" alt=\"\" />.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Differentiability&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p>A complex function f(z) is said to be differentiable at a point&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=z_%7Bo%7D\" alt=\"\" />, if the limit&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=f\'(z_%7Bo%7D)%3D%5Clim_%7Bz%20%5Cto%20z_%7Bo%7D%7D%20%5Cfrac%20%7Bf(z)-f(z_%7Bo%7D%7D%7B%5CDelta%20z%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>exists. The limit&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=f\'(z_%7Bo%7D)\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;is called the derivative of f(z) at&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=z_%7Bo%7D\" alt=\"\" />. Putting&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5CDelta%20z%20%3D%20z-%20z_%7Bo%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;we can write the limit as follows:</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=f\'(z_%7Bo%7D)%3D%20%5Clim_%7Bz%20%5Cto%20z_%7Bo%7D%7D%20%5Cfrac%7Bf(z)-f(z_%7Bo%7D)%7D%7Bz-z_%7Bo%7D%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p><strong>Note:</strong></p>\r\n<p>In real calculus, there are two directions -<strong>right side and left side&nbsp;</strong>to approach a point&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=x_%7Bo%7D\" alt=\"\" />. The&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Clim_%7Bx%20%5Cto%20x_%7Bo%7D%7D%20f(x)\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;exists iff,</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>right side limit&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Clim_%7Bx%20%5Cto%20x_%7Bo%7D%5E%7B%2B%7D%7D%20f(x)\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;exists</li>\r\n<li>left side limit&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Clim_%7Bx%20%5Cto%20x_%7Bo%7D%5E%7B-%7D%7D%20f(x)\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;exists</li>\r\n<li>both are equal</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>But in case of complex numbers the situation is different. One can approah a point&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=z_%7Bo%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;in the complex plane from any of the infinite number of directions. The above limit must exist and be the same when we approach&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=z_%7Bo%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;in any of these directions.&nbsp;<em>All the complex valued functions whose real valued counterparts are differentiable are differentiable.&nbsp;</em></p>\r\n<p><strong>Example 1:</strong></p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cbar%7Bz%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;is not differentiable at any point z.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>\r\n<p>Let&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=f(z)%3D%5Cbar%7Bz%7D%3Dx-iy\" alt=\"\" />. We can write&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5CDelta%20z%20%3D%20%5CDelta%20x%20%2B%20i%20%5CDelta%20y\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cfrac%20%7Bf(z%2B%5CDelta%20z)-f(z)%7D%7B%5CDelta%20z%7D%3D%5Cfrac%20%7B%5Cbar%7Bz%2B%5CDelta%20z%7D-%5Cbar%7Bz%7D%7D%7B%5CDelta%20z%7D%3D%5Cfrac%7B%5Cbar%7B%5CDelta%20z%7D%7D%7B%5CDelta%20z%7D%3D%5Cfrac%7B%5CDelta%20x%20-i%20%5CDelta%20y%7D%7B%5CDelta%20x%20%2B%20i%20%5CDelta%20y%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>If&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5CDelta%20y%20%3D0\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;this gives +1 and if&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5CDelta%20x%20%3D0\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;then the result is -1. Thus the above equation approaches +1 along path I but -1 along path II.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/aqaq-aQaxKYt1.PNG\" alt=\"\" width=\"286\" height=\"182\" /></p>\r\n<p>Thus the limit of above equation as&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5CDelta%20z%20%5Cto%200\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;does not exist at any point z.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Analytic Functions:&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p>A function f(z) is said to be analytic in a domain D if f(z) is defined and differentiable at all points of D. The function f(z) is said to be analytic at a point&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=z%3Dz_%7Bo%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;in D if f(z) is analytic in a&nbsp;<strong>nbd&nbsp;</strong>of&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=z_%7Bo%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;in D.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Analytic functions are also termed as \'Regular\' and \'Holomorphic\' functions. The fact that a function f(z) is holomorphic in a domain D is expressed as&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=f%20%5Cepsilon%20H(D)\" alt=\"\" />.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Cauchy Riemann Equations:</strong></p>\r\n<p>The Cauchy Riemann equations (CREs) give us a test for the analyticity of a complex function</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=w%3Df(z)%3Du(x%2Cy)%2Biv(x%2Cy)\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>f is analytic in a domain D iff,</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>the first partial derivative of u, v exist and are continuous in domain D, and</li>\r\n<li>u, v satisfy the C-R equations,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cfrac%7B%5Cpartial%20u%7D%7B%5Cpartial%20x%7D%3D%5Cfrac%7B%5Cpartial%20v%7D%7B%5Cpartial%20y%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;and&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cfrac%7B%5Cpartial%20u%7D%7B%5Cpartial%20y%7D%3D%20-%20%5Cfrac%7B%5Cpartial%20v%7D%7B%5Cpartial%20x%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;in D.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>If&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=f(z)%3Du(x%2Cy)%2Biv(x%2Cy)\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;is differentiable at z then at this point the first order partial derivatives of u and v exist and satisfy the CREs.</strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>If two real valued functions u(x,y) and v(x,y) of two real variables x and y have continuous first partial derivatives that satisfy CREs in some domain D, then the complex function&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=f(z)%3Du(x%2Cy)%2Biv(x%2Cy)\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;is analytic in D.&nbsp;</strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>Let&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=f(z)%3Du(x%2Cy)%2Biv(x%2Cy)\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;be differentiable in a domain D. Then the CREs can be put in a complex form as&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=f_%7Bx%7D%3D-i%20f_%7By%7D\" alt=\"\" />, where&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=f_%7Bx%7D%3Du_%7Bx%7D%2Biv_%7Bx%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;and&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=f_%7By%7D%3Du_%7By%7D%2Biv_%7By%7D\" alt=\"\" /></strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Cauchy-Riemann equations in Polar form:</strong></p>\r\n<p>If&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=f(z)%3Du(r%2C%20%5Ctheta)%2Biv(r%2C%20%5Ctheta)\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;is differentiable at&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=z%3Dre%5E%7Bi%20%5Ctheta%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;then&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cfrac%20%7B%5Cpartial%20u%7D%7B%5Cpartial%20r%7D%3D%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7Br%7D%20%5Cfrac%7B%5Cpartial%20v%7D%7B%5Cpartial%20%5Ctheta%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;and&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cfrac%7B%5Cpartial%20v%7D%7B%5Cpartial%20r%7D%3D-%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7Br%7D%5Cfrac%7B%5Cpartial%20u%7D%7B%5Cpartial%20%5Ctheta%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>If&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=f(z)%3Du(x%2Cy)%2Biv(x%2Cy)%20\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;is an analytic function in a domain D then&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=Re(f)%3Du%3Du(x%2Cy)\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;and&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=Im(f)%3Dv%3Dv(x%2Cy)\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;have partial derivatives&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=u_%7Bx%7D%2Cu_%7By%7D%2C%20v_%7Bx%7D%2C%20v_%7By%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;and satisfy the CREs.</li>\r\n<li>The derivative&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=f%5E%7B\'%7D(z)\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;can be calculated using either of the two formulas,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=f%5E%7B\'%7D(z)%3Du_%7Bx%7D%2Biv_%7Bx%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;or&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=f%5E%7B\'%7D(z)%3D-iu_%7By%7D%2Bv_%7By%7D\" alt=\"\" />.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Properties of analytic functions:</strong></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>The sum, the difference, the product and the quotient of analytic functions are analytic.&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li>An analytic function of an analytic function is analytic.</li>\r\n<li>An entire function of an entire function is entire. A function which is analytic in the entire complex plane is called an entire function, e.g.&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=e%5E%7Bz%7D\" alt=\"\" />, polynomial,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=sin(z)%2C%20cos(z)\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;etc.</li>\r\n<li>If f is analytic at a point z = a then f is differentiable at z = a. However the converse is not true.&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>It is known that&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=f(z)%3D%7Cz%7C%5E%7B2%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;is differentiable only at z = 0 and nowhere else. This function is not analytic at z = 0 since according to the definition of analyticity at a point, f must be differentiable not only at z = 0 but at every point of some nbd of 0.</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Milne-Thomson\'s method:</strong></p>\r\n<p>FInd the analytic function f(z) = u + iv where&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=u(x%2Cy)%3De%5E%7Bx%7D(x%20cosy-%20y%20sin%20y)%2B2%20cos%20x%20sinh%20y%2B%203x%5E%7B2%7D-3y%5E%7B2%7D\" alt=\"\" />.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>\r\n<p>Differentiate the above real part w.r.t x and y.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=u_%7Bx%7D%3De%5E%7Bx%7D%20(x%20cos%20y-%20y%20sin%20y%2Bcos%20y)%20%2B%202%20cos%20x%20sin%20h%20y%20%2B%203x%5E%7B2%7D-3y%5E%7B2%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=u_%7By%7D%3De%5E%7Bx%7D(-x%20sin%20y%20-%20sin%20y%20-%20y%20cos%20y)%20%2B%202%20sin%20x%20cos%20h%20y-%206xy%2B1\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>It is known that,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=f%5E%7B\'%7D(z)%3Du_%7Bx%7D%2Biv_%7Bx%7D%3Du_%7Bx%7D-iu_%7By%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>Replace x by z and y by 0 in the above equations and put them in&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=f%5E%7B\'%7D(z)\" alt=\"\" />.</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=f%5E%7B\'%7D(z)%3De%5E%7Bz%7D(z.1-0)%2Be%5E%7Bz%7D(1)%2B0%2B3z%5E%7B2%7D-0-2i%20sin%20z%20-%20i\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>To get the value of f(z), integrate the above equation w.r.t z.</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=f(z)%3D2e%5E%7Bz%7D-e%5E%7Bz%7D%2Be%5E%7Bz%7D%2Bz%5E%7B3%7D%2B2i%20cos%20z%20-iz%2Bc\" alt=\"\" />.</p>\r\n<p>In the next article, we will look at Complex intgerals.&nbsp;</p>',0,'',261,5,2,22,'gate mechanical notes, gate mechanical revision notes, gate mechanical free notes, gate mechanical free preparation, gate mechanical online preparation, gate 2018 mechanical online course, gate 2018 online notes, gate mechanical engineering notes','In this article we will learn the basic Analytic functions in Complex variables in the topic of Engineering Mathematics for GATE Mechanical Engineering. ',1),(583,'2017-01-21 08:15:53','2017-07-08 04:00:19','Solve this question on heat transfer','question','solve-this-question-on-heat-transfer-gGoJJUIt','/uploads/images/solve-this-question-on-heat-transfer-DBaMyUfF.jpg','<p>Solve this on heat transfer</p>',0,'',220,5,2,4,' questions for gate, gate MECHANICAL engineering, gate question bank','Solve this problem on heat transfer section in GATE. ',1),(584,'2017-01-26 07:19:20','2017-03-21 12:14:22','Properties of Cast Iron-Short notes on Material Science for GATE Mechanical Engineering','article','properties-of-cast-iron-short-notes-on-material-science-for-gate-mechanical-engi','','<p>In this article, which can be used as short notes on GATE Mechanical Engineering, we will look at properties of Cast Iron.</p>\r\n<p>Cast Iron is an alloy, which is composed of iron and carbon. It is formed by melting pig iron with coke and limestone in a furnace. It contains about 2-4% of C and small amounts of Si, Mg, Sulphur and phosphorus. Carbon exists in CI usually in two forms:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Graphite</li>\r\n<li>Cementite</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><strong>Properties of CI:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>It has high compressive strength</li>\r\n<li>It has high casting characters</li>\r\n<li>It is highly wear resistant</li>\r\n</ul>',0,'',12,5,2,16,'','',0),(585,'2017-01-30 07:52:04','2017-07-06 19:06:37','GATE Mechanical notes for Punching Operation','article','gate-mechanical-notes-on-punching-operation','/uploads/images/short-notes-for-punching-operation-in-sheet-metal-process-for-gate-mechanical-engineering-igFpVMV7.png','<p>In this article, as short notes for <a href=\"https://mindvis.in/courses/gate-2018-mechanical-engineering-online-course\" target=\"_blank\">GATE Mechanical Engineering</a>, we will look at the important facts and concepts on Sheet Metal processes mainly shearing processes. This can be used well for GATE Mechanical Engineering preparation. The figure below gives an outline of the sheet metal processes.</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/sqsdvfg-nhc3o5YH.PNG\" alt=\"\" width=\"419\" height=\"297\" /></p>\r\n<p>The&nbsp;<em>shearing&nbsp;</em>process consists of cutting sheet metal, including plates, bars and tubing of different cross sections, into individual pieces by utilizing shearing stresses the direction of thickness, by using a device called&nbsp;<strong>punch&nbsp;</strong>and a&nbsp;<strong>die.&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/sheasqr-1-yAE7zVdE.PNG\" alt=\"\" width=\"376\" height=\"144\" /></p>\r\n<p>In the above figure, the parameter&nbsp;<strong>\'c\'</strong> is the main factor in determining the shape and quality of the sheared edge. As seen in the figure below, the edges become rougher as the clearance increases with the deformation zone becoming larger.&nbsp;<em>If the value of clearance becomes too large, the sheet metal is bent and is subjected to tensile stresses.</em></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Typically, the value of clearance ranges between 2-8% of the sheet thickness but may be as small as 1% in fine blanking.&nbsp;</strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>For softer materials, the clerance is lower and it increases as the sheet thickness increases.&nbsp;</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>-<img src=\"../../uploads/images/sdbfr-4uLTVUe3.PNG\" alt=\"\" width=\"406\" height=\"151\" /></p>\r\n<p>The parameters of consideration in the shearing process are the following:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>punch force</li>\r\n<li>speed of the punch</li>\r\n<li>edge condition of the sheet</li>\r\n<li>punch and die materials</li>\r\n<li>the corner radii of punch and die</li>\r\n<li>punch clearance, and</li>\r\n<li>lubrication</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Check out the figure below to understand the sheared edge for two sheared surfaces. It may be noted that the edges are neither smooth nor perpendicular to the plane of the sheet.</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/shear-2-Arg0HpLE.PNG\" alt=\"\" width=\"378\" height=\"203\" /></p>\r\n<p>Shearing usually starts with crack formation on top and bottom surfaces of the sheet. These cracks eventually meet and results in complete separation of the material, thus creating a&nbsp;<strong>rough fracture surface.&nbsp;</strong>The&nbsp;<strong>shiny or burnished&nbsp;</strong>surfaces are formed due to the contact and rubbing of the sheared edges against the punch and the die.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>The ratio of burnished to rough areas increases by increasing the sheet metal ductility and decreases by increasing sheet thickness and clearance.&nbsp;</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>The figure above also shows the formation of&nbsp;<strong>burr.&nbsp;</strong>The burr height increases with increasing clearance and increasing the ductility of the material.&nbsp;<em>Tool with blunt edges is also a major cause for burr creation.&nbsp;</em></p>\r\n<p>The punch force, F, is the product of shear strength of the sheet material and the cross sectional area being sheared.&nbsp;<em>The presence of friction between the punch and the sheet can increase this force considerably.&nbsp;</em>An emperical formula, as given below can be used to estimate the&nbsp;<strong>maximum punch force,</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=F_%7Bmax%7D%3D0.7(UTS)tL\" alt=\"\" /></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Where UTS is the ultimate tensile strength of the material, t is the sheet thickness and L is the total length of the sheared edge.&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>For punching a round hole of diameter D,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=L%3D%5Cpi%20D\" alt=\"\" />.&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li>In addition to the punch force, an additional force is also needed to strip the sheet from the punch during its return stroke. It is very difficult to estimate.&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>',0,'',316,5,2,9,'gate mechanical notes, gate mechanical revision notes, gate mechanical free notes, gate mechanical free preparation, gate mechanical online preparation, gate 2018 mechanical online course, gate 2018 online notes, gate mechanical engineering notes, gate 20','In this article, as GATE Mechanical notes, we will look at the important facts and concepts on Sheet Metal processes mainly shearing processes.',1),(586,'2017-02-02 06:36:29','2017-07-10 10:10:59','Notes on Prehistoric Era in History Section for IBPS PO and SSC exams','article','notes-on-prehistoric-era-in-history-section-for-ibps-po-and-ssc-exams','/uploads/images/notes-on-prehistoric-era-in-history-section-for-ibps-po-and-ssc-exams-Zqu9pUqc.jpg','<p><strong>In this article on Prehistoric Era we will look at the&nbsp;Paleolithic Period&nbsp;specifically. This article can be used as a helpful resource for preparation of <a href=\"https://mindvis.in/courses/ibps-prelims-exams\" target=\"_blank\">IBPS PO</a>, banking exams, SSC CGL, SSC JE and other government exams.&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p>Generally, the prehistoric era (until c. 1750 BCE) of South Asia is divided into three major parts. These parts are Stone Age, Indus Valley Civilization &amp; Dravidian Origins. So, in this article we focus on Stone Age. &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Stone Age was a prehistoric cultural phase or level of human development which is known for the creation and use of stone tools. The origin of Stone Age coincides with the discovery of the oldest known stone tools. Which is about 3.3 million (33 Lakhs) years old. Further based on the advancement and use of tools this era is divided into three separate periods &ndash; Paleolithic Period, Mesolithic Period and Neolithic Period. So, before considering these different periods, take a quick look on the chart given below: -</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/qaz-p9I3BB49.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"373\" height=\"298\" /></p>\r\n<p>So, let&rsquo;s observe all these periods in detail.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Paleolithic Period</strong> (2 million BC &ndash; 10,000 BC)</p>\r\n<p>Paleolithic is basically concerned with the origins and development of early human culture. In this period, the first appearance of man is found as a tool-using mammal. During this period man was a food gatherer, largely depends upon hunting wild animals and birds, fishing &amp; collecting wild fruits, nuts and berries.</p>\r\n<p>During this period human developed four important traditions of manufacturing stone tools. These are as follows: -</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Pebble-tool</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<img src=\"../../uploads/images/cv-QPJ8ly9Q.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"145\" height=\"179\" /></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Bifacial tool, or hand-ax tool</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<img src=\"../../uploads/images/1-3f18Fxjq.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"414\" height=\"266\" />&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Flake-tool</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<img src=\"../../uploads/images/4-cF0sJgho.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"453\" height=\"236\" /></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Blade-tool</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<img src=\"../../uploads/images/3-xNGhx1O9.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"303\" height=\"412\" /></p>\r\n<p>So, these different types of tools were used by ancient humans. Now let&rsquo;s see the important points related with Paleolithic Culture: -</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>As per research it is found that in India first human occupation was started in the middle Paleolithic period.</li>\r\n<li>During Paleolithic period, large portion of earth was covered by ice sheets.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Paleolithic sites are mainly found in hilly area, why? As we all know during this period human use tools made up of stone and they easily get stones which are suitable for making their tools in these areas.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Fire, tools made up of lime stone etc. were also invented in this period.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Important Paleolithic sites are :\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Bhimbetka (M.P)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<img src=\"../../uploads/images/2-BYXZF5Ql.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"331\" height=\"245\" />&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Hunsgi</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<img src=\"../../uploads/images/5-owp4Mm5a.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"215\" height=\"300\" /></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Kurnool Caves</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<img src=\"../../uploads/images/7-BTrUc7TZ.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"480\" height=\"360\" /></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Narmada Valley (Hathnora, M.P)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<img src=\"../../uploads/images/8-tkeRqhtm.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"495\" height=\"336\" /></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Kaladgi Basin.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<img src=\"../../uploads/images/6-QziMqFML.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"498\" height=\"371\" />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The Paleolithic age in India is further divided into three stages. These are: -</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Lower Paleolithic or early stone age (5 lakh- 50,000 years back) &ndash; This era was largely covered by ice age. The Early Old Stone age have begun in Africa around 20 lakh years ago, but as per archeological survey of India the stone age in India is not older than 6 lakh years. In this era people use tools like hand axes, cleavers &amp; choppers. The stone tools were mainly used for chopping, skinning and digging. Important site of lower Paleolithic age in India are: -\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Lidder river Pahalgam, (Kashmir)</li>\r\n<li>Sohan valley, Punjab (Pakistan)</li>\r\n<li>Thar Desert</li>\r\n<li>Banks of River Beas, Banganga, Haryana</li>\r\n<li>Chittorgarh and Kota, Rajasthan</li>\r\n<li>Belan valley Mirzapur, UP</li>\r\n<li>Bhimbetka, MP</li>\r\n<li>River Sabarmati and Mahi Basins (Rajasthan &amp; Gujarat)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Middle Paleolithic: - Till the 1960s the Middle Paleolithic age was not recognized. It was established only in the 1960s and was named as Nevasan after the type-site of Nevasa in Maharashtra. The major tools were blades, points, bores and scrapers which were generally made of flakes. In assessment to the lower Paleolithic era, the tools in middle Paleolithic era became smaller, thinner and lighter. Due to this, middle Paleolithic period is also known as Flake took industry.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;Important Middle Paleolithic Sites in India are: -</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Budha Pushkar in Rajasthan</li>\r\n<li>Narmada river and their tributaries in central India which also include Bhimbetka.</li>\r\n<li>Chota Nagpur plateau</li>\r\n<li>Deccan plateau</li>\r\n<li>Eastern Ghats</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Upper Paleolithic &ndash; This is the last phase of stone age as well as ice age. There were very important changes happened in the climate which had its impact on the distribution and living ways of the humans. The occurrence of modern human who are well known as Homo sapiens is also noted in this era. Some important changes in this era are as follows: -</li>\r\n<li>Climate was extremely cold and dry in the high altitude and northern latitudes.</li>\r\n<li>Deserts are formed in North west India.</li>\r\n<li>Coastal areas of south-eastern Tamil Nadu, Saurashtra and Kutch developed quartz and carbonated dunes because of the lowering of the sea level.</li>\r\n<li>Due to the harsh and dry environmental condition, the vegetation was scant though the faunal fossils show occurrence of grasslands.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Important archaeological sites of this age are:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Balan valley</li>\r\n<li>Son valley</li>\r\n<li>Orissa</li>\r\n<li>Eastern Ghats in Andhra Pradesh</li>\r\n<li>Chota Nagpur plateau in Bihar</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>So, this was all about Paleolithic period. As we have already mentioned in the tree diagram, there are two more stages in which stone age is divided, one is Mesolithic and another is Neolithic. We will look at these two stages in the next article.&nbsp;</p>',0,'',396,5,223,26,'short notes for bank exams, ibps exam notes, history notes for ibps po, history notes for Ssc cgl, history notes for ssc cgl, free preparation for bank preparation','In this article on Prehistoric Era we will look at the Paleolithic Period specifically. This article can be used as a helpful resource for preparation of IBPS PO, banking exams, SSC CGL, SSC JE and other government exams. ',1),(587,'2017-02-13 06:26:43','2017-07-10 07:42:31','GATE Mechanical Notes on Fluid Mechanics','article','gate-mechanical-notes-fluid-mechanics','/uploads/images/gate-mechanical-notes-on-fluid-mechanics-M9iky8Vd.png','<p><a href=\"https://mindvis.in/courses/gate-2018-mechanical-engineering-online-course\" target=\"_blank\"><strong>GATE Mechanical</strong></a> Notes can come in handy while preparing for <a href=\"https://mindvis.in/courses/gate-2019-mechanical-engineering\" target=\"_blank\">GATE Mechanical Engineering exam</a>. In this article, we will list all formulas for the section of Fluid Statics section of the subject of Fluid Mechanics.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Density, Specific Volume, Specific Weight and Specific Gravity</strong></p>\r\n<p>Density,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Crho%20%3D%20lim_%7B%5CDelta%20V%5Cto%200%7D%20%5CDelta%20m%20%2F%20%5CDelta%20V\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>Specific Volume,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=v%20%3D%20%20lim_%7B%5CDelta%20V%5Cto%200%7D%20%5CDelta%20W%20%2F%20%5CDelta%20V\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>Specific Weight,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=w%20%3D%20lim_%7B%5CDelta%20V%5Cto%200%7D%20g%20%5CDelta%20m%20%2F%20%5CDelta%20V%20%3D%20%5Crho%20g\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>Specific Gravity,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=SG%3D%5Crho%20%2F%20%5Crho_%7Bw%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>Where&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Crho\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;= density of the fluid, and&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Crho_%7Bw%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;= density of water = 1000 kg/m<sup>3</sup>.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Stress, Pressure and Viscosity</strong></p>\r\n<p>Stress,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Ctau(P)%3D%20lim_%7B%5CDelta%20A%5Cto%200%7D%20%5CDelta%20F%20%2F%20%5CDelta%20A\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>Where&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Ctau(P)\" alt=\"\" />=surface stress vector at point P,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5CDelta%20F\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;= force acting on infinitesimal area&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5CDelta%20A\" alt=\"\" />, and&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5CDelta%20A\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;= infinitesimal area at point P.</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Ctau_%7Bn%7D%3D-p\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Ctau_%7Bt%7D%3D%5Cmu%20(du%2Fdy)\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>Where,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Ctau_%7Bn%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;= normal stress and&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Ctau_%7Bt%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;= tangential stress components at point P.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>p = pressure at point P,</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cmu\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;= absolute dynamic viscosity of the fluid in&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=N.s%2Fm%5E%7B2%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>du = velocity at boundary condition, and&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>dy = normal distance measured from boundary.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Also in terms of Kinematic viscosity,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cnu%20%3D%20%5Cmu%20%2F%20%5Crho\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>For a thin Newtonian fluid film and a linear profile,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=v(y)%3DVy%2F%5Cdelta%20\" alt=\"\" />,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=du%2Fdy%20%3D%20V%2F%20%5Cdelta\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>where&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=V\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;= velocity of plate on film and&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cdelta\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;= thickness of fluid film.</p>\r\n<p>For a power law (non-Newtonian) fluid,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Ctau_%7Bt%7D%3DK(du%2Fdy)%5E%7Bn%7D\" alt=\"\" />, where K = consistency index, and n = power law index. If n1 then the fluid is dilatant.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Surface tension and capillarity</strong></p>\r\n<p>Surface tension&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Csigma\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;is the force per unit contact length. Mathematically,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Csigma%20%3D%20F%2FL\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;where&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Csigma\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;= surface tension in N/m, F = surface force at the interface and L = length of interface.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The capillary rise,&nbsp;<strong>h&nbsp;</strong>is approximated by the mathematical formula&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=h%3D%5Cfrac%7B4%20%5Csigma%20cos%20%5Cbeta%7D%7B%5Crho%20g%20d%7D\" alt=\"\" />,&nbsp;where &nbsp;h = height of the liquid in the vertical tube,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Csigma\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;= surface tension,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cbeta\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;= the angle made by the liquid with the wetted tube wall, d = diameter of the capillary tube.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Pressure field in a static field</strong></p>\r\n<p>As per the figure given below, the relation between the pressures is given as&nbsp;<strong>Absolute pressure = atmospheric pressure + gauge pressure reading</strong> in case of positive pressures and&nbsp;<strong>Absolute pressure = atmospheric pressure - vacuum gauge pressure.</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"../../uploads/images/gate-mechanical-notes-relation-in-absolute-and-gauge-pressure-OYVO7Kfl.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"545\" height=\"261\" /></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Forces on submerged surfaces and the center of pressure</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"../../uploads/images/gate-mechanical-notes-submerged-surfaces-fSNO8bUN.PNG\" alt=\"\" width=\"331\" height=\"165\" /></strong></p>\r\n<p>A = total area of inclined surface</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cbar%7Bh%7D%7B\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;= depth of CG of inclined area from free surface</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=h%5E%7B*%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;= distance of centre of pressure from free surface of liquid</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Ctheta\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;= Angle made by the plane of trhe surface with free liquid surface</p>\r\n<p>O-O is the axis perpendicular to the plane of the surface.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cbar%7By%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;= distance of the CG of the inclined surface from O-O</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=y%5E%7B*%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;= distance of the centre of pressure from O-O</p>\r\n<p>Consider a small strip of area dA at a depth h from free surface and at a distance y from the axis O-O as shown the figure above.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Pressure intensity on the strip,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=p%3D%5Crho%20g%20h\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>Pressure force, dF on the strip, dF = p x area of the strip =&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Crho%20gh%20%5Ctimes%20dA\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>Total pressure force on the whole area,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=F%20%3D%20%5Cint%20F%20%3D%5Cint%20%5Crho%20gh%20dA\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>From the geometry of the figure, we can see,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cfrac%7Bh%7D%7By%7D%3D%5Cfrac%7B%5Cbar%7Bh%7D%7D%7B%5Cbar%7By%7D%7D%3D%5Cfrac%7Bh%5E%7B*%7D%7D%7By%5E%7B*%7D%7D%3Dsin%20%5Ctheta\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>Which gives us&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=h%3Dy%20sin%20%5Ctheta\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>Therefore,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=F%20%3D%20%5Cint%20%5Crho%20g%20%5Ctimes%20y%20%5Ctimes%20sin%20%5Ctheta%20%5Ctimes%20dA%20%3D%20%5Crho%20g%20sin%20%5Ctheta%20%5Cint%20y%20dA\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>It is known that,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cint%20y%20dA%20%3D%20A%20%5Cbar%7By%7D\" alt=\"\" />, where&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cbar%7By%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;= distance of CG from axis O-O.</p>\r\n<p>Therefore,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=F%3D%5Crho%20g%20A%20%5Cbar%7Bh%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>To calculate the position of centre of pressure (<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=h%5E%7B*%7D\" alt=\"\" />), we make use of the following mathematical relation,&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=h%5E%7B*%7D%3D%5Cfrac%7BI_%7BG%7Dsin%5E%7B2%7D%5Ctheta%7D%7BA%5Cbar%7Bh%7D%7D%2B%5Cbar%7Bh%7D\" alt=\"\" />, where&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=I_%7BG%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;= MOI of inclined surfaces about an axis passing through G and parallel to O-O.</p>\r\n<p>In the next article on GATE Mechanical Short notes, we will look at the section of Fluid dynamics from the subject of Fluid Mechanics.&nbsp;</p>',0,'',849,5,2,5,'gate mechanical notes, gate mechanical revision notes, gate mechanical free notes, gate mechanical free preparation, gate mechanical online preparation, gate 2018 mechanical online course, gate 2018 online notes, gate mechanical engineering notes','In this article, as GATE Mechanical notes, we will look at the important facts and concepts on Fluid Statics from Fluid Mechanics.',1),(588,'2017-02-24 06:28:44','2017-07-10 04:48:37','GATE Mechanical Notes on Fluid dynamics','article','gate-mechanical-notes-fluid-dynamics','/uploads/images/gate-mechanical-notes-on-fluid-dynamics-dXxEL4a6.jpg','<p>In the previous article on <a href=\"post/gate-mechanical-notes-fluid-mechanics\" target=\"_blank\">GATE Mechanical Notes on Fluid Mechanics</a>, we listed important relations from the section of fluid statics. In this article on Fluid Mechanics, we will continue on to important relations for fluid dynamics which will be very helpful when revising for <a href=\"https://mindvis.in/courses/gate-2018-mechanical-engineering-online-course\" target=\"_blank\">GATE Mechanical Engineering</a>.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>One dimensional flows</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>The continuity equation</strong>:&nbsp;So long as the flow Q is continuous, the&nbsp;<em>continuity equation,&nbsp;</em>as applied to one-dimensional flows, states that the flow passing two points (1 and 2) in a stream is equal at each point,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=A_%7B1%7DV_%7B1%7D%3DA_%7B2%7DV_%7B2%7D\" alt=\"\" />.</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=Q%3DAV\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cdot%7Bm%7D%3D%5Crho%20Q%20%3D%5Crho%20AV\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=Q%20\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;= volumetric flow rate</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cdot%20%7Bm%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;= mass flow rate</p>\r\n<p>A = cross sectional area of flow</p>\r\n<p>V = average flow velocity, and&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Crho\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;= fluid density</p>\r\n<p><strong>The field equation&nbsp;</strong>is derived when the energy equation is applied to one dimensional flows. Assuming no friction losses and that no pump or turbine exists between the sections 1 and 2 of a system,&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cfrac%7Bp_%7B2%7D%7D%7Bw%7D%2B%5Cfrac%7BV_%7B2%7D%5E%7B2%7D%7D%7B2g%7D%2Bz_%7B2%7D%3D%5Cfrac%7Bp_%7B1%7D%7D%7Bw%7D%2B%5Cfrac%7BV_%7B1%7D%5E%7B2%7D%7D%7B2g%7D%2Bz_%7B1%7D\" alt=\"\" />, where</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=p_%7B1%7D\" alt=\"\" />,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=p_%7B2%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;= pressure at sections 1 and 2</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=V_%7B1%7D\" alt=\"\" />,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=V_%7B2%7D%20\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;= average velocity of the fluid at the sections</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=z_%7B1%7D\" alt=\"\" />,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=z_%7B2%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;= the vertical distance from a datum to the sections (the potential energy)</p>\r\n<p>w = the specific weight of the fluid</p>\r\n<p><strong>Fluid flow</strong></p>\r\n<p>The velocity distribution for&nbsp;<strong>laminar flow&nbsp;</strong>in circular tubes or between planes is given by the formula,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=v%3Dv_%7Bmax%7D%5B1-(r%2FR)%5E%7B2%7D%5D\" alt=\"\" />, where</p>\r\n<p>r = the distance from the centreline,</p>\r\n<p>R = the radius of the tube or half the distance between the parallel planes</p>\r\n<p>v = the local velocity at \'r\' and</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=v_%7Bmax%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;= the velocity at the centreline of the duct&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=v_%7Bmax%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;= 1.18 V, for a fully turbulent flow (Re&gt;10,000)</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=v_%7Bmax%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;= 2 V, for circular tubes in laminar flow and</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=v_%7Bmax%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;= 1.5 V, for parallel planes in laminar flow, where&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>V = the average velocity in the duct</p>\r\n<p>The shear stress distribution is:&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cfrac%7B%5Ctau%7D%7B%5Ctau_%7Bw%7D%7D%3D%5Cfrac%7Br%7D%7BR%7D\" alt=\"\" />, where</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Ctau\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;and&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Ctau_%7Bw%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;are the shear stresses at radii r and R respectively.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The&nbsp;<em><strong>drag force&nbsp;</strong></em><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=F_%7BD%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;on objects immersed in a large body of flowing fluid or objects moving through a stagnant fluid is given by,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=F_%7BD%7D%3D%5Cfrac%7BC_%7BD%7D%5Crho%20V%5E%7B2%7D%20A%7D%7B2%7D\" alt=\"\" />, where</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=C_%7BD%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;= the drag coefficient&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>V = the velocity of the undisturbed fluid, and</p>\r\n<p>A = projected area of the blunt objects such as spheres, ellipsoids, disks and plates, cylinders, ellipses and air foils with axes perpendicular to the flow.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>For flat plates placed parallel with the flow:</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=C_%7BD%7D%3D1.33%2FRe%5E%7B0.5%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=(10%5E%7B4%7D%3CRe%3C5%20%5Ctimes%2010%5E%7B5%7D)\" alt=\"\" /></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=C_%7BD%7D%3D0.031%2FRe%5E%7B1%2F7%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=(10%5E%7B6%7D%20%3C%20Re%20%3C10%5E%7B9%7D)\" alt=\"\" /></strong></p>\r\n<p><em>The characteristic length in the Reynold\'s number (Re) is the length of the plate parallel with the flow. For blunt objects, the characteristic length is the largest linear dimension (diameter of cylinder, sphere, disk etc.) which is perpendicular to the flow.&nbsp;</em></p>\r\n<p><strong>Hydraulic Gradient Line (HGL)</strong></p>\r\n<p>The hydraulic gradient line is defined as an imaginary line above a pipe so that the vertical distance from the pipe axis to the line represents the&nbsp;<em>pressure head&nbsp;</em>at that point.&nbsp;<em><strong>If a row of piezometers were placed at intervals along the pipe, the HGL would join the water levels in the piezometer water columns.&nbsp;</strong></em></p>\r\n<p><strong>Energy Line (Bernoulli Equation)</strong></p>\r\n<p>The Bernoulli equation states that the sum of pressure, velcoity and elevation head is constant. The energy line this sum or the total head line above a horizontal datum.&nbsp;<strong><br /></strong></p>\r\n<p><em><strong>The difference between the HGL and the energy line is the&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=V%5E%7B2%7D%2F2g\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;term.&nbsp;</strong></em></p>\r\n<p><strong>Steady, Incompressible flow in conduits and pipes:</strong></p>\r\n<p>The energy equation for an incompressible flow is as follows:</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cfrac%7Bp_%7B1%7D%7D%7Bw%7D%2Bz_%7B1%7D%2B%5Cfrac%7BV_%7B1%7D%5E%7B2%7D%7D%7B2g%7D%3D%5Cfrac%7Bp_%7B2%7D%7D%7Bw%7D%2Bz_%7B2%7D%2B%5Cfrac%7BV_%7B2%7D%5E%7B2%7D%7D%7B2g%7D%2Bh_%7Bf%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>where&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=h_%7Bf%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;= head loss due to friction losses and all other losses.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>If the cross section and the elevation of the pipe are equal at both sections 1 and 2, then &nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=V_%7B1%7D%3DV_%7B2%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;and&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=z_%7B1%7D%3Dz_%7B2%7D\" alt=\"\" />. The pressure drop&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=p_%7B1%7D-p_%7B2%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;is then given as:</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=p_%7B1%7D-p_%7B2%7D%3Dwh_%7Bf%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>The <strong>Darcy-Weisbach</strong>&nbsp;equation is&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=h_%7Bf%7D%3D%5Cfrac%7BfLV%5E%7B2%7D%7D%7B2gD%7D\" alt=\"\" />, where&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>f = the Moody or Darcy friction factor = f(Re, e/D)</p>\r\n<p>D = diameter of the pipe</p>\r\n<p>L = length over which the pressure drop occurs</p>\r\n<p>e = roughness factor for the pipe</p>\r\n<p><strong><em>A chart that gives \'f\' versus Re for various values of e/D, is known as the Moody or Stanton diagram</em></strong>.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Friction factor for Laminar flow:</strong></p>\r\n<p>The equation for Q in terms of the pressure drop&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5CDelta%20p_%7Bf%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;is the&nbsp;<strong>Hagen-Poiseuille&nbsp;</strong>equation. The relation given below is only valid for flow in the laminar region.</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=Q%20%3D%20%5Cfrac%7B%5Cpi%20R%5E%7B4%7D%20%5CDelta%20p_%7Bf%7D%7D%7B8%20%5Cmu%20L%7D%3D%5Cfrac%7B%5Cpi%20D%5E%7B4%7D%20%5CDelta%20p_%7Bf%7D%7D%7B128%20%5Cmu%20L%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p><strong>Flow in non-circular conduits:</strong></p>\r\n<p>Analysis of flow in conduits having a non-circular cross section uses the hydraulic diameter&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=D_%7BH%7D\" alt=\"\" />, or the hydraulic radius&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=R_%7BH%7D\" alt=\"\" />.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=R_%7BH%7D%3D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;cross sectional area / wetted perimeter =&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=D_%7BH%7D%2F4\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>Make a note of the above points on Fluid dynamics in detail. These notes can be very well used for revision for <a href=\"https://mindvis.in/courses/gate-2018-mechanical-engineering-online-course\" target=\"_blank\">GATE </a><a href=\"https://mindvis.in/courses/gate-2019-mechanical-engineering\" target=\"_blank\">Mechanical Engineering</a>, <a href=\"https://mindvis.in/courses/upsc-ese-mechanical-engineering-2017-online-prep-course\" target=\"_blank\">UPSC ESE</a> and other competetive exams for Mechanical Engineering.&nbsp;</p>',0,'',333,5,2,5,'gate mechanical notes, gate mechanical revision notes, gate mechanical free notes, gate mechanical free preparation, gate mechanical online preparation, gate 2018 mechanical online course, gate 2018 online notes, gate mechanical engineering notes','In this article, as GATE Mechanical notes, we will look at the important facts and concepts on Fluid Dynamics from Fluid Mechanics.',1),(589,'2017-02-27 08:46:48','2017-07-10 11:58:33','GATE Mechanical Questions on Basics of SOM','article','gate-mechanical-practice-questions-som','/uploads/images/gate-mechanical-questions-on-basics-of-som-NzUTi5bb.png','<p>Practice these important questions for <a href=\"https://mindvis.in/courses/gate-2018-mechanical-engineering-online-course\" target=\"_blank\">GATE Mechanical Engineering</a> on the topic of basics of Strength of Materials.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Q1) A cantilever OP is connected to another beam PQ with a pin joint as shown in the figure. A load of 10kN is applied at mid-point of PQ. The magnitude of bending moment in kNm at fixed end O is</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/gate-mechanical-som-questions-1-UDtxl1X2.PNG\" alt=\"\" width=\"352\" height=\"82\" /></p>\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: lower-alpha;\">\r\n<li>2.5</li>\r\n<li>5</li>\r\n<li>10</li>\r\n<li>25</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>Q2) Two planes AB and BC which are at right angles are acted upon by tensile stress of 140MPa and a compressive stress of 70MPa respectively and also by shear stress 35MPa. Determine the principal stresses and the principal planes. Find also the maximum shear stress and planes on which they act.</p>\r\n<p>Q3) A steel bolt of diameter 10 mm passes through a brass tube of ID 15 mm and OD 25 mm. The bolt is tightened by a nut so that the length of tube is reduced by 1.5 mm. If the temperature of the assembly is raised by&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=40%5E%7Bo%7DC\" alt=\"\" />, estimate the axial stresses in the bolt and the tube before and after heating. Material properties for steel and brass are:</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=E_%7Bs%7D%3D2%20%5Ctimes%2010%5E%7B5%7D%20MPa\" alt=\"\" />,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Calpha_%7Bs%7D%3D1.2%20%5Ctimes%2010%5E%7B-5%7D%2FC\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=E_%7Bb%7D%3D1%20%5Ctimes%2010%5E%7B5%7D%20MPa\" alt=\"\" />,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Calpha_%7Bb%7D%3D1.9%20%5Ctimes%2010%5E%7B-5%7D%2FC\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>Q4) For the state of plane stress shown in the figure below, the maximum and minimum principal stresses are:</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/gate-mechanical-som-questions-4-eqfGO85I.PNG\" alt=\"\" width=\"222\" height=\"154\" /></p>\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: lower-alpha;\">\r\n<li>60MPa and 30MPa</li>\r\n<li>50MPa and 10MPa</li>\r\n<li>40MPa and 20MPa</li>\r\n<li>70MPa and 30MPa</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>Q5) Which of the following is true?</p>\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: lower-alpha;\">\r\n<li><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=0%3C%5Cmu%20%3C%20-1%2F2\" alt=\"\" /></li>\r\n<li><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=1%20%3C%20%5Cmu%20%3C0\" alt=\"\" /></li>\r\n<li><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=1%3C%20%5Cmu%20%3C%20-1\" alt=\"\" /></li>\r\n<li><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cinfty%20%3C%20%5Cmu%20%3C%20-%5Cinfty\" alt=\"\" /></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>Q6) Bending moment M and torque T is applied on a solid circular shaft. If the maximum bending stress equals to maximum shear stress developed, then M is equal to</p>\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: lower-alpha;\">\r\n<li>T/2</li>\r\n<li>T</li>\r\n<li>2T</li>\r\n<li>4T</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>Q7) A vertical hanging bar of length L and weighing w N/unit length carries a load W at the bottom. The tensile force in the bar at a distance y from the support will be given by</p>\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: lower-alpha;\">\r\n<li>W+wL</li>\r\n<li>W+w(L-y)</li>\r\n<li>(W+w)y/L</li>\r\n<li>W+W(L-y)/w</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>Q8) In the case of bi-axial state of normal stresses, the normal stress on&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=45%5E%7Bo%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;plane is equal to</p>\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: lower-alpha;\">\r\n<li>the sum of the normal stresses&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li>differences of the normal stresses</li>\r\n<li>half the sum of the normal stresses</li>\r\n<li>half the difference of the normal stresses</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>Q9) The temperature stress is a function of&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Coeffiecient of linear expansion</li>\r\n<li>Temperature rise</li>\r\n<li>Modulus of elasticity</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>The correct answer is&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: lower-alpha;\">\r\n<li>1 and 2 only</li>\r\n<li>1 and 3 only</li>\r\n<li>2 and 3 only</li>\r\n<li>1, 2 and 3</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>Q10) Principal stresses at a point in a plane stressed element are&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Csigma_%7Bx%7D%3D%5Csigma_%7By%7D%3D500%20kg%2Fcm%5E%7B2%7D\" alt=\"\" />. Normal stress on the plane inclined at&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=45%5E%7Bo%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;to x-axis will be</p>\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: lower-alpha;\">\r\n<li>0</li>\r\n<li>500 kg/cm<sup>2</sup></li>\r\n<li>707 kg/cm<sup>2</sup></li>\r\n<li>1000 kg/cm<sup>2</sup></li>\r\n</ol>',0,'',425,5,2,6,'gate mechanical notes, gate mechanical revision notes, gate mechanical free notes, gate mechanical free preparation, gate mechanical online preparation, gate 2018 mechanical online course, gate 2018 online notes, gate mechanical engineering notes ','GATE Mechanical Engineering practice questions for Strength of Materials basic concepts. ',1),(590,'2017-03-02 06:19:12','2017-07-08 16:47:06','Probability Notes for IBPS and SSC CGL','article','probability-notes-for-bank-ssc-exams','/uploads/images/probability-notes-for-ibps-and-ssc-cgl-sZzlfyOq.jpg','<p>In this article, we will study Probability for Banking and SSC CGL exams from the Quantitative Aptitude section.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The word probability is very frequently used in our daily life. We usually say, \'<strong>He may come today</strong>\' or \'<strong>probably it may rain today</strong>\' or \'<strong>most probably I will clear the exam</strong>\'. Look at all these phrases and you will realise they contain an element of uncertainity. So to measure these uncertainities, we use the concept of probability. In simple words, probability is a quantitative measure of the certainity.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The concept of probability has its origins in games of chance, where the outcome of a trial in unknown and uncertain. In the current scenario, concepts of probability have made their way in the world of business and commerce.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Some important terms to be used while learning probability.</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>1. Random experiment or trial:&nbsp;</strong>The performance of an experiment is called a trial. An experiment is defined by the property that the observations of an experiment under a set of conditions do not always lead to the same observed result, but rather to the different outcomes.&nbsp;<em><strong>If in an experiment, all the possible outcomes are already known and none of the outcomes can be predicted with certainity, then such an experiment is known as Random Experiment.&nbsp;</strong></em>For example, tossing a coin or throwing a die are termed as random experiments.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>2.Event:&nbsp;</strong>The possible outcome of an experiment is called an&nbsp;<strong>event.&nbsp;</strong>The events are depicted with the help of capital letters, A, B, C etc.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>For example:&nbsp;<em><strong>when a coin is tossed the outcome of getting a head or a tail is an event.&nbsp;</strong></em></p>\r\n<p><strong>3. Sample space:&nbsp;</strong>It is a set of all possible outcomes of an event. It is denoted by letter S.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>For example:&nbsp;<em><strong>when a coin is tossed, S={H,T}, where H = head, T = tail.&nbsp;</strong></em></p>\r\n<p><em><strong>When two coins are tossed, S={HH, TT, HT, TH}</strong></em></p>\r\n<p><strong>4. Equally likely events:&nbsp;</strong>Events are said to be equally likely if there is no preference of any one event to occur in preference to the other. In simple words, equally likely events mean that outcome is as likely to occur as any other outcome.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>For example:&nbsp;<em><strong>when a die is thrown, all the 6 faces {1,2,3,4,5,6} are equally likely to occur.&nbsp;</strong></em></p>\r\n<p><strong>5. Exhaustive events:&nbsp;</strong>It is the total number of all possible outcomes of any trial.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>For example:&nbsp;<em><strong>when a coin is tossed, either head or tail may turn up and therefore, there are two exhaustive cases.&nbsp;</strong></em></p>\r\n<p><em><strong>there are 6 exhaustive cases or events in throwing a die.&nbsp;</strong></em></p>\r\n<p><em><strong>if 2 dice are thrown simultaneously, there are 36 exhaustive cases. Similarly in case of 3 dice thrown simultaneously, 216 exhaustive events are there.&nbsp;</strong></em></p>\r\n<p><strong>6. Algebra of Events:&nbsp;</strong>Let us say, A and B are two events with sample space A, then</p>\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: lower-roman;\">\r\n<li><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=A%20%5Ccup%20B\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;is the event that either A or B or both occur.</li>\r\n<li><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=A%20%5Ccap%20%20B\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;is the event that A and B both occur simultaneously.</li>\r\n<li><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Coverline%7BA%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;is the event that A does not occur.&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Coverline%7BA%7D%20%5Ccap%20%5Coverline%7BB%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;is an event of non-occurence of both A and B, i.e. none of the events A and B occurs.&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>For example:&nbsp;<strong><em>In a single throw of a die, let A be the event of getting an odd&nbsp;number and B be the event of getting a number greater than 2. Then, A = {1,3,5} and B = {3,4,5,6}, therefore&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=A%20%5Ccup%20B\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;= {1,3,4,5,6}.&nbsp;</em></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong><em><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=A%20%5Ccup%20B\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;is the event of getting an odd number or a number greater than 2.&nbsp;</em></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong><em><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=A%20%5Ccap%20B\" alt=\"\" />={3,5} is the event of getting an odd number and a number greater than 2.&nbsp;</em></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong><em><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Coverline%20%7BA%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;= {2,4,6} is the sample space of elements which are not a part of A or the event of not getting an odd number.&nbsp;</em></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong><em><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Coverline%20%7BB%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;= {1,2} is the event of not getting number greater than 2.&nbsp;</em></strong></p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Coverline%20%7BA%7D%20%5Ccap%20%5Coverline%20%7BB%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;=&nbsp;<strong>{2}&nbsp;<em>is the event of neither getting an odd number nor a number greater than 2.&nbsp;</em></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>7. Mutually Exclusive Events:&nbsp;</strong>If in an experiment, an event rules out the happening of the all other events in the same experiment.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>For example:&nbsp;<em><strong>when a coin is tossed either head or tail will appear. Head and tail cannot appear simultaneously in this case. So, occurence of head or tail are called two mutually exclusive events.&nbsp;</strong></em></p>\r\n<p><strong>POINT TO REMEMBER:&nbsp;<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">A and B are two mutually exclusive events, which means&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=A%20%5Ccap%20B%20%3D%20%5Cphi\" alt=\"\" />, i.e. A and B are disjoint sets.</span></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>8. Mutually Exclusive and Exhaustive Events:&nbsp;</strong>Events&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=E_%7B1%7D%2C%20E_%7B2%7D%2C...E_%7Bn%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;are mutually exclusive and exhaustive if&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=E_%7B1%7D%20%5Ccup%20E_%7B2%7D%20%5Ccup%20E_%7B3%7D...%20%5Ccup%20E_%7Bn%7D%3DS\" alt=\"\" />, and&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=E_%7Bi%7D%20%5Ccap%20E_%7Bj%7D%20%3D%20%5Cphi\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;for all&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=i%20%5Cneq%20j\" alt=\"\" />.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>For example:&nbsp;<em><strong>in a single throw of a die, let A be the event of getting an even number and B be event of getting odd numbers, then A = {2,4,6}, B = {1,3,5},&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=A%20%5Ccap%20B%20%3D%20%5Cphi\" alt=\"\" />,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=A%20%5Ccup%20B%20\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;= {1,2,3,4,5,6} = S. Therefore A and B are mutually and exhaustive events.&nbsp;</strong></em></p>\r\n<p><strong>Definition of Probability of an Event:&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p>It is defined in the following two ways:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Mathematical or a priori definition</li>\r\n<li>Statistical or empirical definition</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><strong>Mathematical or a priori definition:&nbsp;</strong>Probability of an event A, which is denoted as P(A) is defined as, P(A) = (Number of cases favorable to A)/(Number of possible outcomes).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>If an event A happens in \'m\' ways and fails, i.e. does not occur in \'n\' ways and each of total \'m+n\' ways is equally likely to occur then the probability of happening of the event A is given by,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=P(A)%3D%5Cfrac%7Bm%7D%7Bm%2Bn%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;and that the probability of non-occurence of the A is given by,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=P(%5Coverline%7BA%7D)%3D%5Cfrac%7Bn%7D%7Bm%2Bn%7D\" alt=\"\" />.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Always remember,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=P(A)%2BP(%5Coverline%7BA%7D)%3D1\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>The probability of an event, defined in the above mentioned way is called Priori Probability, i.e. it is determined before hand, i.e. before the actual trials are done.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Odds of an Event:&nbsp;</strong>Let, there are \'m\' outcomes favourable to a certain event and \'n\' outcomes unfavourable to the event in a sample space, then&nbsp;<strong>odds in favour of the event is given as = (Number of favourable outcomes)/(Number of unfavourable events) = m/n.&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Odds against the event = (Number of unfavourable outcomes)/(Number of favourable outcome) = n/m.</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Fundamental theorems on Probability:</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Theorem 1:&nbsp;</strong> For a random experiment, let S is the sample space and E is an event, then</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>probability of occurence of an event is always non-negative,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=P(E)%20%5Cgeq%200\" alt=\"\" />.</li>\r\n<li>probability of occurence of an impossible event is 0,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=P(%5Cphi)%3D0\" alt=\"\" />.</li>\r\n<li>probability of occurence of a sure event is 1.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><strong>Theorem 2:&nbsp;</strong>Let A and B are two mutually exclusive events, then</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=P(A%20%5Ccap%20B)%3D0\" alt=\"\" />.</li>\r\n<li><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=P(A%20%5Ccup%20B)%3DP(A)%2BP(B)\" alt=\"\" /></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><strong>Theorem 3:&nbsp;</strong>Let A and B are two mutually exclusive and exhaustive events them&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=P(A)%2BP(B)%3D1\" alt=\"\" />.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Theorem 4:&nbsp;</strong>Let A be any event and&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Coverline%7BA%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;be its complimentary event, then&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=P(%5Coverline%7BA%7D)%2BP(A)%3D1\" alt=\"\" />.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Theorem 5:&nbsp;</strong>For any two events A and B,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=P(A-B)%3DP(A)-P(A%20%5Ccap%20B)\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p><strong>Theorem 6:&nbsp;</strong>Addition theorem - For any two events A and B,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=P(A%20%5Ccup%20B)%3DP(A)%2BP(B)-P(A%20%5Ccap%20B)\" alt=\"\" />.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>If A and B are mutually exclusive events, then&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=P(A%20%5Ccap%20B)%3D0\" alt=\"\" />.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Theorem 7:&nbsp;</strong>For three events A, B and C</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=P(A%20%5Ccup%20B%20%5Ccup%20C)%3DP(A)%2BP(B)%2BP(C)-P(A%20%5Ccap%20B)%20-P(B%20%5Ccap%20C)%20-%20P(A%20%5Ccap%20C)%2BP(A%20%5Ccap%20B%20%5Ccap%20C)\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p><strong>Example:&nbsp;</strong>A card is drawn at random from a well-shuffled pack of 52 cards. Find the probability of getting, (i) a jack or a queen or a king, (ii) a two of heart or diamond.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Solution: (i)&nbsp;</strong>In a pack of 52 cards, we have 4 jacks, 4 queens and 4 kings. So, a jack and a queen and a king are mutually exclusive events.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>P(a jack) = 4/52 = 1/13</p>\r\n<p>P(a queen) = 4/52 = 1/13</p>\r\n<p>P(a king) = 4/52 = 1/13</p>\r\n<p>By addition theorem of probability,&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>P(a jack or a queen or a king) = P(a jack) + P(a queen) + P(a king) = 1/13 + 1/13 + 1/13 = 3/13.</p>\r\n<p><strong>(ii)&nbsp;</strong>P(two of heart or two of diamond) = P(two of heart) + P(two of diamond) = 1/52 + 1/52 = 2/52 = 1/26.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Independent events:&nbsp;</strong>Two events A and B are called independent events if the occurence or non-occurence of one does not affect the the probability of occurence of the other.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>For example:&nbsp;<em><strong>in a simultaneous throwing of 2 coins, getting a tail on the first con and getting a head on the second coin are two independent events.&nbsp;</strong></em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>',0,'',422,5,2,24,'ssc notes, ssc cgl notes, free ssc cgl notes, probability notes for ssc cgl, quant notes in ssc cgl exam, ssc cgl exam notes, quantitative aptitude notes for ssc cgl','SSC CGL notes on Probability from Quantitative Aptitude section, a must read article for all SSC CGL exam aspirants.',1),(591,'2017-03-03 02:31:41','2017-07-09 09:52:18','GATE Mechanical Notes - Heat Conduction Basics','article','gate-mechanical-notes-heat-conduction','/uploads/images/gate-mechanical-notes-heat-conduction-basics-SPFLY4F7.jpg','<p>These notes for <a href=\"https://mindvis.in/courses/gate-2018-mechanical-engineering-online-course\" target=\"_blank\">GATE Mechanical Engineering</a> describe all the important fundamentals for heat conduction, from the subject of Heat Transfer.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Heat transfer:&nbsp;</strong>It is defined as the transmission of heat energy from one region to another because of a temperature gradient. There are three modes of heat transfer, (i) Conduction, (ii) Convection and (iii) Radiation. Heat conduction is majorly due to direct physical contact of a higher temperature medium with a lower temperature medium of a same or a different body. Heat convection is due to the property of moving matter (can be natural or forced) to carry heat from a higher temperature region to a lower temperature region. Heat radiation is due to the property of the matter to emit and absorb electromagnetic radiation, even without a carrying medium.</p>\r\n<p>There are two&nbsp;very important terms one should understand while studying heat transfer, and the same can be applied to the above mentioned three modes&nbsp;:</p>\r\n<p>1)&nbsp;<strong>Steady state heat transfer:&nbsp;</strong>In such a heat transfer, the temperature of the body does not vary with respect to time, but it does vary with respect to the position, i.e.&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=dT%2Fdt%3D0\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;and&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=dT%2Fdx%20%5Cneq%200\" alt=\"\" />.</p>\r\n<p>2)&nbsp;<strong>Unsteady state heat transfer:&nbsp;</strong>In such a heat transfer, the temperature of the body varies with respect to both time and position, i.e.&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=dT%2Fdx%20%5Cneq0\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;and&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=dT%2Fdt%20%5Cneq%200\" alt=\"\" />.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Thermal conductivity:</strong></p>\r\n<p>It is a property specific to the material which is carrying heat. It is defined as the amount of energy that can be conducted through a body or medium of unit thickness and unit area in unit time for a temperature difference of&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=1%5E%7Bo%7DC\" alt=\"\" />.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Thermal conductivity of metals and alloys decrease with rise in temperature.</strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>Thermal conductivity of gases increase with rise in temperature.</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Fourier\'s law of heat conduction:</strong></p>\r\n<p>This is the most fundamental laws for heat conduction. This law states that the rate of heat conduction is directly proportional to the surface area (A) in a direction perpendicular to the surface area and temperature gradient (dT/dx). Refer the figure given below.</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/fourier-law-qMLEYFoL.PNG\" alt=\"\" width=\"146\" height=\"173\" /></p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=Q%3D-kA(dT%2Fdx)\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>or&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=q%20%3D%20Q%2FA%3D-k%20(dT%2Fdx)\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>In the above expression,&nbsp;<strong>k&nbsp;</strong>is called the&nbsp;<strong>thermal conductivity&nbsp;</strong>of the material through which heat is flowing. Units of&nbsp;<strong>thermal conductivity&nbsp;</strong>are&nbsp;<strong>kJ/s-mK&nbsp;</strong>or&nbsp;<strong>kW/mK.</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Thermal resistance:</strong></p>\r\n<p>Heat flow can be considered analogous to electric current flow. As per Ohm\'s law for electricity, the current I flowing through a wall of resistance R, as shown in the figure, is proportional to the potential difference V across it.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<img src=\"../../uploads/images/ohms-law-JCrDExXp.PNG\" alt=\"\" width=\"196\" height=\"51\" /></p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=I%3DV%2FR\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>Recognize the following terms and then find the analogous terms in heat conduction:</p>\r\n<p>1) Flow quantity = current (I)&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Crightarrow\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;heat (Q)</p>\r\n<p>2) Potential difference or driving force = V&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Crightarrow\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;temperature difference (dT)</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/thermal-resistance-cvqs4q0X.PNG\" alt=\"\" width=\"200\" height=\"233\" /></p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=Q%3D-kA%20%5Cfrac%7BT_%7B2%7D-T_%7B1%7D%7D%7Bx%7D%3D%5Cfrac%7BT_%7B1%7D-T_%7B2%7D%7D%7B%5Cfrac%7Bx%7D%7BkA%7D%7D%3D%5Cfrac%7BT_%7B1%7D-T_%7B2%7D%7D%7BR_%7Bt%7D%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>Where&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=R_%7Bt%7D%3D%5Cfrac%7Bx%7D%7BkA%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;= Thermal resistance to the heat flow offered by the material of the wall.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Thermal resistance combinations:</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>(a) Series combination:&nbsp;</strong>Refer the figure below.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/thermal-resistance-series-AuCsqcNZ.PNG\" alt=\"\" width=\"175\" height=\"180\" /></p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=(R_%7Bt%7D)_%7Bseries%7D%3DR_%7B1%7D%2BR_%7B2%7D%3D%5Cfrac%7Bx_%7B1%7D%7D%7Bk_%7B1%7DA%7D%2B%5Cfrac%7Bx_%7B2%7D%7D%7Bk_%7B2%7DA%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=Q%3D%5Cfrac%7BT_%7B1%7D-T_%7B2%7D%7D%7B(R_%7Bt%7D)_%7Bseries%7D%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>Let&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=T_%7Bi%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;= temperature of interface and assuming that the rate of heat flow is equal through both the walls in series.</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=T_%7B1%7D-T_%7Bi%7D%3DQR_%7B1%7D%3D%5Cfrac%7BQx_%7B1%7D%7D%7Bk_%7B1%7DA%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>When there are multiple thermal resistances in series, we can write,&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=(R_%7Bt%7D)_%7Bseries%7D%3D%5Csum%20(R_%7Bt%7D)_%7Bi%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%3D%20%5Csum%20_%7Bi%3D1%7D%20%5E%7Bn%7D%20%5Cfrac%7Bx_%7Bi%7D%7D%7Bk_%7Bi%7DA_%7Bi%7D%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;and&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=Q%20%3D%20%5Cfrac%20%7BT_%7B1%7D-T_%7Bn%2B1%7D%7D%7B%5Csum%20%5Cfrac%7Bx%7D%7BkA%7D%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p><strong>(b) Parallel combination:&nbsp;</strong>Refer the figure below for a parallel combination.</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/thermal-resistance-parallel-FPk0Rn0e.PNG\" alt=\"\" width=\"284\" height=\"119\" /></p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=(%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7BR_%7Bt%7D%7D)_%7Bparallel%7D%3D%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7BR_%7B1%7D%7D%2B%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7BR_%7B2%7D%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=(R_%7Bt%7D)_%7Bparallel%7D%3D%5Cfrac%7BR_%7B1%7DR_%7B2%7D%7D%7BR_%7B1%7D%2BR_%7B2%7D%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>Where,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=R_%7B1%7D%3D%5Cfrac%7Bx%7D%7Bk_%7B1%7DA_%7B1%7D%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;and&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=R_%7B2%7D%3D%5Cfrac%7Bx%7D%7Bk_%7B2%7DA_%7B2%7D%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/thermal-resistance-parallel-2-vQ6VPtOd.PNG\" alt=\"\" width=\"212\" height=\"84\" /></p>\r\n<p>Also,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=Q%3D%5Cfrac%7BT_%7B1%7D-T_%7B2%7D%7D%7B(R_%7Bt%7D)_%7Bparallel%7D%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p><strong>(c) Thermal contact resistance:&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p>Due to surface roughness, the contact surfaces touch only at discrete locations. Due to this, the heat flow area at the interface becomes very small as compared to the geometric area of the face which causes large resistance to the heat flow at the interface. This resistance is termed as&nbsp;<strong>thermal contact resistance</strong>. The result of thermal contact resistance is that there is a drop in the temperature at the interface.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><em><strong>The value of thermal contact resistance depends on the metals involved, the roughness of the surfaces, the contact pressure and temperature and the matter occupying the void spaces.&nbsp;</strong></em></p>\r\n<p>This brings us to the end of the notes on Heat Conduction basics. In the next article, we will look at the&nbsp;<strong>Heat conduction through a cylinder.&nbsp;</strong></p>',0,'',477,5,2,4,'gate mechanical notes, gate mechanical revision notes, gate mechanical free notes, gate mechanical free preparation, gate mechanical online preparation, gate 2018 mechanical online course, gate 2018 online notes, gate mechanical engineering notes','In this article, as GATE Mechanical notes, we will look at the important facts and basic concepts on Heat Conduction from Heat Transfer.',1),(592,'2017-03-03 11:49:46','2017-07-10 09:10:09','Indian Geography notes for SSC CGL - Introduction','article','indian-geography-notes-ssc-cgl','/uploads/images/indian-geography-notes-for-ssc-cgl-introduction-ipWaYSCK.jpg','<h1>Indian Geography notes for SSC CGL - Introduction</h1>\r\n<p>Indian Geography is a major part of SSC CGL exam when it comes to the General Studies section. It is also an important part of exam in major civil services examinations. In this article, we will introduce some important facts about Indian Geography like:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li><strong>Location</strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>Size</strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>Indian Standard Meridian</strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>India and neighbors</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><strong>1. India-Location:</strong></p>\r\n<p>Let us get started with the location of India on the world map.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/map-of-word-sFDQkl1X.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"581\" height=\"339\" /></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Out of the two hemispheres, India is entirely a part of the&nbsp;<strong>northern hemisphere.&nbsp;</strong>To be specific, it is located in the&nbsp;<strong>south-central part of Asia.</strong></li>\r\n<li>On a map, India can be located between&nbsp;<strong>latitudes&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=8%5E%7Bo%7D4\'N\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;</strong>and&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=37%5E%7Bo%7D6\'N\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;and&nbsp;<strong>longitudes&nbsp;</strong><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=68%5E%7Bo%7D7\'E\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;and&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=97%5E%7Bo%7D25\'E\" alt=\"\" />. Check out the map below.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><em><strong>The southern boundary on mainland India extends upto&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=6%5E%7Bo%7D45\'N\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;latitude in the Bay of Bengal.</strong></em></p>\r\n<p><strong>2. India - Size</strong>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Talking about size, with an area of&nbsp;<strong>3,287,590 sq.km.</strong>&nbsp;which is <strong>2.4%&nbsp;</strong>of the total geographical area of the world,<strong>&nbsp;</strong>India is the&nbsp;<strong>7th largest&nbsp;</strong>country in the world. The 6 countries, that have a larger geographical area than India are, in decreasing order are:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li><strong>Russia - 17,075,200 sq.km</strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>Canada - 9,984,670 sq.km</strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>USA - 9,826,630 sq.km</strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>China - 9,596,960 sq.km</strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>Brazil - 8,511,965 sq.km</strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>Australia - 7,686,850 sq.km</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The total land boundary of Indian mainland is&nbsp;<strong>15,200 km.&nbsp;</strong></li>\r\n<li>Bay of Bengal is in the&nbsp;<strong>east coast&nbsp;</strong>and Arabian sea is in the&nbsp;<strong>west coast.</strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>North to South</strong> - length of mainland is&nbsp;<strong>3214 km</strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>East to West&nbsp;</strong>- length of mainland os&nbsp;<strong>2933 km</strong></li>\r\n<li>Territorial limit of India extends to sea upto&nbsp;<strong>12 nautical miles (i.e 21.9 km)</strong> from the coast.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/indian-land-distance-BCLOfTnX.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"456\" height=\"569\" /></p>\r\n<p><strong>3. Indian Standard Meridian:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Indian Standard Time&nbsp;</strong>or&nbsp;<strong>IST&nbsp;</strong>is ahead of&nbsp;<strong>Greenwich&nbsp;</strong>or&nbsp;<strong>Prime Meridian (<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=0%5E%7Bo%7D\" alt=\"\" />) Mean Time&nbsp;</strong>by&nbsp;<strong>5 hours 30 minutes.&nbsp;</strong></li>\r\n<li>Indian Standard Meridian passes through&nbsp;<strong>Mirzapur, UP</strong> at&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=82%5E%7Bo%7D30\'E\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;<strong>Meridian.</strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>Tropic of cancer</strong>&nbsp;which is located at <strong>23<sup>0</sup>30&rsquo;N</strong>&nbsp;passes through Gujarat, Madhya Pradesh, Chhattisgarh, Jharkhand, West Bengal, Tripura, and Mizoram.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>4. India and neighboring countries</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>India is a country of&nbsp;<strong>29 States</strong>, <strong>6 Union Territories</strong>, and <strong>1 National Capital Territory&nbsp;</strong>which is also called the&nbsp;<strong>capital of India, i.e. New Delhi</strong>.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The mountain range of Himalayas bound the North and North-East part of India.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>India has Afghanistan and Pakistan as neighnors in the northwest; China, Tibet (China), Nepal, and Bhutan in the north and northeast; and Myanmar and Bangladesh in the east.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Sri Lanka and Maldives are two island nations which are also neighbors on India.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Sri Lanka is located towards the south of India in the Indian Ocean and it is separated by a thin water body namely <strong>Palk Strait</strong>.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>A group of Islands, namely <strong>Maldives</strong>, is located in the Indian Ocean, south of Indian Union Territories i.e. Lakshadweep Islands.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>After introducing the important and basic facts about Indian Geography, let us now move towards next article, in which we learn about the&nbsp;<strong>Physical Aspects of India.&nbsp;</strong></p>',0,'',706,5,20,27,'ssc notes, ssc cgl notes, free ssc cgl notes, indian geography notes for ssc cgl, general studies in ssc cgl exam, ssc cgl exam notes','SSC CGL notes on Indian Geography - Introduction, a must read article for all SSC CGL exam aspirants. ',1),(594,'2017-03-06 07:38:35','2017-07-08 15:24:43','Analytical Reasoning Notes for SSC CGL, IBPS exams','article','analytical-reasoning-notes-ssc-cgl-ibps','/uploads/images/analytical-reasoning-notes-for-ssc-cgl-ibps-exams-MIqC6lg8.jpg','<p>Analytical Reasoning (AR) is an important part of SSC CGL, IBPS and other Government exams. This section examines the analytical and logical thinking capabilities of a candidate. To answer these questions, no specialized knowledge is required for any particular field. Each question has a specific situation which needs to be analysed on its merit and the questions are to be answered as per that.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Each question or a group of questions in AR is based on a passage or a particular set of conditions. When answering such questions, it is always better to create a rough sketch of the information given. Let us now look at an example below to understand how to go about answering such questions in competetive exams like SSC CGL, IBPS PO etc.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Passage:&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p>A particular Mumbai restaurant serves dinner from Tuesday to Sunday. The restaurant is closed on Monday. Five entrees-Indian, Russian, Continental, Chinese and Italian are served each week as per the following conditions or restrictions:</p>\r\n<ul style=\"list-style-type: circle;\">\r\n<li>Indian is served on 3 days of every week, but it is never served on a Friday.</li>\r\n<li>Continental is served on 3 days of each week, but never on consecutuve days.&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li>Italian is served on 1 day of each week.</li>\r\n<li>Chinese is served 5 days of each week.</li>\r\n<li>Indian and Russian are both served on Saturday and Sunday.<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>Not more than 3 different entrees are served on any given day.&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Q1)&nbsp;</strong>Entrees are identical on which of th following pairs of days of the week?</p>\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: lower-alpha;\">\r\n<li>Friday and Sunday</li>\r\n<li>Tuesday and Wednesday</li>\r\n<li>Saturday and Sunday</li>\r\n<li>Wednesday and Friday</li>\r\n<li>Thursday and Friday</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><strong>Q2) </strong>On which days are Indian and Italian both be served?</p>\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: lower-alpha;\">\r\n<li>Tuesday, Thursday</li>\r\n<li>Tuesday, Wednesday and Thursday</li>\r\n<li>Monday, Tuesday and Wednesday</li>\r\n<li>Tuesday, Wednesday, Thursday and Friday</li>\r\n<li>Tuesday, Wednesday, Thursday and Saturday</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><strong>Q3)&nbsp;</strong>If Continental is served on Saturday, which one of the statements is TRUE?</p>\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: lower-alpha;\">\r\n<li>Russian and Continental are both served on Sunday</li>\r\n<li>Russian and Indian are both served on Tuesday</li>\r\n<li>Italian and Indian are both served on Thursday</li>\r\n<li>Chinese and Russian are both served on Saturday</li>\r\n<li>Italian and Russian are both served on Friday</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><strong>Q4)&nbsp;</strong>From the statements given below, which one gives sufficient information to determine that on which days Indian is served?</p>\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: lower-alpha;\">\r\n<li>Continental are served on the same day</li>\r\n<li>Italian and Russian are served on Tuesday</li>\r\n<li>Chinese is served on Saturday, and Italian is served on Tuesday</li>\r\n<li>Continental is served on Saturday, and Russian is served on all but one of the 6 days</li>\r\n<li>Chinese is served on Sunday, and Russian is served on Tuesday and Thursday</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><strong>Understand the Problem:</strong></p>\r\n<p>Let us organize the data given in the question in the form of a matrix or a checkerboard diagram, as shown below. In this we put a \"X\" against the entree if it&nbsp;is not served on a particular day.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Indian is not served on Friday</li>\r\n<li>Indian and Russian are both served on Saturday and Sunday</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/ssc-cgl-analytical-reasoning-1-pIFAIhG9.PNG\" alt=\"\" width=\"318\" height=\"143\" /></p>\r\n<p>Check the above diagram. As per the conditions given, we cannot have more than 3 tick marks per column. So further analysis tells us:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Continental must be served on Saturday or Sunday, but cannot be done on both days. Why so? If you do so, then this entree must will be served on consecutive days, which contradicts the conditions laid out in the question.&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li>Chinese must be served on Tuesday to Friday and on Saturday or Sunday, but cannot be done on both days. Why so? If Chinese is served on 5 of the 6 days, then it must be served on at least one of the two weekend days. Now if Chinese were served on both Saturday and Sunday, then on one of these 2 days 4 entrees (Russian, Italian, Indian and Continental) would be served.&nbsp;<strong>We have established in the above point that Continental must be served either on a Saturday or a Sunday during the week and not on both days, as it would exceed the limit of 3 entrees per day.</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Based on the above analysis, we get the alternatives, as given below:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Continental food is served on Saturday (but not on Sunday), and Chinese food is served on Saturday (but not on Sunday).&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li>Continental is served on Sunday (but not on Saturday), and Chinese food is served on Saturday (but not on Sunday).</li>\r\n<li>Italian cannot be served on either Sunday or Saturday.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>Based on above points, the matrix diagram obtained is:</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/ssc-cgl-analytical-reasoning-2-9lh8cXpv.PNG\" alt=\"\" width=\"327\" height=\"174\" /></p>\r\n<p><strong>Now let us answer the questions:</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Answer 1)&nbsp;</strong>The correct answer is (d).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Answer 2)&nbsp;</strong>The correct answer is (b).</p>\r\n<p><strong>Answer 3)&nbsp;</strong>The correct answer is (e).</p>\r\n<p><strong>Answer 4)&nbsp;</strong>The correct answer is (e).</p>',0,'',341,5,20,12,'ssc notes, ssc cgl notes, free ssc cgl notes, Analytical reasoning notes for ssc cgl, Reasoning in ssc cgl exam, ssc cgl exam notes, reasoning notes for IBPS exams','SSC CGL, IBPS exam notes on Analytical Reasoning (AR), a must read article for all SSC CGL exam aspirants.',1),(595,'2017-03-06 15:54:35','2017-07-09 20:15:36','Exam dates for IBPS 2017 exams','article','exam-dates-ibps-2017-exams','/uploads/images/exam-dates-for-ibps-2017-exams-4mPZ1efx.jpg','<p>IBPS calendar is busy as always in 2017 too. Here is a tentative list of the exam dates for IBPS CWE for RRBs and PSBs.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>1.<strong> <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">RRBs - CWE RRB VI (Officers) and CWE RRB-VI (Office Assistants)</span></strong></p>\r\n<p>Preliminary Examination - Officer Scale I and office assistants:&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>09-09-2017</li>\r\n<li>10-09-2017</li>\r\n<li>16-09-1017</li>\r\n<li>17-09-2017</li>\r\n<li>23-09-2017</li>\r\n<li>24-09-2017</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Single examination -&nbsp;<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Officers Scale II &amp; III</span>:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>05-11-2017</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Main examination -&nbsp;<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Officer Scale I</span>:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>05-11-2017</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Main examination -&nbsp;<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Office Assistants</span>:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>12-11-2017</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;2.&nbsp;<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><strong>PSBs - CWE PO/MT - VII &amp; CWE Clerk - VII</strong></span></p>\r\n<p>CWE PO/MT-VII -&nbsp;<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Preliminary examination</span>:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>07-10-2017</li>\r\n<li>08-10-2017</li>\r\n<li>14-10-2017</li>\r\n<li>15-10-2017</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>CWE PO/MT-VII -&nbsp;<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Main&nbsp;examination</span>:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>26-11-2017</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>CWE Clerk-VII -&nbsp;<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Preliminary examination</span>:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>02-12-2017</li>\r\n<li>03-12-2017</li>\r\n<li>09-12-2017</li>\r\n<li>10-12-2017</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>CWE&nbsp;Clerk-VII -&nbsp;<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Main&nbsp;examination</span>:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>21-01-2018</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>3.&nbsp;<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><strong>PSBs - CWE SPL - VII</strong></span></p>\r\n<p>This year onwards, for recuritment of Specialist Officers will be done through a two-tier examination. There will be a Preliminary exam for CWE SPL - VII. Based upon the performance in preliminary exam, successful candidates will be called for Main examination. The main examination will comprise of Professional knowledge questions ONLY. Detailed syllabus for this will be available on IBPS website in due course.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>The marks obtained in the Preliminary examination will NOT be considered for the final merit list. Only main examination marks will be considered for shortlisting for interview.&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p>CWE - SPL VII -&nbsp;<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Preliminary examination</span>:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>30-12-2017</li>\r\n<li>31-12-2017</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>CWE - SPL VII -&nbsp;<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Main examination</span>:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>28-01-2018</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>We will keep you updated with latest news from <a href=\"http://www.ibps.in\" target=\"_blank\">IBPS</a>. Meanwhile, keep learning!</p>\r\n<p>For more articles on IBPS preparation, click <a href=\"../../category/ibps-po-preparation\" target=\"_blank\">here</a>.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>',0,'',304,5,2,26,'ibps exam dates 2017, ibps 2017 exam dates, ibps 2017, ibps, ibps exam, ibps dates in 2017, ibps exam in 2017, ibps cwe 7 exam, ibps cwe specialist officer exam','IBPS exam dates in 2017. Plan ahead to be successful in IBPS CWE exams in the year 2017.',1),(596,'2017-03-07 14:29:02','2017-07-09 04:13:49','Indian History Notes for SSC CGL-Eminent Personalities','article','indian-history-eminent-personalities-ssc-cgl','/uploads/images/indian-history-notes-for-ssc-cgl-eminent-personalities-siB8zuX0.jpg','<h1>Indian History Notes for SSC CGL-Eminent Personalities</h1>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Alexander :&nbsp;he was the ruler of Macedonia in Greece. He attacked India in 326 BC and captured upto river Bias.</li>\r\n<li>Ajatasatru :&nbsp;Son of Bimbisara. He established the city of Pataliputra.</li>\r\n<li>Arien :&nbsp;Greek historian who wrote about Alexander&rsquo;s Indian invasion.</li>\r\n<li>Ashwaghosh :&nbsp;Buddhist monk who initiated Kaniskha to Buddhism wrote Buddha charita, Sutralankar and Sandaranand.</li>\r\n<li>AmarSimha :&nbsp;Sanskrit scholar in the court of Chandragupta who wrote Amarakosha.</li>\r\n<li>&nbsp;Aryabhatta :&nbsp;He analysed the reasons for Solar and Lunar eclipses and declared that the Earth is round. Wrote Aryabhattiyam.</li>\r\n<li>Bimbisar :&nbsp;Founded the Magadhan Empire or Haryanka dynasty. He was the first influential king of ancient India.</li>\r\n<li>Banabhatta :&nbsp;Court poet of Harshavardhana and author of Harsha Charita and Kadambari.</li>\r\n<li>Charak :&nbsp;He was an Ayurvedic expert wrote Charak-Samhita and established the Aitereya branch of Ayurvedic medicines.</li>\r\n<li>Amoghavarsha :&nbsp;He was a famous Rashtrakuta ruler.</li>\r\n<li>Dhanananda :&nbsp;He was a powerful king of Magadha. Alexander did not go forward to invade Magadha only after hearing his reputation.</li>\r\n<li>Darius I :&nbsp;The ruler of Iran (Persia) who invaded India in 6th century BC.</li>\r\n<li>Gautami Putra Shatakarni :&nbsp;He was the mostfamous Satavahana king in 2nd Century.</li>\r\n<li>Harisena :&nbsp;He was the writer of Pryaga Prashasti or Allahabad Pillar Inscription.</li>\r\n<li>Kharavel :&nbsp;Ruler of Kalinga in I century AD. The Famous Hathigumbha inscription belonged to him.</li>\r\n<li>Kanishka :&nbsp;(I century AD) : Most powerful Kushan king. Started Shaka Era. Organised fourth Buddhist council at Kundalvan near Kashmir.</li>\r\n<li>Karikala :&nbsp;Chola ruler who founded the city of Puhar (Kaveri patanam) in I century BC.</li>\r\n<li>Kautilya :&nbsp;also known as Vishnugupta or Chanakya. He wrote&nbsp;<em>Arthasasthra</em>, which is compared to &lsquo;<em>The prince</em>&rsquo; of Machiavelli.</li>\r\n<li>Kalidas :&nbsp;Famous Sanskrit poet who wrote,&nbsp;<em>Raghuvamsa, Kumara Sambhavam, Abhigyana</em>&nbsp;<em>Shakuntalam, Vikramorvashiyam and</em>&nbsp;<em>Malavikagnimitram.&nbsp;</em>He also wrote<em>Meghadootam and Ritusamharam.</em></li>\r\n<li>Kamban :&nbsp;A Tamil poet of 11th century who wrote Ramayan in Tamil.</li>\r\n<li>Mihir Bhoja :&nbsp;Famous Prathihara ruler of 9th century.</li>\r\n<li>Kalhana &ndash;&nbsp;Famous Kashmiri poet and historian.He wrote&nbsp;<em>Raja Tarangini</em>.</li>\r\n<li>Marco Polo :&nbsp;Venitian Traveller to India in 13th&nbsp;century.</li>\r\n<li>Menander :&nbsp;He came to India as a foreign aggressor in II Century BC.&nbsp;<em>MilindaPanho</em>, a book written by Nagasena, is about him.</li>\r\n<li>Nagarjuna :&nbsp;Famous Buddhist monk. He popounded the philosophy known as<em>Madhyamika</em>.</li>\r\n<li>Makkali Gosala :&nbsp;Philosopher of 6th Century BC. He was the founder of Ajivika sect.</li>\r\n<li>Mihirkula :&nbsp;Huna conqueror defeated by Yashodharma.</li>\r\n<li>Skand Gupt :&nbsp;Last mighty Gupta ruler.</li>\r\n<li>Shushrut :&nbsp;He was a doctor of Ayurvedic medicine. He started the Dhanwantri branch and was an expert in Plastic Surgery.</li>\r\n<li>Pulikeshin II.&nbsp;Most powerful king of Chalukyas of Vatapi who defeated Harshavardhana in North and Mahendravarman of South.</li>\r\n<li>Pushya Mitra sunga&nbsp;: He killed the last Mauryan ruler and laid the foundation of Sunga dynasty in&nbsp;185 BC.</li>\r\n<li>Pliny :&nbsp;He was a Roman historian who wrote the&nbsp;<em>Natural History</em>. He wrote about the Mauryas of India.</li>\r\n<li>Panini :&nbsp;Sanskrit scholar specially of Grammar. He wrote&nbsp;<em>Ashtadyayi</em>.</li>\r\n<li>Varahamihira :&nbsp;He was famous astronomer who wrote Brihat Samhita.</li>\r\n<li>Sankaracharya :&nbsp;He was born in Kaladi in Kerala. He propagated Advaita Philosophy.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Six systems of Indian Philosophy</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Samkya-&nbsp;Sage Kapila</li>\r\n<li>Yoga-&nbsp;Patanjali</li>\r\n<li>Vaisheshika-&nbsp;Kannada</li>\r\n<li>Nyaya-&nbsp;Akshapada (Gautama)</li>\r\n<li>Mimamsa-&nbsp;Jaimini</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Symbols of Buddha</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Birth&ndash;&nbsp;Lotus and Bull</li>\r\n<li>Renunciation-Horse</li>\r\n<li>Enlightenment&nbsp;-Bodhitree</li>\r\n<li>First&nbsp;Sermon&nbsp;-Dharma Chakra</li>\r\n<li>Nirvana&nbsp;(Death)-Foot prints</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Famous Eras</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Vikram Era&nbsp;-58 BC</li>\r\n<li>Saka Era&nbsp;&ndash; 78 AD</li>\r\n<li>Gupta Era-&nbsp;320 AD</li>\r\n<li>Hijra Era&nbsp;-622 AD</li>\r\n<li>Kollam Era-825 AD</li>\r\n<li>Illahi Era&nbsp;-1583 AD</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Historically Important Places</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Ayodhya-&nbsp;Birth place of Sri Rama (UP)</li>\r\n<li>Amber Palace-&nbsp;Rajasthan</li>\r\n<li>Aghakhan Palace- Pune (Maharashtra)&nbsp;(Gandhi and Kasturba were&nbsp;kept in prison here)</li>\r\n<li>Kedarnath-&nbsp;Holy place of Hindus&nbsp;(Utharanchal)</li>\r\n<li>Amarnath-&nbsp;Pilgrim centre (Kashmir)</li>\r\n<li>Elephanta caves-&nbsp;Near Mumbai</li>\r\n<li>Ellora Caves-&nbsp;Maharashtra &ndash; 34 cavetemples (Hindu, Buddha &ndash; Jaina)</li>\r\n<li>Rajgir-&nbsp;Jain Temple in Bihar</li>\r\n<li>Golden Temple-&nbsp;Amritsar &ndash; Harmandir Sahib of Sikhs</li>\r\n<li>Golgumbus-&nbsp;Bijapur (Karnataka) Tomb of Muhammed Adil Shah</li>\r\n<li>Tanjore-&nbsp;Capital of Cholas &ndash; Brihadveswara Temple</li>\r\n<li>Charminar-&nbsp;Hyderabad (Monument of Plague eradication)</li>\r\n<li>Konark Temple-&nbsp;Orissa (Sun Temple)</li>\r\n<li>Qutab Minar-&nbsp;Delhi</li>\r\n<li>Khajuraho-&nbsp;Near Bhopal (M.P.) 80 temples</li>\r\n<li>Mahabalipuram-&nbsp;Centre of Pallava architecture (Tamil Nadu)</li>\r\n<li>Kurukshetra-&nbsp;Battle of Mahabarata (in Haryana)</li>\r\n<li>TajMahal-&nbsp;Agra (UP) Built by Shah Jahan</li>\r\n<li>Sanchi-&nbsp;Buddhist Stupa (Madhya Pradesh)</li>\r\n<li>Haridwar-&nbsp;Holy Place of Hindus (Uttaranchal)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Books on Sciences</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Chandra Vyakaran-&nbsp;Chandragomin</li>\r\n<li>Amar Kosh &ndash;&nbsp;Amar Singh</li>\r\n<li>Niti Shastra &ndash;&nbsp;Kamandak</li>\r\n<li>Kamasutra &ndash;&nbsp;Vatsya yana</li>\r\n<li>Panchasiddhantika-&nbsp;Varahamihira</li>\r\n<li>Ashtanga Hridaya &ndash;&nbsp;Vaghbhatta</li>\r\n<li>Hastyaurveda- &nbsp;Pulkapya</li>\r\n<li>Sankhyakarika-&nbsp;Iswarkrishna</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Temples and Builders</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Kailas Temple at Ellora&nbsp;&ndash; Krishna I</li>\r\n<li>Chunnakesava Temple, Belur-&nbsp;Vishnuvardhana</li>\r\n<li>Rathas at Mahabilipuram-&nbsp;&nbsp;<wbr />Narashimhavarman I</li>\r\n<li>Brihadeswara Temple, Tanjavur&ndash; RajaRaja Chola</li>\r\n<li>Shore Temple, Mahabalipuram&ndash; Narasimha VarmanII</li>\r\n<li>Lingaraja Temple, Bhavaneswar &ndash;&nbsp;Eastern Gangarubs</li>\r\n<li>Karjuraho Temples-&nbsp;Chandellas</li>\r\n<li>Rajarajeshwara Temple, Tanjavur-&nbsp;Raja raja I</li>\r\n<li>Meenakshi Temple at Madhurai-&nbsp;Nayaka Rulers</li>\r\n<li>Shiva Temple at Tanjavur-&nbsp;Raja Raja Chola</li>\r\n</ul>',0,'',226,5,20,27,'ssc notes, ssc cgl notes, free ssc cgl notes, indian history notes for ssc cgl, Indian history in ssc cgl exam, ssc cgl exam notes, Indian history notes for exams','SSC CGL exam notes on Indian History - Eminent Personalities, a must read article for all SSC CGL exam aspirants.',1),(597,'2017-03-07 19:09:04','2017-07-08 15:24:43','SSC CGL Notes-Facts on Vedic Literature','article','ssc-cgl-notes-vedic-literature','/uploads/images/ssc-cgl-notes-facts-on-vedic-literature-ZbGZ0ZP8.jpg','<h1>SSC CGL Notes-Facts on Vedic Literature</h1>\r\n<p>The <strong>Vedic literature</strong> was composed in <strong>Sanskrit</strong>. To begin with the Vedas were recited and not written. <strong>They were taught by oral method.</strong> Hence they were <strong>called as Sruti (heard) and Smriti (memorized).</strong> But later on they were reduced to <strong>writing after the invention of scripts.</strong></p>\r\n<p>The major literary and religious works of Vedic Period are the f<strong>our Vedas</strong> and <strong>the Upanishads</strong>. These works still continue to hold immense authority in the sphere of spiritual and religious literature. The idea and principles of Karma (action) and Moksha (spiritual liberation) are widely accepted by the people belonging to Hindu faith.</p>\r\n<h2>Four Vedas</h2>\r\n<p>Veda is a sanskrit word. It means &ldquo;knowledge&ldquo;. There were four Vedas :</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li><strong>The Rig Veda</strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>The Sama Veda</strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>The Yajur Veda and</strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>The Atharva Veda.</strong>&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<h3><strong>1. The Rig Veda</strong></h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Collection of hymns</li>\r\n<li>Oldest of all vedas</li>\r\n<li>Associated of 1017 hymns or Suktas after adding &ldquo;Blhilya Sukta&rdquo; number in 1028</li>\r\n<li>Compiled in <strong>10 &lsquo;mandalas</strong>&lsquo; &amp; <strong>8 &lsquo;Akhtaks&rsquo;.</strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>Also contains the famous </strong>Gayatri Mantra</li>\r\n<li>II, III, IV, V, VI &amp; VII are oldest mandalas</li>\r\n<li>I, VIII, IX, X are latest mandalas.</li>\r\n<li>The Tenth &ldquo;Mandalas&rdquo; or chapter which has the &ldquo;<strong>Purushasukta</strong>&rdquo; hymn, was probably added later.</li>\r\n<li>Mandala IX is completely devoted to &lsquo;<strong>Soma</strong>&lsquo;.</li>\r\n<li>Mandala II to VII were created by Grita Samada, Vishwamitra, Vamadeva, Atri, Bharadwaj, Vashistha, VIII Kanwa and Angira, IX Soma</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3><strong>2. Samveda</strong></h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Rhthmic</strong> compilation of hymns for Rigveda</li>\r\n<li><strong>&ldquo;Book for Chants&rdquo;</strong> contains 1,549 hymns, meant to be sung at the &lsquo;soma&rsquo; sacrifice by a special class of Brahmanas called <strong>Udgatris</strong>. But the Samaveda has very little original value.</li>\r\n<li>Has only 75 fundamental hymns</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3><strong>3. The Yajur Veda</strong></h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Book of sacrifical prayers</li>\r\n<li><strong>Rituals of yajnas</strong></li>\r\n<li>Is sung of priest &ldquo;Adhavaryu&rdquo;</li>\r\n<li>Its mantras tell us how the sacrifices were to be performed and what part the &ldquo;Adhvaryus&rdquo;- the Brahmanas who performed the manual work in the arrangement of sacrifice were to play at the time of sacrifice.</li>\r\n<li>Has been compiled in <strong>&ldquo;fourth path&rdquo;</strong></li>\r\n<li>Has been divided into, <strong>Krishna(black) Yajurveda</strong> &amp; <strong>Shukla(white) Yajurveda</strong></li>\r\n<li>Prose text</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3><strong>4. Atharvaveda</strong></h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Mantras for <strong>magic spells</strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>Populate ritualistic</strong> system &amp; superstitions</li>\r\n<li>Associated with &ldquo;Saunkiya&rdquo; and &ldquo;Paiplad&rdquo; community</li>\r\n<li>Collection of 711/731/760 hymns</li>\r\n<li>Not included in &lsquo;<strong>Trai</strong>&lsquo;</li>\r\n<li>Has been divided in 20 &ldquo;<strong>Kandas</strong>&ldquo;</li>\r\n<li>18th, 19th &amp; 20th &lsquo;Kandas&rsquo; are later works</li>\r\n<li>Provides freedom from <strong>evils</strong> <strong>spirits</strong>.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Oldest text on Indian Medicine.</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>The vast literature of the Aryans is divided into two parts &ndash;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Sruti</strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>Smriti&nbsp;</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>1.&nbsp;<u>Sruti Literature</u></strong>: The word Veda has been divided from the Sanskrit word&nbsp;<strong>Ved,</strong>&nbsp;which means &lsquo;spiritual knowledge&rsquo;. The Vedas are four in number &ndash;&nbsp;<strong>Rig Veda, Samaveda, Yajurveda,</strong>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<strong>Atharvaveda.</strong>&nbsp;<wbr />The Rig Veda contains a references only to the first three Vedas, which suggests that the fourth&nbsp;<strong>Veda</strong>&nbsp;was composed at some later date.</p>\r\n<p><strong>The Vedic literature is usually divided into three periods:-</strong></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>The Mantra period when the Samhitas were composed</li>\r\n<li>Brahaman period when the Brahamanas, Upanishads and Aranyakas were composed</li>\r\n<li>the Sutra period.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Brahmanas</strong>&nbsp;are massive prose text which contain speculation of the meaning of the hymns, give precepts for their application, relate stories of their origin in connection with sacrificial rites and explain the secret meaning of the later.</li>\r\n<li>The&nbsp;<strong>Aranyakas</strong>&nbsp;are the concluding parts of the Brahamanas. It doest not lay much stress on rites, rituals and sacrifices, but merely contain the philosophy and mysticism. The lead with the problems of soul, origin and elements of universe and the creation of universe.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Aranyaka:-</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Literarily, it means &lsquo;<strong>Jungle</strong>&lsquo;</li>\r\n<li>Provides description of Moral Science and Philosophy</li>\r\n<li>Provides details of hermits and saints who lived in Jungles</li>\r\n<li>Give stress on meditation</li>\r\n<li>Protests the system of &lsquo;<strong>Yajnas</strong>&lsquo;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>It would be appropriate to describe Upanishadas as mystic writings. There are 108 Upanishads in all, the most prominent of them being&nbsp;<em>Ish, Prasana, Aitareya, Taittiriya, Chhandogaya, Kathoupanishad, Ishopanishad, Brehadaranyaka,</em>&nbsp;etc.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Upanishada</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Literary meaning is &lsquo;<strong>Satra</strong>&lsquo; (to sit near masters feet) in which Guru offers band of knowledge to their disciples</li>\r\n<li>Is a combination of Tatva-mimansa and philosophy</li>\r\n<li>They are also called <strong>&ldquo;Vedanta&rdquo;</strong></li>\r\n<li>Primitive upanishada are<strong> &ldquo;Brahadaranyaka&rdquo; and &ldquo;Chandogya&rdquo;</strong></li>\r\n<li>Later <strong>Upnishada</strong> like &ldquo;<strong>Katha</strong>&rdquo; and &ldquo;<strong>Swetaswatar</strong>&rdquo; have been written in poetic forms.</li>\r\n<li>Brahma is the summary of philosophy, which is the only a &lsquo;truth&rsquo; in the world.</li>\r\n<li>Knowledge awards salvation says Upanishadas</li>\r\n<li>Oldest possibility Narsinghpurvatapani</li>\r\n<li>Latest possibility Allopanishada in Akbar&rsquo;s reign</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong><u>2. Smriti Literature</u></strong>: Smriti is traditional knowledge and designates almost the entire body of post-Vedic classical Sanskrit literature. Smriti literature generally includes the following overlapping subjects:-</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li><strong>The Vedangas</strong>: They refer to certain branches of post-Vedic studies regarded as auxiliary to the Vedas. The Vedangas are conventionally divided into six heading namely:-</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>(i)<strong>Kalpa</strong>&nbsp;or the ritual canon, including the&nbsp;<strong>dharma shastras</strong>&nbsp;or legal codes,</p>\r\n<p>(ii)<strong>Jyotisha</strong>&nbsp;or astronomy,</p>\r\n<p>(iii)&nbsp;<strong>Siksha</strong>&nbsp;or phonetics,</p>\r\n<p>(iv)<strong>Chhanda</strong>&nbsp;or metre</p>\r\n<p>(v)&nbsp;<strong>Nirukta</strong>&nbsp;or etymology</p>\r\n<p>(vi)<strong>Vyakarana</strong>&nbsp;(Grammer)</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>The&nbsp;<strong>Shad-Darsana</strong>: Six orthodox schools of Hindu philosophy, namely Nyaya, &lsquo;Vaiseshikha&rsquo;, Sankhya, Yoga, Mimamsa and Vedanta.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Itihasa</strong>: Legendary or semi-legendary works, specifically the Ramayana and Mahabharata and often extended to the Puranas.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Puranas</strong>: Being a fairly late description of ancient legends, they are heavily coloured with the superstitions. The Puranas represent the most corrupt form of Hinduism. They are 18 in number</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The Eighteen Puranas</li>\r\n<li>Brahma Purana</li>\r\n<li>Vishnu Purana</li>\r\n<li>Shiva Purana</li>\r\n<li>Padma Purana</li>\r\n<li>Shrimad Bhagwat Purana</li>\r\n<li>Agni Purana</li>\r\n<li>Narad Purana</li>\r\n<li>Markandey Purana</li>\r\n<li>Bhavishya Purana</li>\r\n<li>Ling Purana</li>\r\n<li>Varah Purana</li>\r\n<li>Vaman Purana</li>\r\n<li>Brahm Vaivertya Purana</li>\r\n<li>Shanda Purana</li>\r\n<li>Surya Purana</li>\r\n<li>Matsya Purana</li>\r\n<li>Garuda Purana</li>\r\n<li>Brahmand Purana</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Upaveda</strong>: Also known as the auxiliary Vedas, they deal with medicine, architecture, erotics, archery and various arts and crafts. These were partly derived from original Vedic texts and were traditionally associated with one or other of the Vedas.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Tantras</strong>: Tantras are the writings of Shakta or Shaivite sects and also of certain antinomian Buddhist scholars</p>\r\n<p><strong>Agamas</strong>: They are scriptures of sectarian Hindus like Vaishnavites, Shaivites and Shaktas.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Upangas</strong>: They are a generic name for any collection of treatises although traditionally confined to the philosophical systems of &lsquo;Nyaya&rsquo; and &lsquo;Mimansa&rsquo; &ndash; the &lsquo;Dharma Sutras&rsquo; the &lsquo;Puranas&rsquo; and the &lsquo;Tantras&rsquo;</p>\r\n<h2><strong><u>Epics</u></strong></h2>\r\n<p>Some historians regard the Later Vedic Period as the Period of Epics. The&nbsp;<em>Mahabharata</em>&nbsp;and the&nbsp;<em>Ramayana</em>&nbsp;are the two great epics of this period.<br /><strong><em><u>Ramayana</u></em>:</strong> It is said to have been composed by the sage, Valmiki. The incident related in it precedes the&nbsp;<em>Mahabharata</em>&nbsp;by about a hundred and fifty years. The story of Ramayana is of indigenous origin and had existed in ballad form in Prakrit, in more than one version. It was rewritten in Sanskrit and augmented with many &lsquo;Shlokas&rsquo;. The epic was given a Brahmanical character which was not visible in the original work. It is also known as&nbsp;<em>Adi Kavya.</em>&nbsp;Evidence places the oldest part of the Ramayana to before 350 BC. The reference in the epic to the mingled hords of Yavanas and Shakas suggests that it received accretions in the Graeco-Scythian period and may have acquired its final shape by about AD 250.</p>\r\n<p><strong><em><u>Mahabharata</u></em>:</strong> The Mahabharata is the bulkiest epic consisting of 100,000 verses and is divided into 18 paravas (books). This book is usually assigned to Rishi Ved Vyas, but scholars have expressed doubts if such a great work could have been accomplished by one single person. The story itself occupies only about one-fourth of the poem. It is a tale about conflict between Aryans-Kaurava and Pandava.</p>\r\n<p>The rest is episodical comprising cosmology, theogony, state craft, the science of war, ethics, legendary history, mythology, fairy tales and several digressional and philosophical interludes, of which the best known is the&nbsp;<strong><em>Bhagavad Gita.</em></strong></p>',0,'',209,5,20,27,'ssc notes, ssc cgl notes, free ssc cgl notes, indian history notes for ssc cgl, Indian history in ssc cgl exam, ssc cgl exam notes, Indian history notes for exams, facts on vedic literature for ssc cgl','SSC CGL exam notes on Indian History - Facts on Vedic Literature, a must read article for all SSC CGL exam aspirants.',1),(598,'2017-03-08 05:57:23','2017-07-10 12:16:01','SSC CGL Notes-Dynasties of Ancient India','article','ssc-cgl-notes-ancient-dynasties','/uploads/images/ssc-cgl-notes-dynasties-of-ancient-india-4JRCWHc5.jpg','<h1><strong>SSC CGL Notes-Dynasties of Ancient India</strong></h1>\r\n<p>History forms a very important part of the General Awareness section of every competitive exam. In continuation to our previous posts on History notes, here are some very useful notes on&nbsp;Dynasties of Ancient India. Follow these notes to excel in the upcoming Railway and SSC CGL exams.</p>\r\n<p>Two major dynasties of India, the Maurya Empire (321 BC- 185 BC) and Gupta Empire (240 BC-550 AD), were originated from Magadha.</p>\r\n<p>Apart from Maurya and Gupta dynasties, there were other dynasties which were started from Magadha,</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Haryanka dynasty (544-413 BC)</strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>Shishunaga dynasty (413-345 BC)</strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>Nanda dynasty (424-321 BC)</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Haryanka dynasty :-</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Haryanka is</strong> the name of a new dynasty<strong> founded in Magadha by Bimbisara</strong>.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Bimbisara</strong> founded the dynasty by <strong>defeating</strong> the&nbsp; <strong>Brihadrathas</strong>.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Bimbisara</strong> was a contemporary of <strong>Buddha</strong>.</li>\r\n<li>Pataliputra and Rajagriha were the capitals of Magadhan kingdom. Magadha falls in the Patna region of Bihar.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Shishunaga Dynasty:-</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Haryankas were overthrown by <strong>Sisunaga</strong> and he <strong>founded</strong> the Sisunaga dynasty there.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Kalasoka </strong>the son and successor of Sisunaga was succeeded by <strong>Mahapadma Nanda </strong>and he founded the Nanda dynasty.</li>\r\n<li>Ajatasatru&rsquo;s successor <strong>Udayin </strong>was the founder of the city of Pataliputra.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Nanda Dynasty:-</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The Nanda Empire was an ancient Indian dynasty originated from <strong>Magadha</strong> and <strong>was established in 424 BC.</strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>Mahapadma Nanda was the founder</strong> and the <strong>first king of the Nanda</strong> dynasty.</li>\r\n<li>He overthrew the <strong>Magadha</strong> dynasty and established the new Empire.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Initially Nanda Dynast inherited a large kingdom of Magadha and subsequently the boundaries of Nanda Dynasty were expanded in all directions by its rulers.</li>\r\n<li>Nandas formed a vast army, including 200000 infantry, 20000 cavalry, 2000 war chariots and 3000 war elephants.</li>\r\n<li>At its peak, the Nanda Empire expanded from Bengal in the east to Punjab in the west.</li>\r\n<li>In the southern side it extended to the Vindhya Range.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Dhana Nanda was</strong> the <strong>last</strong> ruler of <strong>Nanda Dynasty.</strong></li>\r\n<li>In 321 BC, <strong>Chandragupta Maurya</strong> defeated him and founded the <strong>Maurya Empire.</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3><strong>MAURYAN DYNASTY (321 &ndash; 185 BC):-</strong></h3>\r\n<p><strong>List of Mauryan Emperors:</strong></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Chandragupta Maurya (321 BC-298 BC)</li>\r\n<li>Bindusara (298 BC-272 BC)</li>\r\n<li>Ashoka Maurya (269-232 BC)</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<ol start=\"4\">\r\n<li>Dasaratha Maurya</li>\r\n<li>Samprati</li>\r\n<li>Salisuka</li>\r\n<li>Devavarman</li>\r\n<li>Satadhanvan</li>\r\n<li>Brihadratha Maurya</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><strong>Origin of Mauryan Empire:-</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The Mauryan Empire, started from Magadha was <strong>founded in 321 BC by Chandragupta Maurya</strong>.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Pataliputra</strong>,the modern day <strong>Patna</strong> was the <strong>capital</strong> <strong>city</strong> of Mauryan Empire.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Expansion of Mauryan Empire:-</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Mauryan Empire was <strong>one of the world&rsquo;s largest</strong> empires of that time and expanded to an area of 5,000,000 km2.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Ashoka:-</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Ashoka ascended the throne in <strong>273BC</strong> and ruled upto 232 BC. He was known as &lsquo;<strong>Devanampriya priyadarsi</strong>the</li>\r\n<li>beautiful one who was the beloved of Gods.</li>\r\n<li>He was known as &lsquo;<strong>Devanampriya priyadarsi </strong>the beautiful one who was the beloved of Gods.</li>\r\n<li>Ashoka fought the Kalinga war in 261 BC Kalinga is in modern Orissa. Ashokan inscriptions were deciphered by <strong>James</strong> <strong>Princep</strong>.</li>\r\n<li>After the battle of Kalinga <strong>Ashoka became a Buddhist,</strong> being shocked by the horrors of the war.</li>\r\n<li>Ashoka was initiated to Buddhism by <strong>Upagupta</strong> or <strong>Nigrodha </strong>a disciple of Buddha</li>\r\n<li>For the propagation of Buddhism Ashoka started the institution of<strong>Dharmamahamatras</strong>.</li>\r\n<li>The IV Major Rock Edict of Ashoka tells about the practice of <strong>Dharma</strong></li>\r\n<li>The <strong>Major Rock Edict XII</strong> of Ahoka deals with the conquest of Kalinga.</li>\r\n<li>Ashoka held the third Buddhist council at his capital Pataliputra in 250BC under the presidentship of Moggaliputa Tissa.</li>\r\n<li>He sent his son and daughter to Sri Lanka for the spread of Buddhism (Mahendra and Sanghamitra)</li>\r\n<li>Ashoka spread Buddhism to SriLanka and Nepal. He is known as the <strong>Constantine of Buddhism</strong>.</li>\r\n<li>In his Kalinga Edict he mentions &lsquo;&lsquo;<strong>All man are as my children</strong>&rsquo;&rsquo;.</li>\r\n<li>Ceylones ruler <strong>Devanmpriya Tissa </strong>was Ashoka&rsquo;s first convert to Buddhism. Ashoka ruled for 40 years and died in 232 BC.</li>\r\n<li>The emblem of the Indian Republic has been adopted from the four lion capital of one of Ashokas pillars which is located in <strong>Saranath</strong>.</li>\r\n<li>Rock-cut architecture in India made a beginning during Ashoka&rsquo;s reign.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2><strong>Chanakya the architect of Mauryan Empire:-</strong></h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Chanakya</strong>,also known as Kautilya <strong>was the teacher of Chandragupta Maurya.</strong></li>\r\n<li>He was originally a <strong>teacher</strong> of <strong>Takshashila University.</strong></li>\r\n<li>He is considered to be the main architect in the establishment of the Maurya Empire by defeating the powerful Nanda Empire.</li>\r\n<li>His original name was Vishnugupta.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3><strong>Important points about Mauryan Empire:-</strong></h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Major sources for the study of Mauryan Empire are the <strong>Arthasastra of Kautilya </strong>and<strong>Indika of</strong> <strong>Megasthenes</strong>.</li>\r\n<li>Chandragupta Maurya was the founder of Mauryan Empire. It is also said that his mother was Mura a women of lower birth hence got the name Maurya.</li>\r\n<li>ChandraGupta Maurya was converted to Jainism, abdicated the throne in favour of his son Bindusara, passed his last days at Sravanabelagola (Near Mysore) where he died in 298 BC.</li>\r\n<li>Bindusara was a follower of Ajivika sect.</li>\r\n<li>Bindusara was known as <strong>Amitragatha</strong>.</li>\r\n<li>Megasthenese the first foreign traveller to India mentions about the existence of seven castes in India during the Mauryan period. Stanika in Mauryan administration refers to tax collector.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3><strong>Indo Greeks</strong></h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>First to invade India</strong> were the Greeks who were called <strong>Indo-Greeks.</strong></li>\r\n<li>The most famous Indo-<strong>Greek ruler was Menander</strong> with his <strong>Capital at Sakala</strong> in Punjab (Modern Sialkot)</li>\r\n<li>The Indo-Greeks were the <strong>first to issue gold coins</strong> in India.</li>\r\n<li>Menander was converted into a Buddhist by Buddhist monk Nagasena (Nagarjuna)</li>\r\n<li><strong>Demitrius, the king of Bacteria</strong> invaded <strong>India about 190BC.</strong> He is considered as<strong>Second&nbsp;Alexander</strong> (But the Indian ruler who accepted the name second Alexander<strong>(Sikandar-i-sani)</strong> was&nbsp;Alauddin Khilji)&nbsp;Indo-Greeks were the first to introduce military<br />governorship in India.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3><strong>Kushan Empire</strong></h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Kujula Kadphises</strong> is considered to be the <strong>founder of Kushan Empire.&nbsp;</strong>He established the kingdom by unifying the disparate <strong>Yuezhi tribes</strong> of ancient Bactria in the early 1st century AD and expanded its territory of present day Afghanistan, Pakistan, southern Tajikistan and Uzbekistan.</li>\r\n<li>He established the<strong> capital of Kushan Empire</strong> near <strong>Kabul</strong>.</li>\r\n<li>During the period of first to mid-third centuries AD, Kushan expanded rapidly and represented as a major power in Central Asia and northern India.</li>\r\n<li>The <strong>most famous Kushana ruler was Kanishka.</strong> He became the ruler in 78 AD and<strong>started Saka Era in 78 AD.</strong></li>\r\n<li>The <strong>Capital of Kanishka was Peshawar</strong> or Purushapura. Kanishka c<strong>onvened the fourth Buddhist</strong> council&nbsp;in Kashmir.</li>\r\n<li>The Gandhara School of Art received royal patronage under the Kushans. Kanishka patronised Mahayana form of Buddhism.</li>\r\n<li>The first month of Saka era is Chaithra and the last month&nbsp;is Phalguna.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Vasudeva was the last great king</strong> of Kushana Dynasty.</li>\r\n<li>Kushana school of art is also referred to as the Mathura school.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3><strong>Sunga Dynasty</strong></h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Sunga dynasty</strong> was established<strong> by Pusyamitra Sunga</strong> in 185 BC after assassinating the last Mauryan emperor Brihadratha.</li>\r\n<li>The <strong>capital of Sunga Dynasty was Pataliputra</strong> of ancient Magadha.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Kalidasa&rsquo;s drama Malavikagnimitram</strong> is about the love story of Pushyamitra&rsquo;s son Agnimitra and</li>\r\n<li>Last King of sunga dynasty was Devabhuti. he ruled the kingdom from 83 to 73 BC</li>\r\n<li><strong>Patanjali&rsquo;s Yoga Sutras</strong> and <strong>Mahabhasya</strong> were composed in this period. The ancient Sanskrit grammar, Ashtadayayi by Panini was composed during the period of Sunga Period.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3><strong>Kanva Dynasty</strong></h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Kanva dynasty was<strong> founded by Vasudeva Kanva</strong> in 72 BC after defeating the last Sunga ruler Devabhuti.</li>\r\n<li>This dynasty ruled <strong>for a period of 45 years.</strong></li>\r\n<li>Vasudeva, Bhumimitra, Narayana and Susuman were the rulers of Kanva dynasty.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Satavahana Dynasty</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Satavahanas were <strong>the most powerful ruling dynasty</strong> after the Mauryas.</li>\r\n<li>Satavahanas were also <strong>known</strong> <strong>as Andhras</strong>.</li>\r\n<li>Satavahanas were the Indian rulers who prefixed their mother&rsquo;s name along with their names.</li>\r\n<li>Most important Satavahana ruler was <strong>Gautamiputra Satakarni</strong>. Satavahanas were Brahmanas.</li>\r\n<li>Nagarjuna Konda and Amaravati in Andhrapradesh became important seats of Buddhist culture under the Satavahanas.</li>\r\n<li>The two common structures of Satavahanas were the temple called <strong>Chaitya</strong> and the monastery<strong> called Vihara.</strong></li>\r\n<li>The <strong>official language</strong> of the Satavahanas <strong>was Prakrit</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3><strong>The Cholas</strong></h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Vijayalaya</strong> was the founder of the <strong>Chola empire</strong>. He was a feudatory of the Pallavas of Kanchi.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Raja Raja I</strong> (985 &ndash; 1014) adopted the titles of Arumudivarman, Mammudichodadeva, Jaykonda, Marthanda Chola, Mamudichola etc.&nbsp;He built the <strong>Brihadeshwara temple</strong> at Tanjavur. which is called the RajaRajeswara temple.</li>\r\n<li>Rajendra I led an expedition to North India, defeated the Pala ruler Mahipala I and adtoped the title, Gangaikondachola and established a new Capital, Gangai Konda Cholapuram. Cholas maintained a well established local &ndash; self government system. Ur, Sabha or Mahasabha &ndash; and Nagaram were the assemblies for local administration.</li>\r\n<li>The Uttaramerur inscription of Dantivarman Pallava gives details about the local self government.</li>\r\n</ul>',0,'',327,5,20,27,'ssc notes, ssc cgl notes, free ssc cgl notes, indian history notes for ssc cgl, Indian history in ssc cgl exam, ssc cgl exam notes, Indian history notes for exams, dynasties in Ancient India for ssc cgl','SSC CGL exam notes on Indian History - Dynasties of Ancient India, a must read article for all SSC CGL exam aspirants. ',1),(599,'2017-03-11 14:17:21','2017-07-09 23:18:10','GATE Mechanical Short notes on Fluid Flow-Couette Flow','article','gate-mechanical-short-notes-fluid-couette-flow','/uploads/images/gate-mechanical-short-notes-on-fluid-flow-couette-flow-OvgPIdtM.jpg','<p>In this article on GATE Mechanical Engineering, we will understand an important topic in Viscous Flow in the subject of Fluid Mechanics, i.e. Couette flow.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Couette flow occurs when we analyse the flow between parallel plates. When the plates are fixed, we can obtain the Navier-Stokes equation for the flow. But in the case of Couette flow, the parallel plates are no longer fixed and are able to move at a certain velocity. Let us analyse this mathematically.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Consider the figure below, in which there is a fluid flowing in between two parallel plates and the top plate is moving with a velocity U. If you write down the Navier-Stokes equation for flow between fixed parallel plates, we get,</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/couette-flow-DJFij58M.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"371\" height=\"243\" /></p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=U%3D%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B2%5Cmu%7D%5Cfrac%7B%5Cpartial%20p%7D%7B%5Cpartial%20x%7D%20y%5E%7B2%7D%2Bc_%7B1%7Dy%2Bc_%7B2%7D\" alt=\"\" />.......(1)</p>\r\n<p>The above equation is derived based on the following assumptions:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>steady flow</li>\r\n<li>incompressible flow, and</li>\r\n<li>laminar flow</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>Now, apply the boundary conditions, i.e. u = 0 at y = 0 and u = U at y = h, where \'h\' is the distance between the two plates, in the equation given above. The following will be the result:</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=c_%7B1%7D%3D%5Cfrac%7BU%7D%7Bh%7D%20-%20%5Cfrac%7Bh%7D%7B2%20%5Cmu%7D%20%5Cfrac%7B%5Cpartial%20p%7D%7B%5Cpartial%20x%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;and&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=c_%7B2%7D%3D0\" alt=\"\" />.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Substituting the values of the constants in equation (1), the equation for the new velocity profile becomes as follows:</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=u%3D%5Cfrac%7BUy%7D%7Bh%7D%2B%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B2%20%5Cmu%7D%20%5Cfrac%7B%5Cpartial%20p%7D%7B%5Cpartial%20x%7D%20(y%5E%7B2%7D-hy)\" alt=\"\" />.......(2)&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The figure below shows the&nbsp;<strong>simple shear flow</strong>, in which there is no pressure gradient in the flow direction. This means that the fluid motion is created by simply moving the top plate. This creates a&nbsp;<strong>linear velocity profile (u = Uy/h).&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"../../uploads/images/simple-shear-flow-hy0msqSE.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"263\" height=\"129\" /></strong></p>\r\n<p>Equation (2) can be written in a dimensionless format as well:</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cfrac%7Bu%7D%7BU%7D%20%3D%20%5Cfrac%7By%7D%7Bh%7D%20%2BP%5B%5Cfrac%7By%7D%7Bh%7D%20(1-%5Cfrac%20%7By%7D%7Bh%7D)%5D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;......(3)&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>In equation (3) above, \'P\' is the&nbsp;<strong>dimensionless pressure gradient</strong> and its value can be remembered as,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=P%3D-%20%5Cfrac%7Bh%5E%7B2%7D%7D%7B2%20%5Cmu%20U%7D%20%5Cfrac%7B%5Cpartial%20p%7D%7B%5Cpartial%20x%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;..... (4).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The value of P can be used to plot velocity profiles, as shown in the figure below. It is seen that when P = 0 (i.e. no pressure gradient), linear velocity profile occurs. For P &lt; -1, the phenomena of backflow occurs, i.e. fluid motion created by the top plate is not strong enough to overcome the adverse pressure gradient, which means that u/U is negative and this occurs in the lower half region.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/couette-flow-velocity-profile-jAPNX69j.gif\" alt=\"\" width=\"342\" height=\"213\" /></p>\r\n<p>The above concept can be used for journal bearings, which are used in various mechanical systems. When the bearing is applied upon by a small load, i.e. rotating shaft and bearing remain concentric, the flow between shaft and bearing can be seen as a flow between parallel plates when the top plate moves with a constant velocity. In this situation, the velocity of the lubricant inside the gap is linear, where P = 0.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>',0,'',502,5,2,5,'gate mechanical short notes, gate mechanical, gate, gate mechanical engineering, couette flow, gate mechanical notes on coquette flow, mechanical engineering notes','GATE Mechanical Engineering notes on Fluid Mechanics - Couette flow. A rather less talked about topic in FM for GATE Mechanical Engineering exam. ',1),(600,'2017-03-17 05:35:49','2017-07-08 15:24:43','UPSC ESE Notes-Safety and its Importance','article','upsc-ese-notes-safety-and-importance','/uploads/images/upsc-ese-notes-safety-and-its-importance-EzZS2pIj.jpg','<p>In this article, we will look at a new topic introduced in <a href=\"https://mindvis.in/courses/upsc-ese-mechanical-engineering-2018-online-prep-course\" target=\"_blank\">UPSC Engineering Services Exam (ESE)</a> in prelims paper - Safety and its importance. We will try and cover all major points on this topic which will help you prepare it for <a href=\"https://mindvis.in/courses/upsc-ese-mechanical-engineering-2018-online-prep-course\" target=\"_blank\">UPSC ESE</a> Prelims paper.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>What is Safety?</strong></p>\r\n<p>In general terms, safety means freedom or protection from harm, hazard, danger, risk, injury, accident or any damage. In an industrial context, it means the minimization of contact between human beings and hazardous conditions, and it majorly deals with prevention of physical injury to personnel and property.&nbsp;<strong>Industrial safety is a condition of operations in which, by controlling risks and hazards, accident free production is achieved.&nbsp;</strong>Safety is defined as a positive, well organized program based upon the knowledge of interaction and reaction between man and his working environment, which helps business organization to minimize personnel death, losses caused by injuries, fires, explosions and other occupational hazards.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Safety is the opposite of DANGER.&nbsp;</strong>Freedom from hazards represents absolute safety, which is an ideal and a condition seldom realized. Safety is a situation with an acknowledgement of acceptable risks. Therefore, safety means to bring or keep the hazard level, below permissible safe level. It includes safety, health and environment (SHE) protection including protection of property.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>What is the need for Safety?</strong></p>\r\n<p>There are many benefits of maintaining a SAFE work environment, but first of all \'<strong>it is the RIGHT THING to do</strong>\'. Any company which employs workers must work towards keeping the work environment safe. Responsible employers take the time and use company resources to make sure that each day people coming in to work are SAFE. The major benefits of maintaining a safe work environment are:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>workers are more comfortable to work&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li>productivity levels increase</li>\r\n<li>absenteeism levels decrease</li>\r\n<li>profit margins increase</li>\r\n<li>workers can focus on serving the customers well</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>Companies can also save themselves from legal claims against worngful injury or death, insurance costs and unnecessary expenses.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The formal safety program is a set of written documents that describe a company\'s safety policies, responsibilities and priorities. The program is so designed to bring structure and consistency into a company\'s accident prevention efforts.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><strong>Central and State laws also require that critical jobsite hazards must be controlled through specific written programs and extra training for employees.</strong></span></p>\r\n<p>These programs are:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Confined space entry</li>\r\n<li>Lock out/ Tag out</li>\r\n<li>Fall protection</li>\r\n<li>Scaffolding safety</li>\r\n<li>Hazardous materials</li>\r\n<li>Fire safety etc.&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>The employee safety training programs must cover topics like:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>accident prevention and safety promotions</li>\r\n<li>safe working practices as per industry standards</li>\r\n<li>safety compliance</li>\r\n<li>accident and emergency response</li>\r\n<li>use of personal protective equipment</li>\r\n<li>safe use of equipment and machinary</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>An effective training program can reduce the number of injuries and deaths, property damage, legal liabilities, illnesses, compensation claims and absenteeism.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Safety Management System (SMS)</strong></p>\r\n<p>A SMS is a series of defined, organization-wide processes that provide a basis for effective risk-based decision making related to daily business. SMS focusses on maximizing opportunities to continuously improve the overall safety of the system. The key processes of an SMS are:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Hazard identification - a method to identify hazards related to your organization.&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li>Occurence reporting - a process for the acquisition of safety data.</li>\r\n<li>Risk management - a standard approach for assessing risks and for applying risk controls.</li>\r\n<li>Performance measurement - management tools for analyzing whether the organization\'s safety goals are being achieved.</li>\r\n<li>Quality/ Safety assurance - processes based on quality management principles that support continuous improvement of the organization\'s safety performance.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/safety-management-system-S8acB8Tj.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"500\" height=\"212\" /></p>\r\n<p>The roles and responsibilities of an SMS are:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The senior management is accountable for establishing the SMS and allocating the necessary resources to support and maintain an effective SMS.&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li>The management of the organization is responsible for implementing, maintaining and adhering to SMS processes in their area, and</li>\r\n<li>Employees are responsible for identifying hazards and reporting them.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>SMS is beneficial to an organization in the following ways:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>It provides a basis for a more informed decision making process.</li>\r\n<li>It improves the safety by reducing/ eliminating the risk of accidents.&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li>It provides for a better resource allocation that results in increased efficiencies and reduced costs.&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li>It demonstrated corporate due diligence.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>What SMS is not:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Self-regulation/ deregulation</li>\r\n<li>A stand alone department</li>\r\n<li>A substitute for oversight</li>\r\n<li>An undue burden</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>What SMS does:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Builds on existing processes,</li>\r\n<li>Integrates with other management sytems by making a flexible regulatory framework for the organization, and</li>\r\n<li>Demonstrates good business practice.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Difference between SMS and Quality management system (QMS):</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>SMS focuses on the safety aspects of an organization.</li>\r\n<li>QMS focuses on the services and products of an organization.</li>\r\n<li>QMS works on conformity, SMS focuses on hazards. Both non-conformities and hazards can have an impact on safety.</li>\r\n<li>Both systems enhance safety and are essential and complimentary management tools. We cannot have an effective SMS without applying quality management principles.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Important aspects of SMS:</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong><img src=\"../../uploads/images/safety-management-system-aspects-tfE99hBa.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"540\" height=\"498\" /></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Legislative Compliance Audits:</strong></p>\r\n<p>These type of audits can be specific and undertaken to determine if workplace practices are meeting legislative requirements. Compliance audits are conducted to ensure the workplace meets the requirements of the Factories Act, 1948. A compliance audit will identify hazards, unsafe work practices and procedures, and systems of work do not meet legislated standards. The hazards addressed during a legislative compliance audit are determined by the workplace environment along with information obtained from specific training, relevant injury data and industry input. The outcomes of legislative compliance is being achieved or if further actions are required to meet legislative standards.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Hazard specific audits:</strong></p>\r\n<p>Hazard specific audits address particular issues such as lifting of glassware, or using hazardous substances, and involve the inspection and testing of current workplace control methods . This type of audit has a narrow focus and looks at the effectiveness of policies and procedures in dealing with specific hazards.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Management system Audits:</strong></p>\r\n<p>Management audits have a wider scope. In addition to working as a hazards and risk control mechanism, it also looks at workplace structures, planning activities, responsibilities, implemented procedures, review cycles and measurement and evaluation issues. The management system is a planned, documented and verifiable method of managing Work and Safety hazards. Some of the basic characteristics of a occupational health and safety management system are as follows:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Management commitment</li>\r\n<li>Existence of a health and safety policy that is communicated to staff</li>\r\n<li>Allocation of resources and responsibilities for health and safety issues</li>\r\n<li>Health and safety consultation</li>\r\n<li>Hazard identification, evaluation and control</li>\r\n<li>Provision of information and training of staff.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>In the next article, we will look at the concept of&nbsp;<strong>Occupational Health and Industrial Hygiene.&nbsp;</strong></p>',0,'',418,5,2,7,'upsc ese notes, safety and its importance, upsc engineering services exam, upsc ese 2018 mechanical engineering online course, upsc ese 2018, upsc IES 2018 mechanical engineering','UPSC ESE Notes on Safety and its importance. These notes can help you develop good understanding on the topic for UPSC ESE Prelims. ',1),(601,'2017-03-22 04:31:18','2017-07-10 09:25:18','GATE Question Videos - Mechanical Vibrations','article','gate-mechanical-question-solving-videos-vibrations','/uploads/images/gate-question-videos-mechanical-vibrations-OILEQ8GX.jpg','<p>In this article we will bring you videos on previous <a href=\"https://mindvis.in/courses/gate-2018-mechanical-engineering-online-course\" target=\"_blank\">GATE Mechanical</a> Questions on the subject of Mechanical Vibrations. Feel free to share any queries that you may have on the solutions.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Q1)&nbsp;1. The rotor shaft of a large electric motor supported between short bearings at both the ends shows a deflection of 1.8 mm in the middle of the rotor. Assuming the rotor to be perfectly balanced and supported at knife edges at both the ends, the likely critical speed (in rpm) of the shaft is<br />a. 350<br />b. 705<br />c. 2810<br />d. 4430</p>\r\n<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong><iframe src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/-U_Y4cfc_8Y\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"></iframe></strong></p>\r\n<p>Q2)&nbsp;A concentrated mass m is attached at the centre of a rod of length 2L as shown in the figure. The rod is kept in a horizontal equilibrium position by a spring of stiffness k. For very small amplitude of vibration, neglecting the weights of the rod and spring, the undamped natural frequency of the system is&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/gate-questions-mechanical-vibrations-KCmN3wTI.PNG\" alt=\"\" width=\"285\" height=\"145\" /></p>\r\n<p>a.&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Csqrt%20%7B%5Cfrac%7Bk%7D%7Bm%7D%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>b.&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Csqrt%20%7B%5Cfrac%7B2k%7D%7Bm%7D%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>c.&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Csqrt%20%7B%5Cfrac%7Bk%7D%7B2m%7D%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>d.&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Csqrt%20%7B%5Cfrac%7B4k%7D%7Bm%7D%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong><iframe src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/FKN33v-ivjg\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"></iframe></strong></p>\r\n<p>Q3)&nbsp;An automotive engine weighing 240 kg is supported on four springs with linear characteristics. Each of the front two springs have a stiffness of 16 MN/m while the stiffness of each rear spring is 32 MN/m. The engine seed (in rmp), at which resonance is likely to occur, is</p>\r\n<p>a. 6040</p>\r\n<p>b. 3020</p>\r\n<p>c. 1424</p>\r\n<p>d. 955</p>\r\n<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong><iframe src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/RCpfkarJjvI\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"></iframe></strong></p>\r\n<p>Q4)&nbsp;As shown in figure, a mass of 100 kg is held between two springs. The natural frequency of vibration of the system, in cycles/s, is&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/gate-mechanical-questions-mechanical-vibrations-2-PM27uVFw.PNG\" alt=\"\" width=\"107\" height=\"144\" /></p>\r\n<p>a.&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B2%20%5Cpi%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>b.&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cfrac%7B5%7D%7B%5Cpi%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>c.&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cfrac%7B10%7D%7B%5Cpi%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>d.&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cfrac%7B20%7D%7B%5Cpi%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong><iframe src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/uun_-YqVFuE\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"></iframe></strong></p>\r\n<p>Q5)&nbsp;In a spring-mass system, the mass is m and the spring constant is k. The critical damping coefficient of the system is 0.1 kg/s. In another spring-mass system, the mass is 2m and the spring constant is 8k. The critical damping coefficient (in kg/s) of this system is _________</p>\r\n<p>a. 0.6</p>\r\n<p>b. 0.3</p>\r\n<p>c. 0.4</p>\r\n<p>d. 0.8</p>\r\n<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong><iframe src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/CAiDPGZl_u8\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"></iframe></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Keep visiting for more questions solving videos.&nbsp;</strong></p>',0,'',616,5,2,21,'gate mechanical, gate mechanical video lectures, gate question videos, GATE Question Videos on Mechanical Vibrations, gate videos, gate mechanical videos, gate mechanical engineering','GATE Question Solving on the subject of Mechanical Vibrations. Learn how to tackle a question on Mechanical Vibrations in GATE Mechanical exam.',1),(602,'2017-03-28 06:59:06','2017-07-08 18:10:25','UPSC ESE Mechanical notes - mechatronics','article','upsc-ese-notes-mechanical-mechatronIcs','/uploads/images/upsc-ese-mechanical-notes-mechatronics-3KPKvcF0.jpg','<p><a href=\"https://mindvis.in/courses/upsc-ese-mechanical-engineering-2018-online-prep-course\" target=\"_blank\">UPSC </a>has introduced Mechantronics in its <a href=\"https://mindvis.in/courses/upsc-ese-mechanical-engineering-2018-online-prep-course\" target=\"_blank\">Engineering Services</a> exam recently. We will be introducing the basic concepts of Introduction to Mechatronics in this article, which can be used as short notes for preparing for UPSC ESE Mechanical subject on Mechatronics.</p>\r\n<p><strong>What is mechatronics?</strong></p>\r\n<p>The word \"<strong>Mechatronics</strong>\" was introduced by a Japanese engineer in the year 1969 by combining two words,&nbsp;<strong>mecha</strong> from&nbsp;<strong>mechanisms&nbsp;</strong>and&nbsp;<strong>tronics&nbsp;</strong>from&nbsp;<strong>electronics</strong>. Nowadays, the term is used to describe a philosophy in engineering technology which uses a co-ordinated, and simultaneously developed combination of mechanical engineering with electronics and computer control in manufacturing, design and other industrial processes. In mechatronic systems, many mechnanical processes are replace by electronic processes. This means greater flexibility, easy redesign and reprogramming. This also helps in automatic data collection and reports.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The basic elements of a mechatronic system.</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/basic-elements-of-mechatronics-qVI99D7g.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"595\" height=\"238\" /></p>\r\n<p><strong>Example of Mechatronic system.</strong></p>\r\n<p>Let us consider the modern camera and its auto focus system. Nowadays, we just point and click to shoot a picture. The camera is itself able to adjust the focus by varying the aperture and shutter speed so as to get the correct exposure for the picture. There is no, or very little need of manual adjustment of focus for the perfect shot. This is a very commonly used example of a mechatronic system.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Embedded systems</strong></p>\r\n<p>An embedded system is that system in which microprocessors are embedded into systems and it is this type of system that we generally deal with in mechatronics. A microprocessor is a collection of logic gates and memory elements that are not wired physically but are connected via software to implement the logical functions. The function of a microprocessor is to look at inputs to see whether they are ON or OFF, process the results of such inputs as per a program and then giving an output whether the input is ON or OFF.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>A microprocessor used in a control system needs some additional chips to have as memory for data storage and for Input/ output ports so that it is enabled to process signals.&nbsp;If all these extra facilities are integrated together on a single chip, then such a microprocessor is called&nbsp;<strong>microcontroller.&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>An embedded system is a microprocessor based system that is designed to control a range of functions and is not designed to be programmed by the end user.&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p>The above line means, that the end user cannot change the function of an embedded system by adding or changing the software.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Some examples of microcontrollers in a control system are:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Modern washing machines</li>\r\n<li>pumps</li>\r\n<li>modern car</li>\r\n<li>cell phones etc.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;I hope that in this article, you have got an idea of what do we understand by the term Mechatronics and other terms associated with it. In the next article, we will understand the term Systems and we will further talk about modelling and measurement systems.&nbsp;</p>',0,'',378,5,2,7,'upsc ese notes, mechatronics, upsc engineering services exam, upsc ese 2018 mechanical engineering online course, upsc ese 2018, upsc IES 2018 mechanical engineering, notes for mechatronics','UPSC ESE Notes on Introduction to Mechatronics. These notes can help you develop good understanding on the topic for UPSC ESE Prelims.',1),(603,'2017-03-29 08:13:26','2017-07-10 12:31:35','GATE Mechanical PSU Cut offs','article','gate-mechanical-psu-cut-offs','/uploads/images/gate-mechanical-psu-cut-offs-JrT87tZN.jpg','<p>After GATE Mechanical 2017, many of you will be eager to know about the further options. Getting recruited in a&nbsp;<strong>PSU&nbsp;</strong>through GATE is at the top of the wishlist of every mechanical engineering student. In this article, I am providing you the data regarding cut offs for various PSUs in the last few years.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>1)&nbsp;<strong>Hindustan Petroleum Corporation Limited (HPCL)</strong></p>\r\n<table sty