g>AB&nbsp;</strong>and&nbsp;<strong>BC&nbsp;</strong>which are at right angles are acted upon by tensile stress of 140 MPa and a compressive stress of 70 MPa and also by a shear stress 35 MPa. Determine the principal stresses and the principal planes. Find also the maximum shear stress and planes&nbsp;</p>',0,'',1,5,2,6,'','',0),(605,'2017-04-17 06:13:31','2017-07-10 03:13:53','GATE ME and ESE Practice Questions - SOM','article','gate-me-and-ese-practice-questions-som','/uploads/images/gate-me-and-ese-practice-questions-som-FI3lK520.jpg','<p>Q1) Two planes&nbsp;<strong>AB&nbsp;</strong>and&nbsp;<strong>BC&nbsp;</strong>which are at right angles are acted upon by tensile stress of 140 MPa and a compressive stress of 70 MPa respectively and also by shear stress 35 MPa. Determine the principal stresses and the principal planes. Find also the maximum shear stress and planes on which they act.</p>\r\n<p>Q2) A cantilever tube of length 120 mm is subjected to an axial tension, P = 9 kN, a torsional moment, T = 72 kNm and a bending load, F = 1.75 kN at the free end. The material is aluminium alloy with a yield strength of 276 MPa. Find the thickness of the tube limiting the OD to 50 mm so as to ensure a FOS of 4.</p>\r\n<p>Q3) A 5 cm diameter solid shaft is welded to a flat plate by 1 cm fillet weld. What will be the maximum torque that the welded joint can sustain if the permissible shear stress in the weld material is not to exceed 8 kN/cm<sup>2</sup>?</p>\r\n<p>Q4) A steel bolt of diameter 10 mm passes through a brass tube of ID 15 mm and OD 25 mm. The bolt is tightened by a nut so that the length of tube is reduced by 1.5 mm. If the temperature of the assembly is raised by 40<sup>o</sup>C, estimate the axial stresses in the bolt and the tube before and after heating. Material properties for steel and brass are:</p>\r\n<p>E<sub>s</sub> = 2 x 10<sup>5</sup> MPa,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Calpha_%7Bs%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;= 1.2 x 10<sup>-5</sup>/&nbsp;<sup>o</sup>C</p>\r\n<p>E<sub>b</sub> = 1 x 10<sup>5</sup> MPa,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Calpha_%7Bb%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;= 1.9 x 10<sup>-5</sup> /&nbsp;<sup>o</sup>C</p>\r\n<p>Q5) A MS shaft of 50 mm diameter is subjected to a bending moment of 1.5 kNm and torque T. If the yield point of steel in tension is 210 MPa, find the maximum value of the torque without causing yielding of the shaft material according to&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>(i) maximum principal stress theory, and</p>\r\n<p>(ii) maximum shear stress theory</p>\r\n<p>Q6) A timber beam 15 cm wide and 20 cm deep carries a UDL over a span of 4 m and is simply supported. If the permissible stresses are 30 MPa longitudinally and 3 MPa transverse shear, calculate the maximum load which can be carried by the timber beam.</p>\r\n<p>Q7) A solid shaft is to transmit 300 kW at 120 rpm. If the shear stress is not to exceed 100 MPa, find the diameter of the shaft. What percent saving in weight would be obtained if this shaft were replaced by a hollow one whose ID equals 0.6 of the OD, the length, material and maximum allowable shear being the same?</p>\r\n<p>Q8) A SSB AB of span 4 m supports a UDL of intensity q = 4 kN/m spread over the entire span and a concentrated load, P = 2 kN placed at a distance of 1.5 m from left end A. The beam is constructed of a rectangular cross section with width b = 10 cm and depth d = 20 cm. Determine the maximum tensile and compressive stresses developed in the beam due to loading.</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/qewvgrt-5jrTZoD6.PNG\" alt=\"\" width=\"217\" height=\"149\" /></p>\r\n<p>Q9) A beam AB is hinge supported at its ends and is loaded by couple P.e as shown in the figure. The magnitude of shearing force at a section x of the beam is&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/qwfer-hsNLz93g.PNG\" alt=\"\" width=\"262\" height=\"83\" /></p>\r\n<p>(a) 0</p>\r\n<p>(b) P</p>\r\n<p>(c) P/2L</p>\r\n<p>(d) P.e/2L</p>\r\n<p>Q10) Circumferential and longitudinal strains in cylindrical boiler under internal steam pressure, are&nbsp;&epsilon;<sub>1</sub> and&nbsp;&epsilon;<sub>2</sub> respectively. Change in volume of the boiler cylinder per unit volume will be</p>\r\n<p>(a)&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cepsilon_%7B1%7D%20%2B%202%20%5Cepsilon_%7B2%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>(b)&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cepsilon_%7B1%7D%20%5Cepsilon_%7B2%7D%5E%7B2%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>(c)&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=2%20%5Cepsilon_%7B1%7D%20%2B%20%20%5Cepsilon_%7B2%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>(d)&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cepsilon_%7B1%7D%5E%7B2%7D%20%5Cepsilon_%7B2%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>',0,'',391,5,2,2,'gate practice questions, gate mechanical revision notes, gate mechanical free notes, gate mechanical free preparation, gate mechanical online preparation, gate 2018 mechanical online course, gate 2018 online notes','Free Practice questions for GATE ME and ESE exams from the subject of SOM. ',1),(606,'2017-04-28 09:50:46','2017-07-07 03:25:03','GATE ME Short notes - Abrasive Jet Machining ','article','gate-me-short-notes-abrasive-jet-machining','/uploads/images/gate-me-short-notes-abrasive-jet-machining-J0qSDf8H.jpg','<p><strong>Abrasive Jet Machining</strong>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Abrasive Jet Machining (AJM) is a machining process that&nbsp;makes&nbsp;use&nbsp;of&nbsp;a stream of fine grained abrasive mixed with air or some other carrier gas at high pressure. This stream is directed by means of a suitably designed nozzle on to the work surface to be machined. Metal removal occurs due to erosion caused by the abrasive particles impacting the work surface at high speed. The figure below shows a schematic diagram of the working of this process.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/abrasive-jet-machining-jhy1v7vW.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"588\" height=\"216\" /></p>\r\n<p><strong>Applications of Abrasive Jet Machining (AJM):</strong>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li data-listid=\"1\" data-aria-posinset=\"1\" data-aria-level=\"1\">Removing flash and parting lines from injection&nbsp;molded&nbsp;parts.&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li data-listid=\"1\" data-aria-posinset=\"2\" data-aria-level=\"1\">Deburring and polishing plastic, nylon and teflon components.&nbsp;&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li data-listid=\"1\" data-aria-posinset=\"3\" data-aria-level=\"1\">Cleaning metallic mold cavities which otherwise may be inaccessible.&nbsp;&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li data-listid=\"1\" data-aria-posinset=\"4\" data-aria-level=\"1\">Cutting thin sectioned fragile components made of glass, refractories, ceramics, mica etc.&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li data-listid=\"1\" data-aria-posinset=\"5\" data-aria-level=\"1\">Producing high quality surfaces.&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li data-listid=\"1\" data-aria-posinset=\"6\" data-aria-level=\"1\">Removing glue and paint from paintings and leather objects.&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li data-listid=\"1\" data-aria-posinset=\"7\" data-aria-level=\"1\">Reproducing designs on a glass surface with the help of masks made of rubber, copper etc.&nbsp;&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li data-listid=\"1\" data-aria-posinset=\"8\" data-aria-level=\"1\">Frosting interior surfaces of glass tubes.&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li data-listid=\"1\" data-aria-posinset=\"9\" data-aria-level=\"1\">Etching markings of glass tubes.&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Advantages and disadvantages of Abrasive Jet Machining (AJM):</strong>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The advantage of this process is its ability to machine brittle materials with thin sections, especially in areas which are inaccessible by ordinary methods. Absence of tool work contact and metal removal at microscopic level leads&nbsp;to very little or no heat generation, resulting in insignificant surface damage. The process is characterized by low capital investment and low power consumption.&nbsp;However, the application of AJM is restricted to brittle materials due to lower rates of metal removal attainable in cases of ductile materials. Sometimes, the part to be machined needs to undergo an additional operation of cleaning as there is a possibility of the abrasive grains sticking to the surface. The machining accuracy is poor and the nozzle wear rate is high. Also, the process tends to pollute the environment.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Variables in Abrasive Jet Machining (AJM):</strong>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>These are the parameters which influence&nbsp;the&nbsp;material removal rate and accuracy of machining. The following are such parameters:&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li data-listid=\"2\" data-aria-posinset=\"1\" data-aria-level=\"1\">Carrier gas&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li data-listid=\"2\" data-aria-posinset=\"2\" data-aria-level=\"1\">Type of abrasive&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li data-listid=\"2\" data-aria-posinset=\"3\" data-aria-level=\"1\">Size of&nbsp;abrasive&nbsp;grain&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li data-listid=\"2\" data-aria-posinset=\"4\" data-aria-level=\"1\">Velocity of abrasive jet&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li data-listid=\"2\" data-aria-posinset=\"5\" data-aria-level=\"1\">Mean number of abrasive particles per unit volume of the carrier gas&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li data-listid=\"2\" data-aria-posinset=\"6\" data-aria-level=\"1\">Work material&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li data-listid=\"2\" data-aria-posinset=\"7\" data-aria-level=\"1\">Stand off&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li data-listid=\"2\" data-aria-posinset=\"8\" data-aria-level=\"1\">Nozzle design&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li data-listid=\"2\" data-aria-posinset=\"9\" data-aria-level=\"1\">Shape of cut&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><em>Carrier gas:</em>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Carrier gas which&nbsp;is to be used in AJM must not flare excessively when discharged from the nozzle into the atmosphere. Further, the gas should be non-toxic, cheap, easily available and capable to being dried or cleaned without difficulty. The gases that can be used as:&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li data-listid=\"3\" data-aria-posinset=\"1\" data-aria-level=\"1\">Air&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li data-listid=\"3\" data-aria-posinset=\"2\" data-aria-level=\"1\">Carbon dioxide&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li data-listid=\"3\" data-aria-posinset=\"3\" data-aria-level=\"1\">Nitrogen&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Due to low cost and easy availability, air is the preferred gas.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><em>Type of abrasive:</em>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The choice of abrasive depends upon the type of machining operation, e.g. roughing, finishing etc., work material and cost. The abrasive should have a sharp and irregular shape and be fine enough to remain suspended in the carrier gas and should also have&nbsp;excellent&nbsp;flow&nbsp;characteristics. The abrasives used for cutting are&nbsp;aluminum&nbsp;oxide and silicon carbide, whereas sodium bicarbonate, dolomite, glass beads etc., are used for cleaning, etching, deburring and polishing. Re-use of abrasives is not recommended because not only does it reduces the cutting ability, it also contaminates or clogs the orifice of the nozzle.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><em>Grain size:</em>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The material&nbsp;removal&nbsp;rate depends on the size of the abrasive grain. Finer the grains, less irregular they are in shape and hence possess less cutting abilities. Also, finer grains tend to stick together and choke the nozzle orifice. The preferred grain sizes range from 10 to 50&micro;. Coarse grains are recommended for cutting, whereas finer grains are useful in polishing, deburring etc. The effect of grain size on the&nbsp;MRR is&nbsp;shown the figure below.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/wed-tQRbJeSk.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"385\" height=\"272\" /></p>\r\n<p><em>J</em><em>et velocity:</em>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The kinetic energy of the abrasive jet is utilized for metal removal by erosion. For erosion to occur, the jet must impinge the surface with a certain minimum velocity. For the erosion of glass by silicon carbide (grain size&nbsp;25&micro;), the minimum jet velocity has been found to be around 150 m/s. The jet velocity is a function of the nozzle pressure, nozzle design, abrasive grain size and the mean number of abrasives per unit volume of the carrier gas.</p>\r\n<p><em>Mean number of abrasive grains per unit volume of the carrier gas:</em>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>To get an idea about the mean number of abrasive grains per unit volume, we can look at mixing&nbsp;ratio, M. It is defined as:&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>M = (volume flow rate of the abrasive per unit time)/(volume flow rate of the carrier gas per unit time)&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>A larger value of M results in higher rates of metal removal but a&nbsp;large abrasive flow rate has been found to adversely influence jet velocity, and may sometimes even clog the nozzle. Thus for the given conditions, there is an optimum mixing ratio that leads to a maximum metal removal rate.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><em>Work material:</em>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>This process is recommended for the processing of brittle materials like glass, ceramics, refractories etc. Most of the ductile materials have been found to be unmachinable by AJM process. The metal removal rate for brittle materials depend upon the Mohr\'s hardness of the material.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><em>Stand off</em><em>&nbsp;distance (SOD):</em>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Stand off&nbsp;is defined as the distance work surface and the face of the nozzle. The SOD has been found to have considerable effect on the metal removal rate and the accuracy of the process. If the&nbsp;value of SOD is large then the jet flares up, thus decreasing the accuracy of the process. Low MRR at low value of SOD is mainly due to decrease in pressure of jet with a decreasing distance between nozzle face and work surface. The drop in MRR at high value of SOD is due to decrease in the jet velocity with an increase in the distance.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Metal Removal Rate in AJM:</strong>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The MRR in AJM is obtained by the relation,&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=Q%3DK_%7Bd%7DNd%5E%7B3%7Dv%5E%7B3%2F2%7D(%5Cfrac%7B%5Crho_%7B%20a%7D%7D%7B12%20%5Csigma_%7By%7D%7D)%5E%7B3%2F4%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>Where Q = metal removal rate</p>\r\n<p>N = number of abrasive particles taking cut at a time</p>\r\n<p>d = size of abrasive particle</p>\r\n<p>v = velocity of sound</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Crho_%7Ba%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;= density of abrasive material</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Csigma_%7By%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;= yield stress of material&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>',0,'',260,5,2,9,'gate mechanical short notes, gate mechanical, gate, gate mechanical engineering, Abrasive Jet Machining, gate mechanical notes on abrasive jet machining, mechanical engineering notes','GATE Mechanical Engineering notes on Manufacturing Engineering - Abrasive Jet Machining. A rather less talked about topic in Manufacturing Engineering for GATE Mechanical Engineering exam. ',1),(607,'2017-05-03 15:08:30','2017-07-09 18:23:12','Future scope for Mechanical Engineering','article','future-scope-for-mechanical-engineering','','<p>Hi, I am preparing for GATE 2018 for Mechanical Engineering. I aspire to do masters in mechanical engineering. I want to ask about the future scope of Masters in Mechanical Management? In general, what are the areas in which there is a scope of a better future in mechanical engineering after a masters degree?&nbsp;</p>',0,'',210,5,256,28,'','',1),(608,'2017-05-04 06:34:48','2017-07-10 09:30:16','Future Career options for Mechanical Engineers','article','future-career-options-for-mechanical-engineers','/uploads/images/future-career-options-for-mechanical-engineers-CiqMLY3z.jpg','<p>What are the career options for Mechanical Engineers in future? This is a question that many a students, aspiring engineers ask their teachers, mentors on a regular basis. In this article, I have tried to answer this query for all mechanical engineers that will help them look at and plan a career&nbsp;from a perspective of where the world around us will be in the next 20 years.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Mechanical engineering will evolve as a global profession over the next 20 years as it will playa key role in&nbsp;development&nbsp;of engineering solutions that support a cleaner, healthier, safer and sustainable world.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" src=\"../../uploads/images/career-options-for-mechanical-engineers-geekvis-2-OcUYdYG7.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"229\" height=\"160\" /></p>\r\n<p>Mechanical engineers play a critical role in technologies that serve people. Their skills will be needed to&nbsp;design&nbsp;new energy sources, make existing energy sources cleaner and improve existing energy sources. The major industries which will witness tremendous input from mechanical engineers ae environmental engineering, farming and food production, housing, transportation, safety, healthcare and water resources.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>As nations like India and China grow, everyone is at the cusp of some wonderful opportunities. This is going to bring in more than a billion people into the middle class which will make them utilize or rather exploit the world\'s resources. A major challenge for mechanical engineers&nbsp;will be to help these countries build a sustainable future.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>To make sure that the engineers are able to handle the emergent complex system, significant public support will be needed and mechanical engineers will have to be plugged into the political system and work as policy makers.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>An inherent quality, that has been a part of the character of great mechanical engineers throughout history to the next generation, is the joy of discovery. This will be a major reason of attracting young people into the profession of mechanical engineering, as it will allow the practitioners experience the joy of turning tough problems into breakthrough solutions serving all people.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Due to an accelerating change in the development of new scientific and technological breakthroughs, the current practices of universities, colleges and professional societies are not adequate to prepare globally competent engineers and&nbsp;engineering&nbsp;leaders.&nbsp;These institutions should make new learning strategies to engage new learners to learn basic technical skills and acquire higher order thinking skills for innovation and problem solving.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Globally there is a huge market for mechanical engineering that serves the poorest of us. In the next 20 years, almost 2 billion additional people are expected to populate the earth with 95% of them in developing or underdeveloped countries. This large and growing population will require access to food and clean water, sanitation, energy, education, healthcare and transportation.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Mechanical engineers of today and tomorrow must be able to conceive and direct projects of enormous complexity that require a highly integrative view of engineering systems. Employers will be demanding engineers adept at integrating different disciplines,&nbsp;addressing&nbsp;increasingly complex customer and stakeholder requirements. Simulations and computer aided design will play a major role in this area.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Nonotechnology&nbsp;is poised for even greater success over the next 20 years. It can be used to create more efficient solar cells that produce electricity cheaper than coal, to deliver drugs to a precise part of the body and to build terabyte data chips the size of postage stamps. Emerging technologies like CAD, materials, robotics, nanotechnology will likely come together to transform how engineers work.</p>\r\n<p><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" src=\"../../uploads/images/career-options-for-mechanical-engineers-geekvis-1-Wz9EAxgD.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"308\" height=\"173\" />&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>So, the mechanical engineers must develop skills that will be relevant in the coming future and think on a global scale. The aim should be to develop core competencies in mechanical engineering and at the same time seek interdisciplinary technical skills for complex problem solving.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>',0,'',380,5,2,28,'career options for mechanical engineers, mechanical engineering, mechanical, engineers, mechanical engineers, future career options for mechanical engineers, nanotechnology, CAD, robotics','Mechanical Engineering will be a global profession. In this article, we discuss career options for mechanical engineers in the coming 20 years globally. ',1),(609,'2017-05-11 09:22:46','2017-07-10 11:57:31','GATE Mechanical Questions - Stress and Strains','article','stress-and-strains-gate-me-questions','/uploads/images/gate-mechanical-questions-stress-and-strains-0q6xmSGH.jpg','<p>Try out these practice questions on Simple stress and strains.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<div class=\"csvQues\">\r\n<h5 class=\"qno\">Question 1</h5>\r\n<p>The strain energy stored in a body due to external loading, within elastic limit is known as</p>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> A </span>Malleability</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> B </span>Ductility</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> C </span>Toughness</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> D </span>Resilience</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<hr />\r\n<div class=\"csvQues\">\r\n<h5 class=\"qno\">Question 2</h5>\r\n<p>Proof resilience in a member is stored strain energy</p>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> A </span>per unit volume</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> B </span>in whole volume</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> C </span>per unit area</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> D </span>per unit length</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<hr />\r\n<div class=\"csvQues\">\r\n<h5 class=\"qno\">Question 3</h5>\r\n<p>Resilience of a material is considered when it is subjected to</p>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> A </span>Frequent heat treatment</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> B </span>Fatigue</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> C </span>Creep</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> D </span>Shock loading</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<hr />\r\n<div class=\"csvQues\">\r\n<h5 class=\"qno\">Question 4</h5>\r\n<p>The ability of a tool material to resist shock or impact forces is known as</p>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> A </span>wear resistance</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> B </span>toughness</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> C </span>red hardness</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> D </span>machinability</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<hr />\r\n<div class=\"csvQues\">\r\n<h5 class=\"qno\">Question 5</h5>\r\n<p>Which of the following is a dimensionless quantity?</p>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> A </span>Shear stress</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> B </span>Bulk modulus</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> C </span>Poisson\'s ratio</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> D </span>Shear modulus</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<hr />\r\n<div class=\"csvQues\">\r\n<h5 class=\"qno\">Question 6</h5>\r\n<p>Percentage elongation during tensile test is indicative of</p>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> A </span>creep</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> B </span>malleability</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> C </span>ductility</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> D </span>elasticity in the metal</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<hr />\r\n<div class=\"csvQues\">\r\n<h5 class=\"qno\">Question 7</h5>\r\n<p>On the application of a given load, the length of a wire is stated to increase by 1mm. If the same force is now applied to a wire of same material but of the length and radius twice the first, the extension produced would be</p>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> A </span>0.25 mm</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> B </span>0.5 mm</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> C </span>2.0 mm</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> D </span>4.0 mm</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<hr />\r\n<div class=\"csvQues\">\r\n<h5 class=\"qno\">Question 8</h5>\r\n<p>Consider a bar of length \'l\' and tapering uniformly from diameter&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=d_%7B2%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;to&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=d_%7B1%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;and subjected to axial load W. The extension of the bar will be</p>\r\n<p>(1)&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=4Wl%2F%20%5Cpi%20d_%7B1%7D%20d_%7B2%7D%20E\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>(2)&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=4WEl%2F%20%5Cpi%20d_%7B1%7D%20d_%7B2%7D%20\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>(3)&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cpi%20WEl%2F%204%20d_%7B1%7D%20d_%7B2%7D%20E\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>(4)&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cpi%20Wl%2F%20%5C4%20d_%7B1%7D%20d_%7B2%7D%20E\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> A </span>1</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> B </span>2</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> C </span>3</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> D </span>4</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<hr />\r\n<div class=\"csvQues\">\r\n<h5 class=\"qno\">Question 9</h5>\r\n<p>Poisson\'s ratio is used in&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> A </span>one dimensional body</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> B </span>two dimensional body</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> C </span>three dimensional body</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> D </span>both two and three dimensional body</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<hr />\r\n<div class=\"csvQues\">\r\n<h5 class=\"qno\">Question 10</h5>\r\n<p>Hooke\'s law holds good upto</p>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> A </span>yield point</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> B </span>limit of proportionality</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> C </span>breaking point</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> D </span>elastic limit</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<hr />\r\n<div class=\"csvQues\">\r\n<h5 class=\"qno\">Question 11</h5>\r\n<p>The percentage reduction in area in case of CI when it is subjected to tensile test is of the order of</p>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> A </span>0%</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> B </span>10%</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> C </span>20%</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> D </span>25%</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<hr />\r\n<div class=\"csvQues\">\r\n<h5 class=\"qno\">Question 12</h5>\r\n<p>When a wire is stretched to double in length, the longitudinal strain produced in it is</p>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> A </span>0.5</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> B </span>1.0</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> C </span>1.5</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> D </span>2.0</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<hr />\r\n<div class=\"csvQues\">\r\n<h5 class=\"qno\">Question 13</h5>\r\n<p>If equal and opposite forces applied to a body tend to elongate it, the stress so produced is called&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> A </span>internal resistance</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> B </span>tensile stress</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> C </span>transverse stress</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> D </span>compressive stress</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<hr />\r\n<div class=\"csvQues\">\r\n<h5 class=\"qno\">Question 14</h5>\r\n<p>The strain energy stores in a body due to direct stress \'<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Csigma\" alt=\"\" />\' is:</p>\r\n<p>(1)&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cfrac%7B%5Csigma%7D%7B2E%7D%20%5Ctimes%20vol\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>(2)&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cfrac%7B%5Csigma%5E%7B2%7D%7D%7BE%7D%5Ctimes%20vol\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>(3)&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cfrac%7B%5Csigma%5E%7B2%7D%7D%7B2E%7D%5Ctimes%20vol\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>(4)&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cfrac%7B2%20%5Csigma%7D%7BE%7D%5Ctimes%20vol\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> A </span>1</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> B </span>2</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> C </span>3</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> D </span>4</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<hr />\r\n<div class=\"csvQues\">\r\n<h5 class=\"qno\">Question 15</h5>\r\n<p>Modulus of rigidity is the ratio of:</p>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> A </span>Axial stress to lateral strain</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> B </span>Linear stress to longitudinal strain</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> C </span>Shear stress to shear strain</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> D </span>Hydrostatic stress to volumetric strain</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<hr />\r\n<div class=\"csvQues\">\r\n<h5 class=\"qno\">Question 16</h5>\r\n<p>The elastic constants E, G and K are related by the expression</p>\r\n<p>(1)&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=E%3D%5Cfrac%7BGK%7D%7BK%2BG%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>(2)&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=E%3D%5Cfrac%7BGK%7D%7B2K%2BG%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>(3)&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=E%3D%5Cfrac%7B3GK%7D%7BK%2B2G%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>(4)&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=E%3D%5Cfrac%7B9GK%7D%7B3K%2BG%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> A </span>1</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> B </span>2</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> C </span>3</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> D </span>4</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<hr />\r\n<div class=\"csvQues\">\r\n<h5 class=\"qno\">Question 17</h5>\r\n<p>A cylindrical rod of length \'l\' and diameter \'d\' is rigidly fixed at its upper end and hangs vertically. The elongation produced in rod due to its self weight \'W\' is</p>\r\n<p>(1)&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cfrac%7BWl%7D%7BAE%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>(2)&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cfrac%7BWl%7D%7B2AE%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>(3)&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cfrac%7B2Wl%7D%7BAE%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>(4)&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cfrac%7B3Wl%7D%7B2AE%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> A </span>1</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> B </span>2</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> C </span>3</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> D </span>4</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<hr />\r\n<div class=\"csvQues\">\r\n<h5 class=\"qno\">Question 18</h5>\r\n<p>True stress represents the ratio of&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> A </span>average load and average area</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> B </span>average load and maximum area</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> C </span>maximum load and maximum area</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> D </span>instantaneous load and the instantaneous area</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<hr />\r\n<div class=\"csvQues\">\r\n<h5 class=\"qno\">Question 19</h5>\r\n<p>Which material has the highest value of Poisson\'s ratio?</p>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> A </span>Rubber</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> B </span>Copper</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> C </span>Steel</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> D </span>Concrete</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<hr />\r\n<div class=\"csvQues\">\r\n<h5 class=\"qno\">Question 20</h5>\r\n<p>The deformation per unit length in the direction of the force is known as</p>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> A </span>linear stress</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> B </span>shear stress</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> C </span>linear strain</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> D </span>lateral strain</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<hr />\r\n<div class=\"csvQues\">\r\n<h5 class=\"qno\">Question 21</h5>\r\n<p>In a tensile test of a specimen, the ratio of maximum load to the original cross sectional area of the test piece is called</p>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> A </span>ultimate stress</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> B </span>sea stress</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> C </span>breaking stress</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> D </span>yield stress</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<hr />\r\n<div class=\"csvQues\">\r\n<h5 class=\"qno\">Question 22</h5>\r\n<p>A steel bar is fixed at both ends. If the bar is heated, it will develop</p>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> A </span>compressive stress</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> B </span>tensile stress</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> C </span>bending stress</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> D </span>none of these</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<hr />\r\n<div class=\"csvQues\">\r\n<h5 class=\"qno\">Question 23</h5>\r\n<p>The value of Poisson\'s ratio is always less than</p>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> A </span>1</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> B </span>0.2</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> C </span>0.4</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> D </span>0.5</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<hr />\r\n<div class=\"csvQues\">\r\n<h5 class=\"qno\">Question 24</h5>\r\n<p>Stress due to change in temperature developed in a bar depends upon</p>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> A </span>coefficient of thermal expansion</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> B </span>thermal conductivity</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> C </span>density</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> D </span>Poisson\'s ratio</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<hr />\r\n<div class=\"csvQues\">\r\n<h5 class=\"qno\">Question 25</h5>\r\n<p>For a material with Poisson\'s ratio 0.25, the ratio of modulus of rigidity to modulus of elasticity will be</p>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> A </span>0.4</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> B </span>1.2</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> C </span>2.0</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> D </span>3.6</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<hr />\r\n<div class=\"csvQues\">\r\n<h5 class=\"qno\">Question 26</h5>\r\n<p>If equal and opposite forces applied to a body tend to elongate it, then the stress produced is</p>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> A </span>tensile stress</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> B </span>bending stress</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> C </span>compressive stress</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> D </span>shear stress</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<hr />\r\n<div class=\"csvQues\">\r\n<h5 class=\"qno\">Question 27</h5>\r\n<p>Poisson\'s ratio is the ratio of</p>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> A </span>shear stress to shear strain</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> B </span>longitudinal strain to lateral strain</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> C </span>lateral strain to longitudinal strain</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> D </span>axial stress to axial strain</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<hr />\r\n<div class=\"csvQues\">\r\n<h5 class=\"qno\">Question 28</h5>\r\n<p>In a composite bar the resultant strain produced will be</p>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> A </span>same as the strain produced in each bar</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> B </span>sum of the strain produced by the individual bars</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> C </span>same as the stress produced in each bar</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> D </span>difference of strain produced by individual bars</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<hr />\r\n<div class=\"csvQues\">\r\n<h5 class=\"qno\">Question 29</h5>\r\n<p>Volumetric starin of a rectangular body subjected to an axial force in terms of linear strain \'e\' and Poisson\'s ratio&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cmu\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;is equal to</p>\r\n<p>(1)&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=e(1%2B%5Cmu)\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>(2)&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=e(1-2%5Cmu)\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>(3)&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=e(1-3%5Cmu)\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>(4)&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=e(1-%5Cmu)\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> A </span>1</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> B </span>2</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> C </span>3</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> D </span>4</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<hr />\r\n<div class=\"csvQues\">\r\n<h5 class=\"qno\">Question 30</h5>\r\n<p>The diameter of core of a circular section is given by</p>\r\n<p>(1)&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cfrac%7Bd%7D%7B%5Csqrt%7B%5Cpi%7D%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>(2)&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cfrac%7Bd%7D%7B2%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>(3)&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cfrac%7Bd%7D%7B3%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>(4)&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cfrac%7Bd%7D%7B4%7D\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> A </span>1</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> B </span>2</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> C </span>3</div>\r\n<div class=\"qop\"><span class=\"qal\"> D </span>4</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<hr />',0,'',366,5,2,6,'gate mechanical practice questions, free practice questions for gate, Practice, Objective, Questions, GATE, Exam','Free sample practice questions for GATE on simple stress and strains from the subject of strength of materials.',1),(610,'2017-05-12 05:43:51','2017-07-08 02:41:32','GATE Practice Questions-Matrices','article','gate-practice-questions-matrices','/uploads/images/gate-practice-questions-matrices-CPPGKWfK.png','<h1>GATE Practice Questions-Matrices</h1>\r\n<p>Matrices and Linear Algebra is an important topic from Engineering mathematics in GATE exam. Try solving these challenging questions to test your competency level and understanding of the topic of Matrices.</p>\r\n<p>Q1) If A =&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cbegin%7Bbmatrix%7D%200%20%26%201%5C%5C%20%20-1%20%26%200%20%5Cend%7Bbmatrix%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;find out the values of&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Calpha\" alt=\"\" />,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cbeta\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;such that&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=(%5Calpha%20I%20%2B%20%5Cbeta%20A)%5E%7B2%7D%3DA%5E%7B2%7D\" alt=\"\" />.</p>\r\n<p>Q2)&nbsp;<span class=\"TextRun SCX89505555\" lang=\"EN-US\" xml:lang=\"EN-US\"><span class=\"NormalTextRun SCX89505555\">Show that if</span></span><span class=\"TextRun SCX89505555\" lang=\"EN-US\" xml:lang=\"EN-US\"><span class=\"NormalTextRun SCX89505555\"> A is a Hermitian (Skew-Hermitian) matrix, then </span></span><span class=\"TextRun SCX89505555\" lang=\"EN-US\" xml:lang=\"EN-US\"><span class=\"SpellingError SCX89505555\">iA</span></span><span class=\"TextRun SCX89505555\" lang=\"EN-US\" xml:lang=\"EN-US\"><span class=\"NormalTextRun SCX89505555\"> is a Skew-Hermitian (Hermitian) matrix.</span></span></p>\r\n<p>Q3) Determine the values of&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Calpha\" alt=\"\" />,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cbeta\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;and&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cgamma\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;when A =&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cbegin%7Bbmatrix%7D%200%20%26%202%5Cbeta%20%26%20%5Cgamma%5C%5C%20%20%5Calpha%20%26%20%5Cbeta%20%26%20-%20%5Cgamma%20%5C%5C%20%5Calpha%20%26%20-%20%5Cbeta%20%26%20%5Cgamma%5C%5C%20%5Cend%7Bbmatrix%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;is orthogonal.</p>\r\n<p>Q4) If A is real skew-symmetric matrix such that&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=A%5E%7B2%7D%2BI%3DO\" alt=\"\" />, show that A is orthogonal and is of even order.</p>\r\n<p>Q5) Find the inverse of the matrix&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=S%3D%5Cbegin%7Bbmatrix%7D%200%20%26%201%20%26%201%5C%5C%20%201%20%26%200%20%26%201%5C%5C%20%201%20%26%201%20%26%200%20%5Cend%7Bbmatrix%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;and show that the transform of the matrix&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=A%3D%5Cbegin%7Bbmatrix%7D%20b%2Bc%20%26%20c%2Ba%20%26%20b-c%5C%5C%20%20c-b%20%26%20c%2Bb%20%26%20a-b%5C%5C%20%20b-c%20%26%20a-c%20%26%20a%2Bb%20%5Cend%7Bbmatrix%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;by S, i.e.&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=SAS%5E%7B-1%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;is a diagonal matrix.</p>\r\n<p>Q6) If&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=f(x)%3D%5Cbegin%7Bvmatrix%7D%20x%2Bc_%7B1%7D%20%26%20x%2Ba%20%26%20x%2Ba%5C%5C%20%20x%2Bb%20%26%20x%2Bc_%7B2%7D%20%26x%2Ba%20%5C%5C%20%20x%2Bb%20%26%20x%2Bb%20%26%20x%2Bc_%7B3%7D%20%5Cend%7Bvmatrix%7D\" alt=\"\" />, then show that f(x) is a linear in x.</p>\r\n<p>Q7) Find the value of&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cbegin%7Bvmatrix%7D%20l_%7B1%7D%20%26%20m_%7B1%7D%20%26%20n_%7B1%7D%5C%5C%20%20l_%7B2%7D%20%26%20m_%7B2%7D%20%26%20n_%7B2%7D%20%5C%5C%20%20l_%7B3%7D%20%26%20m_%7B3%7D%20%26%20n_%7B3%7D%20%5Cend%7Bvmatrix%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;where&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=l_%7B1%7D%5E%7B2%7D%2Bm_%7B1%7D%5E%7B2%7D%2Bn_%7B1%7D%5E%7B2%7D%3D1\" alt=\"\" />, etc. and&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=l_%7B1%7Dl_%7B2%7D%2Bm_%7B1%7Dm_%7B2%7D%2Bn_%7B1%7Dn_%7B2%7D%3D0\" alt=\"\" />, etc.</p>\r\n<p>In the next round of questions we will share the questions on Rank of a matrix, System of equations and Eigen vectors.&nbsp;</p>',0,'',301,5,223,20,'gate mechanical practice questions, free practice questions for gate, Practice, Objective, Questions, GATE, Exam, gate practice questions on matrices','Test your skill level with these free sample practice questions for GATE on matrices from the subject of Engineering Mathematics.',1),(613,'2017-05-12 14:27:14','2017-07-10 06:14:23','GATE Practice Questions-Differential Equations','article','gate-practice-questions-differential-equations','/uploads/images/gate-practice-questions-differential-equations-6NT59wmn.jpg','<p>After matrices and linear algebra, differential equations is probably the most extensively asked topic in GATE from the subject of Engineering Mathematics. Try and solve the questions from ordinary differential equations below to test your preparedness. All the best!</p>\r\n<p>1) Consider two solutions&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=x(t)%3Dx_%7B1%7D(t)\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;and&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=x(t)%3Dx_%7B2%7D(t)\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;of the differential equation&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cfrac%7Bd%5E%7B2%7Dx(t)%7D%7Bdt%5E%7B2%7D%7D%2Bx(t)%3D0%2C%20t%3E0\" alt=\"\" />, such that&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=x_%7B1%7D(0)%3D1\" alt=\"\" />,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=dx_%7B1%7D(t)%2Fdt%20%7C_%7Bt%3D0%7D%3D0\" alt=\"\" />,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=x_%7B2%7D(0)%3D0\" alt=\"\" />,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=dx_%7B2%7D(t)%2Fdt%20%7C_%7Bt%3D0%7D%3D1\" alt=\"\" />. The Wronskian&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=W(t)%3D%5Cbegin%7Bvmatrix%7D%20x_%7B1%7D(t)%20%26%20x_%7B2%7D(t)%5C%5C%20%20%5Cfrac%7Bdx_%7B1%7D(t)%7D%7Bdt%7D%20%26%20%5Cfrac%7Bdx_%7B2%7D(t)%7D%7Bdt%7D%20%5C%5C%20%20%5Cend%7Bvmatrix%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;at&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=t%3D-%5Cfrac%7B%5Cpi%7D%7B2%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;is _________.</p>\r\n<p>2) Water is flowing at a steady rate through a homogeneous and saturated horizontal soil strip of 10 m length. The strip is being subjected to a constant water head (H) of 5m at the beginning and 1 m at the end. If the governing equation of flow in the soil strip is&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cfrac%7Bd%5E%7B2%7DH%7D%7Bdx%5E%7B2%7D%7D%3D0\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;(where x is the distance along the soild strip), the value of H (in m) at the middle of the strip is __________.</p>\r\n<p>3) A steam pipe of diameter D m is protected with an h-m thik covering for which the conductivity of the material is K. Determine the heat loss per hour &nbsp;through an L m long pipe, if the surface of the pipe is at temperature&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=T_%7Bp%7D%5E%7Bo%7DK\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;and the outer surface of the covering is at&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=T_%7Bc%7D%5E%7Bo%7DK\" alt=\"\" />. Use concept of differential equations to derive a relation for heat flow and temperature at any point.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>4) The solution of the differential equation&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cfrac%7Bdy%7D%7Bdx%7D%2By%5E%7B2%7D%3D0\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;is&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: lower-alpha;\">\r\n<li><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=y%3D%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7Bx%2Bc%7D\" alt=\"\" /></li>\r\n<li><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=y%3D%5Cfrac%7B-x%5E%7B2%7D%7D%7B3%7D%2Bc\" alt=\"\" /></li>\r\n<li><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=ce%5E%7Bx%7D\" alt=\"\" /></li>\r\n<li>unsolvable as equation is non linear</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>5) If&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=x%5E%7B2%7D%5Cfrac%7Bdy%7D%7Bdx%7D%2B2xy%3D%5Cfrac%7B2%20ln(x)%7D%7Bx%7D\" alt=\"\" />, and y(1)=0, then what is the value of y(e)?</p>\r\n<p>6) The solution of dy/dx=y<sup>2</sup> with initial value y(0)=1 is bounded in the interval</p>\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: lower-alpha;\">\r\n<li><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=-%5Cinfty%20%5Cleq%20x%20%5Cleq%20%5Cinfty\" alt=\"\" /></li>\r\n<li><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=-%5Cinfty%20%5Cleq%20x%20%5Cleq%201\" alt=\"\" /></li>\r\n<li>x&lt;1, x&gt;1</li>\r\n<li><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=-2%20%5Cleq%20x%20%5Cleq%202\" alt=\"\" /></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>7) A spherical naphthalene ball exposed to the atmosphere loses volume at a rate proportional to its instantaneous surface area due to evaporation. If the initial diameter of the ball is 2 cm and the diameter reduces to 1 cm after 3 months, the ball completely evaporates in _______ months.</p>\r\n<p>8) The transformation to linear form by substituting&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=v%3Dy%5E%7B1-n%7D\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;of the equation&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cfrac%7Bdy%7D%7Bdt%7D%2Bp(t)y%3Dq(t)y%5E%7Bn%7D\" alt=\"\" />; n&gt;0 will be</p>\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: lower-alpha;\">\r\n<li><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cfrac%7Bdv%7D%7Bdt%7D%2B(1-n)pv%3D(1-n)q\" alt=\"\" /></li>\r\n<li><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cfrac%7Bdv%7D%7Bdt%7D%2B(1-n)pv%3D(1%2Bn)q\" alt=\"\" /></li>\r\n<li><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cfrac%7Bdv%7D%7Bdt%7D%2B(1%2Bn)pv%3D(1-n)q\" alt=\"\" /></li>\r\n<li><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cfrac%7Bdv%7D%7Bdt%7D%2B(1%2Bn)pv%3D(1%2Bn)q\" alt=\"\" /></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>9) Solution of the differential equation&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=3y%20%5Cfrac%7Bdy%7D%7Bdx%7D%2B2x%3D0\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;represents a family of&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: lower-alpha;\">\r\n<li>ellipses</li>\r\n<li>circles</li>\r\n<li>parabolas</li>\r\n<li>hyperbolas</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>10) The solution of&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%5Cfrac%7Bd%5E%7B2%7Dy%7D%7Bdx%5E%7B2%7D%7D%2B2%5Cfrac%7Bdy%7D%7Bdx%7D%2B17y%3D0%3B%20y(0)%3D1\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=%3B%20%5Cfrac%7Bdy%7D%7Bdx%7D(%5Cfrac%7B%5Cpi%7D%7B4%7D)%3D0\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;in the range&nbsp;<img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=0%3Cx%3C%5Cpi%2F4\" alt=\"\" />&nbsp;is given by</p>\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: lower-alpha;\">\r\n<li><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=e%5E%7B-x%7D(cos4x%2B%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B4%7Dsin%204x)\" alt=\"\" /></li>\r\n<li><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=e%5E%7Bx%7D(cos4x-%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B4%7Dsin%204x)\" alt=\"\" /></li>\r\n<li><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=e%5E%7B-4x%7D(cosx-%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B4%7Dsin%20x)\" alt=\"\" /></li>\r\n<li><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=a,s,000000|bg,s,FFFFFF00&amp;chl=e%5E%7B-4x%7D(cos4x-%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B4%7Dsin%204x)\" alt=\"\" /></li>\r\n</ol>',0,'',284,5,2,22,'gate mechanical practice questions, free practice questions for gate, Practice, Objective, Questions, GATE, Exam, gate practice questions on differential equations','Test your skill level with these free sample practice questions for GATE on ordinary differential equations from the subject of Engineering Mathematics.',1),(617,'2017-05-14 06:08:21','2017-07-10 01:50:14','GATE Practice Questions-Bending stresses in beams','article','gate-practice-questions-bending-stresses-in-beams','/uploads/images/gate-practice-questions-bending-stresses-in-beams-6vq6VptA.jpg','<p>Bending stresses in beams is an important topic from the subject of Strength of Materials in GATE exam. Try out these basic questions on the topic of Bending stresses in beams to check your level of understanding.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Q1)&nbsp;</strong>A flitched timber beam made up of steel and timber has a section as shown in the figure. Determine the resistance of the beam. Take&nbsp;&sigma;<sub>s</sub>=100 MPa,&nbsp;&sigma;<sub>w</sub>=5 MPa.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/gate-bending-stress-q1-jeLrjet4.PNG\" alt=\"\" width=\"179\" height=\"117\" /></p>\r\n<p><strong>Q2)&nbsp;</strong>A rectangular beam of cross section (300x200) mm<sup>2</sup> is simply supported in a span of 5 m. What uniformly distributed loads/metre the beam may carry in its positions (i) when the height is 300 mm and (ii) when the height is 200 mm is the bending stress is not going to exceed 130 MPa.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Q3)&nbsp;</strong>A beam of CI having section 50 mm external diameter and 25 mm internal diameter is supported at two points 4 m apart. The beam carries a concentrated load of 100 N at its centre. Find the maximum bending stress induced in the beam.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Q4)&nbsp;</strong>A short hollow column having 200 mm OD and 120 mm ID is subjected to vertical compressive load acting at an eccentricity of 60 mm from the axis of the column. Find the greatest allowable load if the permissible stresses are 80 MPa in compression and 20 MPa in tension.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/e-vc-30LVtsxQ.PNG\" alt=\"\" width=\"138\" height=\"122\" /></p>\r\n<p><strong>Q5)&nbsp;</strong>A short column of 20 cm OD and 15 cm ID is subjected to a load. The stress measurements indicate that the stress varies from 150 MPa compressive at one end and 25 MPa tensile on the other end. Estimate the load and distance of the line of action from the axis of the column?</p>\r\n<p><strong>Q6)&nbsp;</strong>A long rod of a uniform rectangular section and thickness \'t\', originally straight is bent into the form of a circular arc and the displacement d of the midpoint of a length L, is measured by the means of a dial gauge. If d is regarded as small as compared to L, show that the longitudinal strain (&epsilon;) is given by&nbsp;&epsilon;=(4td)/L<sup>2</sup>.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/ecd-k6PgYfBF.PNG\" alt=\"\" width=\"238\" height=\"106\" /></p>\r\n<p><strong>Q7)&nbsp;</strong>A CI pipe of wall thickness 10 mm and OD 120 mm carries water and is supported at a distance of 9 m. Calculate the value of maximum bending stress and its nature when the water is running full. Take the density of CI as 7 g/cc.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Q8)&nbsp;</strong>What is the reaction at support B of the structure,</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"../../uploads/images/egr-Tv035i7w.PNG\" alt=\"\" width=\"283\" height=\"151\" /></p>\r\n<p><strong>Q9)&nbsp;</strong>A cantilever tube of length 120 mm is subjected to an axial tension, P=9 kN, a torsional moment T=72 Nm and a bending load F=1.75 kN at the free end. The material is aluminium alloy with a yield strength of 276 MPa. Find the thickness of the tube limiting the OD to 50 mm so as to ensure a FOS of 4.&nbsp;</p>',0,'',230,5,2,6,'gate mechanical practice questions, free practice questions for gate, Practice, Objective, Questions, GATE, Exam, gate practice questions on strength of materials, gate sample questions on bending stresses in beams','Test your basic understanding with these free sample practice questions for GATE on bending stresses from the subject of Strength of Materials.',1),(618,'2017-05-15 06:20:30','2017-07-10 12:02:30','GATE Practice Questions-Strength of Materials','article','gate-practice-questions-strength-of-materials','/uploads/images/gate-practice-questions-strength-of-materials-WGTpaOQt.jpg','<p><strong>Q1)&nbsp;</strong>The maximum allowable compressive stress corresponding to lateral buckling in a discretely laterally supported symmetrical I-beam, does not depend upon</p>\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: lower-alpha;\">\r\n<li>modulus of elasticity</li>\r\n<li>radius of gyration about the minor axis</li>\r\n<li>span/length of the beam</li>\r\n<li>ratio of overall depth to thickness of the flange</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><strong>Q2)&nbsp;</strong>The buckling load in steel is</p>\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: lower-alpha;\">\r\n<li>related to length</li>\r\n<li>directly proportional to the slenderness ratio</li>\r\n<li>inversely proportional to the slenderness ratio</li>\r\n<li>non-linearly to the slenderness ratio</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><strong>Q3)&nbsp;</strong>When two mutually perpendicular principal stresses are unequal but alike, the maximum shear stress is represented by</p>\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: lower-alpha;\">\r\n<li>the diameter of the Mohr circle</li>\r\n<li>half the diameter of the Mohr\'s circle</li>\r\n<li>one-third the diameter of the Mohr\'s circle</li>\r\n<li>one-fourth the diameter of the Mohr\'s circle</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><strong>Q4)&nbsp;</strong>Sets of principal stresses acting any point in a stressed body are given below:</p>\r\n<p>I. {&sigma;,0}&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>II. {&sigma;,&sigma;}</p>\r\n<p>III. {&sigma;,-&sigma;}</p>\r\n<p>IV. {&sigma;,&sigma;/2}</p>\r\n<p>The correct sequence of the ascending order of intensity of the maximum shear stress induced by the above setd will be</p>\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: lower-alpha;\">\r\n<li>I, IV, III, II</li>\r\n<li>II, I, IV, III</li>\r\n<li>I, III, IV, II</li>\r\n<li>II, IV, I, III</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><strong>Q5)&nbsp;</strong>Under torsion, brittle materials generally fail</p>\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: lower-alpha;\">\r\n<li>along a plane perpendicular to its longitudinal axis</li>\r\n<li>in the direction of minimum tension</li>\r\n<li>along surfaces forming a 45<sup>o</sup> angle with the longitudinal axis</li>\r\n<li>not in any specific manner</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><strong>Q6)&nbsp;</strong>Four vertical columns of the same material, height and weight have the same end conditions. The buckling load will be the largest for a column having the cross section of a/an</p>\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: lower-alpha;\">\r\n<li>solid square</li>\r\n<li>thin hollow square</li>\r\n<li>solid circle</li>\r\n<li>I-section</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><strong>Q7)&nbsp;</strong>A gas is stored in a cylindrical tank of inner radius 7 m and wall thickness 50 mm. The gauge pressure of the gas is 2 MPa. The maximum shear stress (in MPa) in the wall is</p>\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: lower-alpha;\">\r\n<li>35</li>\r\n<li>70</li>\r\n<li>140</li>\r\n<li>290</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><strong>Q8)&nbsp;</strong>At a point in a strained material, if two mutually perpendicular tensile stresses of 2000 kg/cm<sup>2</sup> and 1000 kg/cm<sup>2</sup> are acting, then the intensity of tangential stress on a plane inclined at 15<sup>o</sup> to the axis of the minor stresses will be _______ kg/cm<sup>2</sup>.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Q9)&nbsp;</strong>At &nbsp;a point in a steel member, the major principal stress is 200 MPa (tensile) and the minor principal stress is compressive. If the uniaxial tensile yield stress is 250 MPa, then according to the maximum shear stress theory, the magnitude of the minor principal stress (compressive) at which yielding will commence is __________ MPa.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Q10)&nbsp;</strong>If the strain energy absorbed in a cantilever beam in bending under its own weight is K times greater than the strain energy absorbed in an identical simply supported beam in bending under its own weight, then the magnitude of K is ____________.</p>',0,'',269,5,2,6,'gate mechanical practice questions, free practice questions for gate, Practice, Objective, Questions, GATE, Exam, gate practice questions on strength of materials, gate sample questions ','Test your basic understanding with these free sample practice questions for GATE exam for Mechanical Engineering from the subject of Strength of Materials.',1),(619,'2017-05-16 06:00:26','2017-07-10 10:46:28','GATE Practice Questions-First Law of thermodynamics','article','gate-practice-questions-first-law-of-thermodynamics','/uploads/images/gate-practice-questions-first-law-of-thermodynamics-NjBNAOrk.jpg','<p>A good understanding of First Law of Thermodynamics lays the foundation of a strong hold on the entire subject of thermodynamics. Here are 0 thought provoking and challenging questions to attempt from the topic of First Law of Thermodynamics.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Q1)&nbsp;</strong>The internal energy of a certain substance is given by the following equation: u = 3.56pv+84, where u is given in kJ/kg, p is in kPa and v is in m<sup>3</sup>/kg. A system composed of 3 kg of this substance expands from an initial pressure of 500 kPa and a volume of 0.22 m<sup>3</sup> to a final pressure of 100 kPa in a process in which pressure and volume are related by pv<sup>1.2</sup>=constant.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>(a) If the expansion is quasi static, find Q,&nbsp;&Delta;U and W for the process.</p>\r\n<p>(b) In another process, the same system expands according to the same p-v relationship as in part (a), and from the same initial state to the same final state as in part (a), but the heat transfer in this case is 30 kJ. Find the work transfer for this process.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Q2)&nbsp;</strong>A piston&ndash;cylinder device contains 0.15 kg of air initially&nbsp;at 2 MPa and 350&deg;C. The air is first expanded isothermally&nbsp;to 500 kPa, then compressed polytropically with a&nbsp;polytropic exponent of 1.2 to the initial pressure, and finally&nbsp;compressed at the constant pressure to the initial state. Determine&nbsp;the boundary work for each process and the net work of&nbsp;the cycle.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Q3)&nbsp;</strong>A 0.5-m<sup>3</sup> rigid tank contains refrigerant-134a initially&nbsp;at 160 kPa and 40 percent quality. Heat is now transferred to&nbsp;the refrigerant until the pressure reaches 700 kPa. Determine&nbsp;(a) the mass of the refrigerant in the tank and (b) the amount&nbsp;of heat transferred.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Q4)&nbsp;</strong>An insulated tank is divided into two parts by a partition.&nbsp;One part of the tank contains 2.5 kg of compressed liquid&nbsp;water at 60&deg;C and 600 kPa while the other part is evacuated.&nbsp;The partition is now removed, and the water expands to fill the&nbsp;entire tank. Determine the final temperature of the water and&nbsp;the volume of the tank for a final pressure of 10 kPa.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Q5)&nbsp;</strong>An insulated piston&ndash;cylinder device contains 5 L of&nbsp;saturated liquid water at a constant pressure of 175 kPa.&nbsp;Water is stirred by a paddle wheel while a current of 8 A&nbsp;flows for 45 min through a resistor placed in the water.&nbsp;If one-half of the liquid is evaporated during this constantpressure&nbsp;process and the paddle-wheel work amounts to&nbsp;400 kJ, determine the voltage of the source.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Q6)&nbsp;</strong>Two tanks (Tank A and Tank B) are separated by a&nbsp;partition. Initially Tank A contains 2-kg steam at 1 MPa and&nbsp;300&deg;C while Tank B contains 3-kg saturated liquid&ndash;vapor&nbsp;mixture with a vapor mass fraction of 50 percent. Now the&nbsp;partition is removed and the two sides are allowed to mix&nbsp;until the mechanical and thermal equilibrium are established.&nbsp;If the pressure at the final state is 300 kPa, determine (a) the&nbsp;temperature and quality of the steam (if mixture) at the final&nbsp;state and (b) the amount of heat lost from the tanks.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Q7)&nbsp;</strong>A 3-m<sup>3</sup>&nbsp;rigid tank contains hydrogen at 250 kPa and&nbsp;550 K. The gas is now cooled until its temperature drops to&nbsp;350 K. Determine (a) the final pressure in the tank and&nbsp;(b) the amount of heat transfer.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Q8)&nbsp;</strong>A 4-mx5-mx7-m room is heated by the radiator&nbsp;of a steam-heating system. The steam radiator transfers heat&nbsp;at a rate of 10,000 kJ/h, and a 100-W fan is used to distribute&nbsp;the warm air in the room. The rate of heat loss from the room&nbsp;is estimated to be about 5000 kJ/h. If the initial temperature&nbsp;of the room air is 10&deg;C, determine how long it will take for&nbsp;the air temperature to rise to 20&deg;C. Assume constant specific&nbsp;heats at room temperature.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Q9)&nbsp;</strong>A mass of 15 kg of air in a piston&ndash;cylinder device is&nbsp;heated from 25 to 77&deg;C by passing current through a resistance&nbsp;heater inside the cylinder. The pressure inside the cylinder is&nbsp;held constant at 300 kPa during the process, and a heat loss of&nbsp;60 kJ occurs. Determine the electric energy supplied, in kWh.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Q10)&nbsp;</strong>Carbon steel balls (&rho;=7833 kg/m<sup>3</sup>&nbsp;and c<sub>p</sub>=0.465&nbsp;kJ/kg &middot; &deg;C) 8 mm in diameter are annealed by heating them&nbsp;first to 900&deg;C in a furnace, and then allowing them to cool&nbsp;slowly to 100&deg;C in ambient air at 35&deg;C. If 2500 balls are to&nbsp;be annealed per hour, determine the total rate of heat transfer&nbsp;from the balls to the ambient air.</p>',0,'',278,5,2,3,'gate mechanical practice questions, free practice questions for gate, Practice, Objective, Questions, GATE, Exam, gate practice questions on first law of thermodynamics, gate sample questions, first law of thermdynamics','Test your basic understanding with these free sample practice questions for GATE exam for Mechanical Engineering from the subject of Thermodynamics on First Law of Thermodynamics.',1),(620,'2017-05-17 09:07:42','2017-07-08 18:16:39','GATE Practice Questions-Linear Algebra','article','gate-practice-questions-linear-algebra','/uploads/images/gate-practice-questions-linear-algebra-A221Nine.jpg','<p>Linear algebra covers almost 5-6 marks in <a href=\"https://mindvis.in/courses/gate-2018-mechanical-engineering-online-course\" target=\"_blank\">GATE </a>exam which makes it very important from a scoring perspective. Try out these questions on solutions on linear equations and eigen values and eigen vectors and check how much you understand the concepts involved.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Q1)&nbsp;</strong>The system of linear equations</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://chart.googleapis.com/chart?cht=tx&amp;chf=